<STRONG><H2><CENTER>NMFS HABITAT HAPPENINGS...</CENTER></H2></STRONG><P>
<P>


<STRONG><CENTER>December, 1995</CENTER></STRONG><P>

<P>

<P><B>Restoration of Coral Reef Deemed a Success</B><P>
<P>

Two vessels, the<I>M/V Alec Owen Maitland</I>, a 155-foot oil field supply vessel and the <I>M/VElpis</I>, a 470-foot cargo freighter, ran aground on a coral reef system within the Florida Keys NationalMarine Sanctuary in October and November 1989. The groundings and salvage significantly injured the reefstructure and threatened living marine resources. Out of court settlements in 1991 resulted in $ 2.74 million torestore the reef system.  After engineering planning and design, a team assembled from NOAA's DamageAssessment and Restoration Program (the Restoration Center of the National Marine Fisheries Service, theDamage Assessment Center of the National Ocean Service, and the General Counsel for Natural Resources) andNOAA's Sanctuaries and Reserves Division participated in an unprecedented effort to restore the damaged coralreef habitats. The goals were to stabilize the reef structure and prevent additional injury from loose debris. Theteam also wanted to rehabilitate part of the living portion of the reef system and make it indistinguishable fromnatural, unimpacted reefs.<P>

<P>
At the Maitland site (cover photograph), a three-dimensional relief habitat composed of reef replicating armorunits was created.  The units are concrete structures cast with different size rocks and boulders to provide a stable,natural framework on which transplanted corals, coral larvae, and other organisms may colonize, restoring theinjured area's habitat value and providing a natural framework for recovery.  Forty of the large, pre-cast concretereef units were placed in the injured area following removal of rubble caused by the groundings.<P>

<P>
At the Elpis site, quarried limestone boulders were used to fill in excavations in the reef. Sand was poured aroundthe boulders to form a continuous surface. The structures recreate the typical three-dimensional habitat relief ofnatural Florida Keys reefs. During the next several years, sanctuary biologists will transplant corals, sea fans, andsponges into the restored area with the goal of accelerating the rate of recovery by years or decades. <B>TimOsborn (301) 713-0174</B><P>

<P>

<P>
<B>Magnuson Act Reauthorization Progresses with House Approval of H.R. 39</B><P>
<P>
On Oct. 18, 1995, the House amended and passed H.R. 39, reauthorization of the Magnuson Fishery Conservationand Management Act (MFCMA), by a vote of 388-37.  The bill would amend and reauthorize the MFCMAthrough 1999 and provide for increased habitat conservation activities by the regional fishery management councilsand the Secretary of Commerce.  All councils would be required to submit an amendment for each fisherymanagement plan to include a description of essential fishery habitat for approval by the Secretary of Commerce. Federal agencies would be required to consult with the Secretary regarding any action that  may result in the"destruction or adverse modification of such essential fishery habitat." The Secretary would be required tocomment on and make recommendations regarding such actions; and the Federal agency would be required toprovide a detailed, written response to the Secretary. These provisions received formal Administration support ina Statement of Policy on H.R. 39, released September 18th by the Executive Office of the President, Office ofManagement and Budget. Another provision would make mandatory a previously discretionary provision requiringcouncils to include, in fishery management plans, measures that would minimize, to the extent practicable, anyadverse impact of fishing on essential fish habitat, and a requirement that Regional Councils evaluate the impact offishing gear on habitat. The Administration supported this provision but recommended that fishery managementplans should also include measures to minimize impacts from activities other than fishing. On the Senate side, thelast two field hearings on S. 39 were conducted by the Committee on Commerce, Science and Transportation onJuly 15 and 17 in Charleston, SC and Morehead City, NC. A Senate mark-up will be held once a substitute bill is developed.  Committee staff are predicting mark-up in early 1996. <B>Ralph Lopez (301)713-2325</B><P>

<P>

<P>
<B>Progress Continues on Habitat Strategic Plan</B> <P>

<P>

On September 28, 1995, Rollie Schmitten, the Assistant Administrator for Fisheries, approved the release of aPublic Review Draft of "A Strategic Plan to Strengthen the National Marine Fisheries Service's National HabitatProgram." This new Strategic Plan contains 25 major recommendations and 80 individual actions to beimplemented to strengthen the NMFS habitat program. These recommendations cover the areas ofConservation,Restoration, Understanding, and Management Improvements.  In early October, the Public Review Draft wasdistributed to about 150 constituents involved in the numerous public workshops that NMFS hosted to develop thePlan. Comments are due by mid-December. NMFS plans to issue the final Plan in early 1996. <B>JimBurgess (301) 713-2325</B><P>

<P>

<P>
<B>First Objective Completed in Essential Fish Habitat Initiative</B>
<P>

In FY 1995, the Office of Habitat Protection initiated an effort aimed at identifing essential fish habitat inanticipation of proposed Magnuson Act amendments.  A first milestone, a demonstration projecton summerflounder, was completed in September.  The project was a cooperative venture between the Office of HabitatProtection and the National Ocean Survey's Strategic Environmental Assessments Division, to develop amethodology for identifying and assessing important habitats for NMFS managed species.  The project reviewedenvironmental and biological data, geographic information systems and desktop mapping software, and evaluativetools available within NOAA.  A series of maps, demonstrating one methodology that may be useful fordeveloping descriptive map products to identify essential habitats, were produced. A summary report wasprepared that reviews the methodologies tested and results obtained, availability of data, and conclusions andrecommendations based on the demonstration project. The report will provide a basis for expansion of theEssential Fish Habitat Initiative in FY 1996. <B>Ramona Schreiber (301) 713-2325</B>
<P>
<P><B>Habitat to be Central Focus of Upcoming ASMFC Workshop</B><P>

<P>
The Atlantic States Marine Fisheries Commission (ASMFC) will sponsor a Habitat Managers Workshop in March1996.  Purposes of the workshop are to: (1) identify state and Federal habitat managers that the ASMFC cancoordinate with; (2) provide habitat managers with information about current ASMFC fishery management plans;(3) inform habitat managers how to become more involved in the fishery management process at the Federal,ASMFC, and state levels); (4) identify information habitat managers and fishery managers need from each other;(5) provide an opportunity for technology exchange; and (6) develop a communication process between fishery andhabitat managers.  The tentative agenda calls for eight sessions: (1) Overview of Fisheries Management; (2)Existing Creative Tools for Fish Habitat Management; (3) Implications of Identifying Essential Fish Habitat; (4)Restoration or Enhancement for Fisheries; (5) Linking Habitat Loss to Fisheries Impacts; (6) Review of Issues andIdentification of Research Needs; (7) What Kind of Information Do Habitat Managers Need?; and (8) Wrap-up. Regional and Headquarters Habitat representatives are on the Workshop Steering Committee.  <B>Lee Crockett(410) 267-5672</B><P>

<P>

<P>
<B>NMFS' FY 1996 Habitat Budget Initiative Still Pending in Congress</B><P>
<P>

The President's FY 1996 Budget contained two major initiatives to enhance the resources needed to begin toimprove the effectiveness of the NMFS habitat program. The Budget contained a $3.6 million increase in the"Habitat Conservation" line item to enhance the base habitat program activities as well as to begin to meet therequirements outlined in the Administration's "essential fish habitat" initiative to improve the management of fishery resources under the Magnuson Fishery Conservation and Management Act.  In addition, the budgetcontained $1.5 million for base program funds for NOAA's Restoration Center, which is part of the NMFS'Office of Habitat Protection. These funds, which are contained in the "Resource Information" line item, areessential if NMFS is to continue its partnership with other NOAA offices for implementation of the DamageAssessment and Restoration Program and other restoration efforts. The House and Senate have provided only levelfunding for the "Habitat Conservation" line item, and only slight increases in the "Resource Information" lineitem, which will not accommodate the President's full increase request for habitat restoration. In addition,Chesapeake studies were reduced by $900 thousand in the House markup and by $300 thousand in the Senatemarkup, which will greatly limit pur habitat work in Chesapeake Bay. <B>Jim Burgess (301)713-2325</B><P>

<P>

<p>
<B>NOAA Clears Mitigation Banking Guidance  - Final Release Near</B><P>
<P>

Following evaluation of the comments received on the public review draft of the Federal interagency guidance onmitigation, NMFS and other Federal agencies held discussions on how the guidance should be amended to resolveconcerns raised in the public comments.  Major concerns included a misinterpretation of the example of 15%advanced debiting of banks as a set limit; a perception that the interagency coordination procedures would slowdown the development of the bank; and a need for more guidance on how mitigation banks fit into the establishedprocess of avoidance of wetland impacts, minimization of wetland impacts, and on-site compensatory mitigationfor unavoidable wetland impacts.  The guidance was revised to address these and other concerns, but the essencedid not change substantially.  NOAA signed the document in August and we are awaiting signature by Armybefore releasing it. Once released, NMFS will provide copies to all Offices with a memorandum offeringadditional guidance in implementation in accordance with NMFS habitat conservation policies. <B>Susan-Marie Stedman (301) 713-2325</B>
<P>

<P>
<B>NMFS Raises Concerns About Proposed Corps Appeals Process</B>
<P>

NMFS reviewed and developed NOAA comments on the Army Corps of Engineers (Corps) draft AdministrativeAppeals Process. The proposed process would allow administrative appeals of decisions made by the Corps aspart of their administration of the Clean Water Act Section 404 program.  Under the proposed process, appealabledecisions would include jurisdictional determinations, permit denials and conditions, and administrative penalties. The inclusion of permit conditions as an appealable decision was not part of the Clinton Administration's 1993Wetland Policy, and is of concern because permit conditions recommended by NMFS are an important tool inconserving fishery habitat.  NOAA's comments to the Corps expressed this concern, recommending that permitconditions be dropped from the list of appealable decisions. We also informed the Corps that should permitconditions remain on the list of appealable decisions, the final appeals process must recognize that Federal naturalresource statutes require full consultation with NMFS on any permit amended as a result of an appeal.  We willcontinue to work with the Corps to establish an appeals process that does not undermine NMFS' ability to protectimportant fish habitat. <B>Susan-Marie Stedman (301) 713-2325</B><P>

<P>

<P>
<B>NMFS Works Closely With Corps on New Nationwide Permit</B><P>
<P>

On July 7 the Corps authorized a new nationwide permit that will allow the filling of up to 1/2 acre ofnon-tidal water or wetlands for the purpose of building or expanding a single-family home.  NMFS has beenworking with the Corps on the development of this permit and was responsible for the restriction of the permit tonon-tidal water and wetlands.  NMFS also recommended excluding anadromous fish spawning habitat, and severalother provisions that would have improved our ability to ensure that adverse impacts to fish habitat do not occur,but those provisions were not included in the current permit.  However, this nationwide permit, as well as all ofthe other nationwide permits, will be re-authorized by the Corps in 1996.  NMFS plans on making a renewedeffort to amend the new Nationwide at that opportunity. <B>Susan-Marie Stedman (301)713-2325</B><P>
<P>

<P>
<B>Concerns for Anadromous Fish Addressed in Review of Forest Service Hydropower Policy</B><P>
<P>

The Office of Habitat Priotection developed NMFS comments on the Forest Service's proposed policy onhydropower applications that addresses procedures for the administration of authorizations and the processing ofproposals for 240 hydropower projects affecting National Forest System lands. NMFS efforts to move fish pasthydropower sites on Forest Service lands are especially critical, since these lands embrace some of the lastremaining areas in the contiguous states where anadromous fish habitat still exists in a pristine state.  Therecurring theme of the policy was the devolution of authority from the Forest Service, a resource managementagency that shares NMFS concerns for the integrity of aquatic ecosystems.  NMFS comments recommended thatthe Forest Service withdraw the parts of their proposal that would exacerbate difficulties that already exist inmanaging fisheries under Federal Energy Regulatory Commission licensing.  <B>Stephen Waste (301)713-2325</B><P>

<P>

<P>
<B>NMFS Reviews Proposed Legislation for Protection of Living Marine Resources</B><P>
<P>

The Office of Habitat Protection developed NMFS comments on the proposed Federal Power AdministrationTransfer Act that would authorize the Secretary of the Department of Energy to study and prepare plans to sell ortransfer the Southeastern, Southwestern, and Western Power Administrations out of Federal ownership. Althoughthe Act proposes to increase the responsiveness of the power administrations to local concerns, it does notcommunicate that ownership involves responsibility for protecting living marine resources, primarily anadromousfish. The Act would also require the Secretary of the Department of Energy to ignore Federal, state, and localenvironmental laws, describing them as "impediments" to the sales. We disagreed that compliance with existingFederal laws should be viewed an impediment to the Act.<P>

<P>
The Alaska Power Administration Sale Authorization Act would authorize the sale of two Federally licensedhydropower projects in Alaska, Eklutna and Snettisham, to the Alaska Power Authority. We supported this Actbecause it properly incorporates into law a 1991 Memorandum of Agreement entered into by NOAA and the Stateof Alaska regarding fish protection measures. The Act would also give the United States District Court for Alaskajurisdiction to review decisions pursuant to the Memorandum of Agreement, as well as enforcement authority. Together, these provisions would preserve the fisheries management capabilities NMFS previously exercised underthe Federal Power Act, despite the change in jurisdiction resulting from the sale from a Federal to a state entity.<B>Stephen Waste (301) 713-2325</B>
<P>

<p>
<B>AROUND THE COUNTRY</B>
<P>

<P>

<P>
<B>Recommendations for Habitat Conditions Submitted to Boston Harbor Navigation ImprovementProject</B>
<P>

NMFS' Northeast Region reviewed the Final Environmental Impact Statement (FEIS) for the Boston HarborNavigation Improvement Project, one of the largest dredging projects ever undertaken in New England.  Itinvolves the removal of 1.1 million cubic yards of contaminated silt, 1.7 million cubic yards of clean parentmaterial, and 88,000 cubic yards of rock.  An additional 1.8 million cubic yards of clean material would bedredged to create in-channel disposal sites for the contaminated material, and the disposal sites would be cappedwith clean sand.  The Region compiled NOAA's comments on the Final Environmental Impact Statement,including input from the Stellwagen Bank National Marine Sanctuary and the Office of Coastal ResourceManagement. Among other things, we recommended additional fish sampling at the disposal sites, development ofcontingency plans case the in-channel sites cannot contain all the contaminated material, feasibility investigationsof using turbidity control chutes during dredged material disposal, and development of a detailed long-term monitoring plan for the in-channel disposal sites. <B>Jon Kurland (508) 281-9204</B><P>

<P>

<P>

<B>Port Facility a Serious Threat to Habitat - NMFS Recommends Alternative Location</B><P>

<P>

NMFS' Northeast Region reviewed the Draft Supplemental Environmental Impact Statement for a proposal by theMaine Department of Transportation to construct a new 95-acre port facility on Sears Island in Penobscot Bay,Maine. The project would result in substantial adverse effects to eelgrass beds, tidal flats, shellfish habitat, andfreshwater wetlands and wildlife habitat on Maine's largest undeveloped island. Over 200 people attended therecent public hearing for the project, which included about 130 speakers and lasted more than nine hours. TheDeputy Regional Director read a prepared statement at the hearing, saying the Sears Island proposal "would beone of the most damaging coastal development projects to occur in New England since modern environmentalstandards went into effect in the 1970s." NMFS is recommending that the Corps of Engineers deny a permit forSears Island, and that the applicant instead build the port at a nearby industrially-developed site that supportedcargo wharves in the 1930s.<B>Jon Kurland (508) 281-9204</B><P>

<P>
<B>Concerns for Anadromous Fish Support Decommission of Dam</B><P>
<P>

NMFS' Northeast Region submitted preliminary fishway prescriptions to the Federal Energy RegulatoryCommission (FERC) on the relicensing application for the Edwards Dam hydroelectric project on the KennebecRiver in Augusta, Maine.  The project impounds and degrades a 15-mile stretch of river that is historic spawninghabitat for anadromous fish. The area between Edwards Dam and the next upstream dam constitutes the historicupstream migratory limit of four anadromous species. Those species do not use conventional fishways, sobreaching the dam is the only viable way to provide fish passage. NMFS recommended that FERC deny therelicensing application and order the project decommissioned and removed. This is the first hydroelectric projectnationally to test the scope of FERC's authority (and willingness) to order dam removal at the licensee's expense. <B>Jon Kurland (508) 281-9204</B><P>

<P>

<P>
<B>NMFS Advocates Expansion of Shellfish Aquaculture Operation</B><P>
<P>

Spatco, Ltd. is a small aquaculture venture in Point Judith Pond, Rhode Island that produces American oysters,hard clams and bay scallops for the commercial seafood industry.  In response to a proposal to expand theoperation, NMFS' Northeast Region conducted an environmental assessment. The evaluation considered possibleimpacts of the project on local habitat quality and hydrodynamic characteristics and phytoplankton abundance andconcluded that the project would have only minimal adverse impact, and  could provide habitat benefits as well.  Inparticular, the additional cages would create more hard substrate that would provide crevices and other refuge forsmall or juvenile finfish, crustacean and molluscan species.  The area also would increase available spawningsubstrate for organisms with demersal, adhesive eggs. The expanded operation may promote improved waterquality of this nutrient-enriched habitat due to increased grazing by the growing shellfish.  NMFS' support of thisproject at a public hearing was instrumental in obtaining the necessary permits. <B>Cori Collins (203)783-4213</B><P>

<P>

<P>
<B>Restoration of 225 Acres Planned for Army Creek Superfund Site</B><P>

<P>

The Restoration Plan for the Army Creek Landfill Superfund site has been completed, and will be presented to theDamage Assessment and Restoration Program Board for approval early next quarter.  Following public review, itis anticipated that restoration actions will be initiated in the spring of 1996.  The plan delineates rehabilitation of225 acres of degraded saltmarsh and restoration of tidal influence to 1 mile of impounded river.  Additionally,NMFS' Northeast Region, NOAA's Restoration Center, and NMFS' Southeast Region have developed theframework for monitoring the relative success of proposed measures to restore wetland and fish habitat at ArmyCreek. <B>Tim Goodger (410) 226-5771</B><P>

<P>
<P>
<B>FY 1995 a Strong Year in Chesapeake Bay Research</B><P>
<P>

NOAA's Chesapeake Bay Office (NCBO) continues to support Bay research projects, begun in 1985 with the firstChesapeake Bay Studies funding from Congress.  In FY 1995, NCBO supported the following efforts: ChesapeakeBay Stock Assessment Committee, $540,000; Chesapeake Bay Environmental Effects Committee, $600,000;Chesapeake Bay Remote Sensing Support $60,000; and Bioavailability of Organic Nitrogen in Lower ChesapeakeBay Waters, $55,000.  <B>Bess Gillelan (410) 267-5661</B>
<P>

<P>
<B>Nutrient Loading, Chlorophyll Levels, and Atmospheric Deposition of Nitrogen to Coastal WatersAddressed in NCBO Water Quality Research</B>
<P>
<P>
NOAA's Chesapeake Bay Office (NCBO) is investigating the condition of habitats in Chesapeake Bay and itsmajor tributaries.  NCBO is analyzing water quality monitoring data to determine whether reductions in nutrients(nitrogen and phosphorus) can be detected in the Bay and, if so, whether they are playing a role in improvingfisheries habitat. The common belief is that increased nutrient concentrations over several decades has led toincreased algal (phytoplankton) growth and subsequent decreased dissolved oxygen (DO) during the summer whenthe algae die and decompose. Bay DO levels in summer had increased in recent decades, limiting bottom andpelagic habitat for estuarine biota.  Monitoring data are collected through grants from EPA's Chesapeake BayProgram and analyzed by NCBO for trends in oxygen, chlorophyll (as a measure of algal growth), nitrogen,phosphorus, and other factors.   Images are  compiled from these data to give visual representations of habitatquality.<P>

Surface chlorophyll levels are also measured through a remote sensing project sponsored jointly by NCBO and theMaryland Sea Grant Program.  In its sixth year, the project has begun to show year-to-year patterns of spring andsummer algal blooms. These data will assist in evaluation of the Bay's response to decreasing nutrient loads to theBay over the long term.<P>

NCBO is addressing the issue of atmospheric deposition of nitrogen in the Bay watershed in conjunction NOAA'sOffice of Oceanic and Atmospheric Research's Air Resource Laboratory (ARL), which has been investigating thisphenomenon for several years using the Bay watershed as a case study.  This issue has become increasinglyimportant to regional water quality efforts designed to meet the Bay-wide goal of reducing nitrogen andphosphorus by 40% by the year 2000.  As much as 20-40% of the total nitrogen entering the Bay is estimated tocome from atmospheric deposition (a combination of deposition directly to the water surface and to land areas andsubsequent runoff).  Atmospheric nitrogen is not yet factored into policies to meet the Bay-wide 40% nutrientreduction goal, but air pollution controls designed to reduce ground-level ozone will reduce nitrogen oxides andthereby help Bay states meet this goal and limit nitrogen and phosphorus input to the Bay beyond the year 2000. <B>Bess Gillelan (410) 267-5661</B>
<P>

<P>
<B>NCBO Works to Improve Habitat Sections in Chesapeake Bay Fishery  ManagementPlans</B><P>
<P>

NOAA's Chesapeake Bay Office is working with other state and federal agencies of the Chesapeake Bay Program(CBP) to incorporate habitat management measures in the fishery management plans (FMP's) developed forChesapeake Bay fisheries under the Chesapeake Bay Agreement.  Traditionally, habitat sections in the FMP's forthe CBP provided only general descriptions of the types of habitats used by fishery species, making little effort tosuggest management measures that might improve their habitats.  Recently, the CBP decided to strengthen itsFMP's by including more specific habitat requirements in new and revised Bay-wide FMP's, as they aredeveloped. A workgroup was established to develop a source document that will describe the habitat requirementsof fish stocks and provide needed background information on the types of activities that adversely impact thosehabitats. The source document will be reviewed by the CBP be signed by the member organizations, providing amechanism for states to either encourage or require adequate consideration of habitat impacts in all permitting decisions. <B>Anne Lange (410) 267-5675</B>
<P>

<P>

<B>Restoration Project Initiated on Chesapeake Bay's Poplar Island</B><P>

<P>

The project, a "beneficial use" of dredged material from the Baltimore approach channels, will restoreapproximately 1,100 acres of a mixed habitat island in Chesapeake Bay. Current plans call for creating a1,110-acre island which would consist of 50% wetlands and 50% uplands. Of the wetlands, 80% is proposed tobe low marsh, which has the highest habitat value for living marine resources.  NOAA's involvement is acooperative effort among NOAA's Chesapeake Bay Office and Restoration Center, and NMFS's Northeast Regionand Southeast Fisheries Science Center's Beaufort Laboratory.  The Beaufort Laboratory has the lead forlong-term monitoring studies in which changes in structure and function will be measured, and the relative use ofcreated habitats by fisheries resources will be compared with natural habitats. <B>Tim Goodger (410)226-5771 or Lee Crockett (410) 267-5672</B><P>

<P>

<P>
<B>New Role in Cooperative Research Designated for the Oxford Laboratory</B><P>
<P>

On June 2, a ground-breaking ceremony was held at the Cooperative Oxford Maryland Laboratory.  NMFS andthe Maryland Department of Natural Resources (DNR), which have shared the Oxford Laboratory since 1987under a cooperative agreement, joined forces in a unique project to renovate the main building and add a wing. NOAA transferred approximately $720 thousand to the DNR for the renovation effort, and DNR provided in kindlabor to design and construct the new wing. NMFS Deputy Director and the Beaufort Laboratory Director, joinedMaryland officials and Maryland Senator Paul Sarbanes for the event. NOAA's Administrator agreed in 1994 to aplan to manage the NMFS element of the cooperative laboratory through the Beaufort Laboratory, with programguidance from NOAA's Chesapeake Bay Office. The new program at the Oxford Laboratory will operate as adivision of the Beaufort Laboratory. New initiatives are being developed to strengthen the oyster disease researchprogram, initiate habitat restoration science efforts, and to coordinate with the DNR on its regional responses tomarine mammal strandings and sea turtle mortality around the Delmarva peninsula. <B>Bess Gillelan (410)267-5661</B><P>

<P>

<P>
<B>Habitat Restoration Saves Coral Reef Ecosystem in Florida Marine Sanctuary</B><P>
<p>

The <I>COLUMBUS ISELIN</I>, a 160-foot research vessel owned by the University of Miami, ran agroundon August 10, 1994 in the western portion of Looe Key Reef, within the Looe Key National Marine Sanctuary. The ship remained on the spur and groove formations for two days, resulting in substantial destruction of livingcorals and reef biota and generating a large amount of coral rubble.  NOAA filed an administrative notice ofviolation against the University and assessed the maximum available civil penalty under the regulations. In May,the University agreed to pay the penalty.  This summer, NOAA's Restoration Center coordinated the removal ofcoral rubble from the site; such unconsolidated coral rubble is easily moved by winter storms and can causeadditional injury to surrounding healthy coral.  With the immediate threat of additional injury removed, focus willshift to stabilizing and restoring the coral spurs at the grounding site. <B>Erik Zobrist (301)713-0174</B><P>

<P>

<P>
<B>Habitat Conservation Engineering Teams Established in Southwest</B><P>

<P>

NMFS's Southwest Region recognizing the need to coordinate closely with other resource agencies to maximizestaff efficiency established a Regional Habitat Conservation engineering team. The team will train an interagencygroup of diverse fish passage/screening experts to address issues related to screening diversions to protectoutmigrating juvenile salmon in the Sacramento River and FEMAT/PACFISH rivers and streams. This is acritical program in dealing with issues such as the Sacramento River/Delta where there are more than 1,700unscreened diversions which result in annual losses of millions of juveniles. <B>Marcin Whitman  (707) 578-7513</B>
<P>
<P>

<P><B>Funding Received for Fisheries Restoration Project</B>
<P>

NMFS's Southwest Region received $25,000 from NOAA's Restoration Center to fund a 1 1/2-mile fisheriesrestoration project on Brush Creek in the City of Santa Rosa, California. The project concentrates on tree plantingto provide canopy riparian habitat, which will provide the single-most long-term solution to the problem of highwater temperatures which adversely impact anadromous fish.  The project has gained support from federal, state,and local governments; as well as, community organizations and businesses.  Under the direction of the SonomaCounty Water Agency and the Sonoma County Relief more than 200 students will plant 1500 trees on November9, 1995.  The Pacific Gas and Electric Company has committed to donate 251 specially silk-screened T-shirts forthe volunteers and the Calistoga Mineral Water Company has agreed to donate 300 bottles of mineral water for theevent. Letters of invitation schools, governments, and dignitaries to join in this unique tree planting event will begoing out soon. <B>Dave Mattens (707) 578-7513</B><P>

<P>

<P>
<B>Interagency Effort Wins Restoration of Tidal Marsh at Hamilton Army Airfield</B><P>

<p>

This past summer, NMFS's Southwest Region initiated an active campaign with state and Federal natural resourceagencies for restoration of the Hamilton Army Airfield Base to tidal wetlands. The base is located approximately25 miles north of San Francisco on San Pablo Bay in the City of Novato. The base is being disposed by theDepartment of Army under the Base Closure and Realignment Act of 1988 or BRAC 1. The airfield parcelcomprises approximately 700 acres of diked historic tidal salt marsh. There have been no attempts by the resourceagencies to collectively pool their efforts for obtaining and restoring the property to wetlands.  We saw thisopportunity and organized a focused effort by the agencies to have the property transferred and restored towetlands. The effort has met immediate success.  A state resource agency willingly stepped forward to serve asthe landowner. In addition, the Army has agreed to examine the feasibility of linking their contamination cleanupresponsibilities to the wetland restoration effort. The state and Federal agencies have agreed in principal on a setof fish and wildlife restoration goals and objectives. The Region also presented the project to the SouthwestImplementation Team of Coastal America and received their endorsement.  Efforts by the Region are now focusedon resolving flood control issues between the Army and the potential new landowner by proposing the Army useclean dredge spoils to isolate contamination on the parcel and transfer funds originally designated forcontamination cleanup to flood control.<B> Mark Helvey (310) 980-4079</B><P>

<P>

<P>

<B>First Year of San Diego Bay Fishery Utilization Study Completed</B> <P>

<P>

The first year of a five-year comprehensive fishery study of San Diego Bay was completed.  The Bay was dividedinto four geographic areas with two stations in each area being sampled on a quarterly basis. Five types ofsampling gear are being employed at each station to ensure that the entire fishery community is adequatelysampled.  NMFS's Southwest Region was successful in convincing the Navy and Port of San Diego to jointly fundthe project for up to $500,000.  The Region provides technical oversight for the project. The results will be usedas a planning tool to assist the Navy and Port of San Diego in locating future projects in areas with the leastimpacts to fishery and other wildlife resources.  <B>Robert Hoffman (310) 980-4043</B><P>

<P>

<P>
<B>Pilot Project Makes Substantial Progress in Restoration of Industrial Uplands to Valuable EstuarineHabitat</B><P>
<P>

A groundbreaking ceremony was held for the Middle Waterway Restoration Pilot Project June 15, marking thesuccessful implementation of an industry-government-public partnership between Tacoma Simpson Kraft Companyand the natural resource trustees (the u.s. Fish and Wildlife Service; NOAA; the Washington Departments ofEcology, Fish and Wildlife, and Natural Resources; and the Puyallup and Muckleshoot Indian Tribes).  Project goals are to create productive and diverse estuarine habitats for fish and wildlife; and to provide an outdoorlaboratory for studying various planting strategies, monitoring protocols, and volunteer/ stewardship models forfuture natural resource restoration efforts in the region.  The 4.9 acre project will convert industrial uplands toestuarine upper intertidal wetlands, salt marsh and intertidal mud/sand habitats.  A riparian buffer and transitionzone will screen, protect, and support the diversity of the remnant Middle Waterway mudflats. To date, theproject has created 1.5 new acres of high intertidal habitat from an industrial fill adjacent to 1.9 acres of existingrelic tidal flats.  Salvaged intertidal plants have survived the hot Northwest summer.  A 600+ plant upland bufferplanting operation, supported mainly by volunteers, was completed October 21. The site has started revegetatingsince completion of construction, and has stabilized very quickly. <B>Bob Clark (206) 526-4338</B><P>

<P>

<P>
<B>NPDES General Permit For Alaskan Log Transfer Facilities a Cause for Alarm</B><P>

<P>

In Alaska, timber harvested on numerous coastal islands and isolated mainland areas is transported over short roadnetworks to termination point at salt water where the log bundles are transferred either into the saltwater or ontobarges or ocean-going vessels. These log transfer facilities (LTFs) generally consist of an upland logtruckunloading area and a device to transfer the log bundles. When the transfer is into the water there is usually anearby rafting area where log bundles are grouped and restrained against each other prior to towing them to millsor into the holds of ocean-going vessels. Section 404 permits are required for the intertidal modificationsnecessary to construct the facilities; and Section 402 (NPDES) permits for the discharge of bark and wood wasteinto nearshore habitat that occurs in the transfer process. Since the mid-1980s, comments on proposed LTFs andmodifications to existing facilities have been solicited through combined NPDES and Section 10/404 public noticesissued by the Corps of Engineers. The Environmental Protection Agency is now proposing to issue a NPDESgeneral permit (GP) for new and modified LTFs. NMFS's Alaska Region is concerned the GP will preclude theopportunity for agencies and other interested parties to comment on qualifying LTF proposals.  Opportunities torelocate facilities away from valuable shellfish habitat, eelgrass beds, nursery areas, etc. may be lost due to theuse of this GP. <B>Andrew Grossman (907) 586-7235</B><P>

<P>

