<BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0000" ALINK="#800080"><BR>
<STRONG><H2><CENTER>NMFS HABITAT HAPPENINGS...</CENTER></H2></STRONG>
<STRONG><H3><CENTER><U>AUGUST 96</U></CENTER></H3></STRONG><BR>




                                <U><U><CENTER><STRONG>NATIONAL PROGRAM</STRONG></CENTER></U></U><P>
                                        <P>
                        <STRONG> <CENTER>Habitat Funding Requests Move Through Congress</CENTER> </STRONG><P>

<P>
<BR>
Congressional appropriations committees in the Senate and House of Representatives have marked funding levels for NMFS Office of Habitat Conservation programs for Fiscal Year 1997, which begins  October 1, 1996. The President s FY97 budget had requested increases of $2.3 million for the NMFS Habitat Conservation line item (from $8 to $10.3 million) and $1.5 million for habitat restoration under the NMFS Resource Information line item. The House did not provide any increased funding for these two high-priority program activities. However, the House did provide for an increase for the  Chesapeake Bay Studies program activities to restore funding to the level of the FY96 President s request. The Senate on the other hand provided sufficient funds for the habitat conservation and restoration requests, but did not restore the Chesapeake Bay funding.<P>

<P>
<BR>
The President s Habitat Conservation line item request related to supporting growing demands on NMFS to identify and preserve essential fish habitats, implement innovative approaches for the protection of coastal wetlands, and deal with the significantly increased influx of major hydroelectric dam relicensings during the late 1990 s. The habitat restoration funding request represents necessary base funding that has never been available to implement NMFS responsibilities under the NOAA Damage Assessment and Restoration Program, including funds necessary to initiate a restoration research program. Lack of base funding has restricted NMFS restoration activities to natural resource damage actions, collaborative projects with the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, and other reimbursable projects.  <P>
<P>
<BR>
Support for increased NMFS activities is a key step towards implementing the NMFS Habitat Plan. Differences between the House and Senate appropriations levels will be resolved during a House-Senate conference in September.  
<STRONG>Jim Burgess (301) 713-2325
</STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>
          <STRONG><CENTER>Progress on Senate Magnuson Act Reauthorization Legislation</CENTER></STRONG><P>

<P>
<BR>

In late March, the Committee on Commerce, Science, and Transportation of the U.S. Senate marked up and reported S. 39, the <STRONG><EM>Sustainable Fisheries Act,</EM></STRONG> to the Senate floor. While the full Senate failed to take up S. 39 prior to recessing for the month of August, substantial progress was made in resolving concerns that have prevented floor action to date. Staff for Senators Stevens, Kerry, Gorton, Murray, Wyden, and Snowe appear to have reached agreement on the provisions of the manager s amendment that will enable the bill to go to the Senate floor on September 4 under unanimous consent.  <P>
<P>

Like H.R. 39, the <STRONG><EM>Fishery Conservation and Management Amendments of 1995,</EM></STRONG> which the House of Representatives passed by a vote of 388 to 37 last October, the Senate version provides for increased habitat conservation activities by the regional fishery management councils and the Secretary of Commerce. The strengthened habitat provisions call for the councils to identify essential fish habitat for each fishery and minimize adverse effects on habitat due to fishing. The bill also expands the existing authority of the councils and the Secretary to comment on Federal actions that would affect habitat.<STRONG> Ralph Lopez (301) 713-2325</STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>

 <STRONG>  <CENTER>Federal Guidance for the Establishment, Use, and Operation of Mitigation Banks Published</CENTER></STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>

The final Federal Guidance for the Establishment, Use, and Operation of Mitigation Banks was published in the Federal Register on November 28, 1995. It became effective on December 28, 1995, and will serve as guidance for all Federal agencies involved in mitigation banking. The guidance was developed as an interagency effort by staff from NMFS  Office of Habitat Conservation in cooperation with staff from the Fish and Wildlife Service, the Environmental Protection Agency, the Army Corps of Engineers, and the Natural Resources Conservation Service. The draft guidance was published in the Federal Register in March 1995 for public comment and revised after consideration of those comments.<P>
<P>
<BR>
The major purpose of the guidance is to coordinate and facilitate the establishment, use, and operation of mitigation banks to provide ecologically sound wetland mitigation. To that end, the guidance establishes an interagency process that allows resource protection agencies such as NMFS to have input into mitigation bank planning and operation, beginning at the earliest stages. By soliciting recommendations from resource protection agencies early in the planning process, bank sponsors are better able to plan mitigation banks that provide appropriate mitigation and whose use will be acceptable to the resource agencies.<P>
<P>
<BR>
The guidance has been sent to all NMFS Habitat field offices, is available as a WordPerfect file via e-mail (send an e-mail request to  Susan.Stedman@noaa.gov ), and can be accessed via the NMFS Habitat Program World Wide Web Homepage (http://www.kingfish.ssp.nmfs.gov/rschreib/habitat.html).  To further facilitate the establishment of good mitigation banks, an interagency group is working on a sample mitigation banking agreement and other technical appendices to the guidance. These documents will be publicized as they become available. <STRONG>Susan-Marie Stedman (301) 713-2325</STRONG><P>
 <P>
<BR>
<STRONG><CENTER> Corps Issues Draft Regulatory Guidance Letter on Programmatic General Permits</CENTER></STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>
On April 26, 1996 the Army Corps of Engineers (Corps) published a draft Regulatory Guidance Letter (RGL) on Programmatic General Permits (PGPs) in the Federal Register for public comment.  PGPs are used extensively in the northeast United States and a few other parts of the country to coordinate state and Federal programs and provide a more efficient wetland regulatory process for permit applicants. There is substantial interest from both Federal and state agencies in expanding the use of PGPs because PGPs allow Federal agencies to screen proposed projects and concentrate their evaluation efforts on those projects with the greatest potential for harming the  environment, while allowing states to take the lead in wetland permitting.<P>
<P>
<BR>
As part of the White House Wetlands Working Group, NOAA and NMFS staff reviewed early drafts of the RGL and suggested improvements, most of which were incorporated into the current version of the RGL.  During the public comment period that ended May 28, we solicited input and formal comments on the draft RGL from NMFS field offices. Our comments generally supported the draft RGL, but suggested that the RGL be  amended to 1) direct the Corps to coordinate with Federal natural resource agencies during reviews of PGPs and 2) remove numerical examples in the discussion of review categories. Publication of the final RGL is expected by the end of the summer. 
<STRONG>Susan-Marie Stedman (301) 713-2325</STRONG><P>
<P>
 <BR>
     <STRONG> <CENTER>Sustain Healthy Coasts FY98 Budget Initiative Well Received by NOAA</CENTER></STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>
NOAA s Sustain Healthy Coasts (SHC) budget team presented its FY98 budget initiative to the NOAA Administration on May 3, 1996. The Office of Habitat Conservation represents the NMFS on the SHC team. NOAA guided the teams to develop initiatives based on two tiers of budget growth. Based on the team's Strategic Plan goals to "Protect, Conserve and Restore Coastal Habitats," "Promote Clean Coastal Waters," and "Foster Well-Planned Coastal Communities," three initiatives were proposed.  NMFS and the Office of Habitat Conservation solicited input from the regions and incorporated this information into a series of new initiatives. <P>
<P>
<BR>
Within the "Strengthen National Coastal Monitoring and Assessment" initiative, NMFS proposed two activities: "Enhance the Coastal Change Analysis Program," and "Build an Integrated Information Base for Water Quality Management." Several activities were proposed by NMFS within the "Improve Ecosystem Approaches to Coastal Management" initiative, including: "Enhance Ability to Influence Decisions;" "Build Regional Ecosystem Management and Assessments;" "Enhance Habitat Restoration;" "Improve Collection and Use of Biodiversity Information;" and "Improve Coral Reef Ecosystem Management." The "Improved Guidance" activity within the third initiative, "Mitigate Impacts of Coastal Hazards: Reduce Losses of Life and Property," also included a NMFS component. Many of these activities include the other line-office members of SHC: NOS, COP, OAR, and NESDIS.<P>
<P>
<BR>
Initial feedback from NOAA Administration has indicated support for NMFS  proposals.  Each of the proposals submitted within the first tier was supported at or near requested levels and one activity proposed in the second tier was pulled into the first tier by NOAA. NOAA forwarded the final budget proposal to the Department of Commerce on June 17.  
<STRONG>Ramona Schreiber (301) 713-2325</STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>


     <STRONG><CENTER>ASMFC Adopts NMFS Format for Species Distribution and Habitat Maps in 
                               Weakfish Amendment</CENTER></STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>
The Atlantic States Marine Fisheries Commission (ASMFC) is working to improve the habitat sections of its interstate fishery management plans. Following a presentation on NMFS  activities in mapping fish habitats and distributions at their annual meeting (November, 1995),  ASMFC  looked to the Office of Habitat Conservation for assistance in developing a series of maps for amendment 3 to their weakfish FMP.<P>
<P>
<BR>
The Office of Habitat Conservation collected weakfish distribution data from several sources, including NOS, NMFS, and seven Atlantic states. Maps have been prepared to display seasonal distribution and relative abundance for juvenile and adult weakfish throughout its range. The package was distributed to the state commissioners for review at the ASMFC spring meeting, where it was well received. Final maps have been refined for the final document. A full complement of maps will be included in the source document, and a summary series of maps will be included in the final amendment. This information is especially useful to expand the habitat sections and improve the overall amendments.  
<STRONG>Ramona Schreiber (301) 713-2325</STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>

                             <U>  <CENTER>AROUND THE COUNTRY</CENTER></U><P>
<P>
<BR>


         <STRONG>New Bedford Harbor: First Round of Restoration Ideas Selected</STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>

During the past six months, the restoration of New Bedford Harbor has begun to take shape. The New Bedford Harbor Trustee Council has moved to identify restoration ideas, partners, and levels of funding for its first round of restoration implementation, employing extensive public involvement. The restoration has received a great deal of media coverage and, at times, generated a fair amount of controversy.<P>
<P>
<BR>
Last October, the Trustee Council issued a  Request for Ideas  to solicit restoration ideas and to publicize evaluation criteria.  As a result, 56 ideas were received from citizens, non-profits, municipalities, academic institutions, state and Federal agencies, and private businesses. A 15-member Community Restoration Advisory Board (CRAB) was established in early February. Along with a Technical Advisory Committee and the Trustees  legal counsel, the CRAB reviewed restoration ideas and made recommendations to the Trustees. Public meetings and a public comment period ensured a full exchange of information between poject proponents, members of the public, and the Trustees throughout the evaluation process.<P>
<P>
<BR>
On May 14th, the Trustees announced their commitment to 13 restoration ideas, related to: salt marsh and sea grass; shellfish; anadromous fish runs; tern colonies; conservation land acquisition; harbor management planning; and contributions toward habitat and public access aspects of municipal park construction. Total cost of the Trustees commitments is estimated at approximately $5 million of the $20 million restoration fund.<P>
<P>
<BR>
Ideas notably omitted were a feasibility study for an aquarium complex in downtown New Bedford and a number of sewer projects submitted by area municipalities.In spite of intense lobbying by proponents, elected officials, and the New Bedford Standard-Times, the Trustee Council decided that these ideas did not clearly satisfy the Trustees  mandate to restore natural resources injured by PCB releases.<P>
<P>
<BR>
At present, Habitat staff are working with idea proponents to finalize project outlines. These will become the preferred alternatives in a Restoration Plan/Draft EIS that is being developed by Habitat staff, with help from the Department of the Interior. Once the RP/EIS is completed and financial decisions are rendered by the Trustee Council, funds can be awarded; implementation of selected projects is expected during the spring and summer of 1997.<P>
<P>
<BR>
The Trustee Council intends to initiate a second funding round once EPA issues a second Record of Decision for the Harbor cleanup; restoration activities will continue until EPA has completed remediation of the Harbor in about 10 years. 
<STRONG>Tom Ardito (301) 713-0174</STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>


                          <STRONG><CENTER>Maryland State Programmatic 
                                 General Permit</CENTER></STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>

In March the Army Corps of Engineers  Baltimore District notified NMFS that they planned to issue the Maryland State Programmatic General Permit (SPGP) over NMFS objections. The SPGP would authorize a variety of construction activities in coastal and inland waters and wetlands throughout Maryland via a streamlined permitting process. Although NMFS supports the concept of streamlined wetlands permitting in Maryland, the SPGP would have allowed dredging or filling up to 5 acres of tidal waters and wetlands per project with minimal Federal oversight, leaving NMFS with much less opportunity to avoid and minimize the loss of important fish and shellfish habitat. In April NMFS elevated the issue to NOAA's Assistant Secretary for Oceans and Atmosphere with a recommendation to seek review
of the Baltimore District s decision by the Assistant Secretary of the Army for Civil Works pursuant to Section 404(q) of the Clean Water Act. After interagency discussions at the headquarters level NOAA decided not to refer the issue to Army under 404(q), but instead reached agreement with Army to resolve many of NMFS  concerns. The revised SPGP which became effective July 1, includes a reduced (3 acre) upper threshold for tidal waters and many procedural improvements that will
simplify NMFS efforts to review projects of concern to marine resources.<STRONG> Jon
Kurland (508) 281-9204 or John Nichols (410) 226-5771</STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>


                     <STRONG> <CENTER>National Shellfisheries Association 
                                 (NSA) Meeting</CENTER></STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>

The 1996 NSA annual meeting, held in Baltimore April 15-19, provided a forum for presenting results of more than 25 oyster disease research projects funded by NOAA through NCBO during 1993-94.  Abstracts of all papers are available. In addition a special Blue Crab Symposium, organized by Maryland Department of Natural Resources and NMFS scientists from the Cooperative Oxford Laboratory and NCBO, reviewed the current status of blue crab stocks, fisheries, and management throughout the Atlantic and Gulf coasts. Preliminary results of the Chesapeake Bay Stock Assessment Committee s blue crab stock assessment were presented. A break-out session was held to discuss research priorities for Chesapeake Bay blue crabs. The large uncertainty regarding the longevity of blue crabs was a major
topic of discussio since new information suggests the maximum age may be 6-8 years, rather than 4 years. A report for this symposium will be available shortly.  
<STRONG>Bess Gillelan (410) 267-5661 or Anne Lange (410) 267-5675</STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>
                           <STRONG><CENTER>Chesapeake Bay Blue Crab 
                               Stock  Assessment</CENTER></STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>

The Chesapeake Bay Stock Assessment Committee (CBSAC), chaired by NCBO, is nearly finished with its blue crab stock assessment. The assessment is based on size composition data from the NCBO-funded winter dredge survey, other long-term trawl surveys, biological information determined from NCBO-funded projects and other Bay-area blue crab scientific research. A subcommittee of state and NMFS fishery biologists completed a draft report in August, which will be reviewed initiatilly
through a mail review in September, followed by a review panel of stock assessment scientists in November, before final release of results.
<STRONG>Bess Gillelan (410) 267-5661</STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>


             <STRONG> <CENTER> Dredged Material Placement in Upper Chesapeake Bay</CENTER></STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>
The NCBO and NMFS  Northeast Region have been participating with other stakeholders (state and Federal agencies, port industries, fishermen,  environmental groups) on technical and policy committees to evaluate options for disposal of clean dredged material from the Chesapeake Bay approach channels to Baltimore Harbor. About 108 million cubic yards of material will need to be dredged during the next
20 years, and existing placement sites will be filled up by fall 1997. The Governor has proposed a set of options developed through a consensus-based process that includes a mix of beneficial use, open water disposal, and containment sites. Chris Mantzaris, Habitat Division Chief, NMFS/NER, testified in general support of this process in a Maryland General Assembly hearing in March.<P>

<BR>
Habitat staff from the NCBO and NER have taken an active role in steering site selection away from areas of high living resource value, using a GIS overlay of key fish and waterfowl habitats and unique ecological features of the Bay. This new screening tool was developed by NCBO during the fall of 1995 in cooperation with other state and Federal natural resource agencies. The tool was instrumental in helping to narrow containment site options to four locations, three of which are in areas without high living resource value.  It has enabled NMFS to play a more constructive role in finding workable solutions to the dredged material placement issue, and may have applications elsewhere.<P>
<BR>
The Maryland General Assembly has pressured the state to identify two large containment sites in the upper Bay by September 1996 to solve the long-term capacity shortfall and calm the fears of port-related industries. Private industry has suggested dumping material into the "Deep Trough" of the Bay, an inexpensive but highly controversial option not in the Governor s action plan due to numerous environmental concerns, e.g., it is a refuge for over-wintering fish. The beneficial use/island restoration project at Poplar Island has broad support and is in the Governor s action plan but is very expensive relative to the other options. The Poplar Island project is expected to receive $22 million in FY97 from the Army Corps, with dike construction to begin this fall; no other option will be ready to accept material when capacity at existing sites runs out in 1997.<P>
<BR>
In early September, NMFS is expected to join other Federal and state resource agencies in signing a Statement of Cooperation to support the stae's efforts to identify a long-term economically and environmentally sound dredged material management plan, in accordance Federal and state laws.  
<STRONG>Bess Gillelan (410) 267-5661, Lee Crockett (410) 267-5672 or  Chris Mantzaris  (508) 281-9346
</STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>

                        <STRONG> <CENTER>Sandy Island, South Carolina 
                                Mitigation Bank</CENTER></STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>
NMFS entered into a Memorandum of Agreement with the South Carolina Departments of Transportation, Natural Resources and Health and Environmental Control; Federal Highway Administration; Corps of Engineers; Environmental Protection Agency; and the Fish and Wildlife Service to establish the $14 million Sandy Island Mitigation Bank. The agreement was produced as mitigation to offset the environmental impact of highway construction projects in South Carolina. Sandy Island comprises more than 9,000 acres of lands and wetlands of outstanding fish and wildlife value that
were faced with the imminent threat of development. The Agreement is intended to ensure that the area is maintained in its natural state in perpetuity. The agreement resolved complex issues and is an exceptional partnership effort between construction, regulatory, review, and private sector interests. According to Federal Highway Administration, they intend to use lessons learned in South
Carolina to foster better relations in other areas. NMFS notes that in South Carolina and Georgia the Federal Highway Administration has played an important role as mediator during negotiations regarding technical aspects of highway design and environmental protection compliance.<P>
<BR>

As an added bonus, the negotiations also resulted in the acquisition of an 8,000-acre tract of ecologically-important forested wetlands located in the Pee Dee River drainage in northeastern South Carolina. Reaction has been highly favorable and the land acquisitions have been regarded as being good investments because they foster needed highway projects and protect ecologically sensitive and
important areas. The purchase was made possible by eliminating extensive bridging of marginal value wetlands and re-diverting some funds to wetland and upland preservation.  
<STRONG>David Rackley (803) 762-8574</STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>

                         <STRONG> <CENTER>Summary of CWPPRA Activities</CENTER></STRONG>

The  Coastal Wetlands Planning, Protection and Restoration Act (CWPPRA) was enacted November 29, 1990 to establish a Federal/State Interagency Task Force in Louisiana for the development, funding, and implementation of wetland restoration projects focused on the protection, conservation, enhancement, and restoration of eroding/threatened wetlands in the state. The goal of the Act is to reverse the long-term trend of coastal wetland loss. The focus on Louisiana is due to the state containing slightly more than 40% of the nation s coastal wetlands, but suffering 80% of total national wetland loss. A national component of the CWPPRA program is implemented by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service through two grants programs that fund wetlands conservation projects. The Task Force consists of:

      <UL>
<LI>U.S. Army Corps of Engineers
</UL>

     <UL>
<LI> NOAA s National Marine Fisheries Service (Department of Commerce)
</UL>

     <UL>
<LI> U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service (Department of Interior)
</UL>

     <UL>
<LI> U.S. Natural Resource Conservation Service (Department of Agriculture)
</UL>

     <UL>
<LI> Environmental Protection Agency
</UL>

     <UL>
<LI> State of Louisiana (represented by the Governor s Office)

</UL><P>
<P>
<BR>

The principle responsibilities are development of a long-term restoration plan for Louisiana s coastal wetlands, and development of an annual priority project list for implementing wetland restoration projects.  Each restoration project is evaluated on anticipated benefits and cost-effectiveness and funded on a 75% Federal, 25% state cost-share basis. Currently more than 60 projects are authorized at a total cost of $160 million.  NMFS is the sponsor o 11 CWPPRA funded projects with approximately $40 million of funds (Federal and state) being allocated to the projects.  More than 40,000 acres are expected to benefit from these projects. The following four are representative:<P>
<P>
<BR>

     <STRONG> Mississippi River Feasibility Study and Diversion Project -</STRONG>  This study is
evaluating the large-scale use of river diversions to preserve, create, enhance, and protect Louisiana s wetlands.  NMFS was awarded one of the first large-scale wetland restoration projects by the CWPPRA Task Force. The Myrtle Grove Freshwater Diversion project was one of only two watershed scale "big picture" projects ever awarded funding by the Task Force.  The project is located in Plaquemines Parish (south of New Orleans) and will provide up to 2,100 cubic feet per second of freshwater from the Mississippi River to a 15,000 acre project area of eroding fresh and brackish marsh and wetlands. The project cost is estimated at $15 million.<P>
<P>
<BR>

      <STRONG>Vermillion Parish Wetlands  -</STRONG> The Little Vermillion Sediment Trapping/Terracing project will create wetlands by dredging small distributary channels into Little Vermillion Bay from the navigation channel.  The area has a large movement of sediment into the bay and the project will direct and trap the sediment into emergent marsh.<P>
<P>
<BR>
     <STRONG> Barrier Island EIS -</STRONG> NMFS signed a Memorandum of Agreement (MOA)to develop  an Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) to restore Louisiana s barrier islands. The MOA is with the Minerals Management Service (MMS) and the Louisiana Department of Natural Resources (DNR), and establishes the roles and funding for preparing the EIS. The MMS and NMFS are co-lead agencies for the EIS and the DNR is the lead cooperating agency for the state. The MMS is contracting the development of the EIS with Louisiana State University. The EIS scoping meeting was in May.  <P>
<P>
<BR>

     <STRONG> Point au Fer Island -</STRONG> Final implementation of construction for the Point au Fer Island project is scheduled for Fall, 1996. Constructionincluded seven canal plugs  and active planning for final construction in Mobil Canal on the western side of the island. 
<STRONG>Tim Osborn (301) 713-0174</STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>


                        California Biodiversity Council

The Southwest Region, as a member of the California Biodiversity Council is
playing an ever increasing role in habitat protection through its involvement on
the Council.  The Council is comprised of senior representatives of local, state,
and Federal agencies involved in resource management decisions.  Activities focus
on developing statewide strategies to conserve biological diversity and to
coordinate implementation of the strategies through regional and local
institutions.  The enhancement of interagency communications and cooperation are
facilitated through a web site
(http://spp-www.cdf.ca.gov/htdocs/biodiv/bechome.html) developed and maintained
by the California Resources Agency.  Quarterly meetings of the Council are
scheduled in various locations throughout the state to highlight issues of
regional concern.  
Marty Golden (310) 980-4004


             <STRONG><CENTER>Batiquitos Lagoon Enhancement Project Nears Completion</CENTER></STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>


The Batiquitos Lagoon Enhancement Project, located near San Diego, California, is one of the most significant wetlands restoration projects in the United States. Restoration work to return the Lagoon to a full tidal system is ongoing and should be completed in early 1997. The project is funded by the Port of Los Angeles as a mitigation measure to offset the loss of deep-water marine habitat in outer Los
Angeles Harbor. When completed, the Lagoon will provide nearly 600 acres of restored subtidal, intertidal, and saltmarsh habitat. <STRONG>Robert Hoffman (310) 980-4043</STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>



                 <STRONG> <CENTER> Successful Live Coral Transplant in Hawaii</CENTER></STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>

The world s first successful large-scale coral transpant took place in Kawaihae Bay, Hawaii. Over a period of six months, beginning in September 1995, nearly 15 tons of live coral colonies were transplanted from two breakwater alignments to two large sites under 15 to 20 feet of water. Additional coral transplants in 10 to 50 feet of water were relocated to seven other experimental sites.  <P>
<P>
<BR> 

"The Kawaihae project has been an unprecedented success, with ninety-nine percent of the coral surviving relocation," said Hilda Diaz-Soltero, NMFS Southwest Regional Administrator.<P>
<P>
<BR>

The coral transplant project was recommended by NOAA s National Marine Fisheries Service, through the Pacific Islands Habitat Program, to restore adjacent coral reef habitat which was damaged during construction of a small boat harbor. Negotiations to develop mitigation for coral loss during harbor construction began in 1992 between NMFS, other Federal agencies, and Hawaii resource agencies. <P>
<P>
<BR>

In September 1995 the coral transplant was started with funding from the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers (COE).  Volunteer divers from the Science Department of Hawaii Preparatory Academy were instrumental to the transplant effort. As coral heads were carefully detached by divers, then placed in large wire trays, they were lifted up off the bottom and transported by boat, still submerged, to the new sites. Several coral attachment methods were utilized and sediment traps were placed to measure sedimentation rates.<P>
<P>
<BR>
   
Photographic and visual sensoring techniques are being used to evaluate and monitor the coral survival.  Monitoring will continue through August 1998 under contract services with students and staff of the University of Hawaii Institute of Marine Biology. Reports on the growth rates and mortality of the coral will be available during these three years.<P>
<P>
<BR>

Other parties participating in the project with NMFS and COE include the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, state of Hawaii Division of Aquatic Resources, and the staff and students of the University of Hawaii Institute of Marine Biology and Hawaii Preparatory Academy.<P>
<P>
<BR>
 
As stated by Hilda Diaz-Soltero, this unprecedented project study "proves that large quantities of these living animals can survive the trauma of transplant." 
<STRONG>John Naughton (808) 973-2940
</STRONG><P>
<P>
<BR>
