<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Elmer Dills
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="AA0000" VLINK="BBBB00">
<BR><IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=2 WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=10  CELLPADDING=8>
	<TR>
     	<TD><IMG SRC="710talk4.gif"></TD>

     	<TD WIDTH=75% >
	<H1>ELMER DILLS</H1>

	<FONT SIZE=5>"The Elmer Dills Show"<BR>
Sunday  4-7 p.m.<BR></FONT></TD>	
<CENTER></TABLE>

<BR><IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=70% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=0>
<TD>

<P>There are few people in the world who can claim to have eaten in as many restaurants as has 
Elmer Dills. He has sampled, enjoyed and even despised food from all around Southern California 
and the globe.<P>

<P>During his weekly Sunday program on KABC Talkradio, Elmer discusses restaurants and shares his recommendations with his 
listening audience. In addition to reviewing restaurants, Elmer focuses on various unique travel destinations for Southern 
Californians, including bed and breakfasts and romantic weekend getaways.<P>

<P>Elmer developed his love of traveling and dining during his 22 years as a Foreign Service Officer for the U.S. State 
Department, where he specialized in protocol matters. The majority of his job entailed entertaining,  and dining with, 
diplomats. His assignments included working in Europe and the Middle East. According to Dills, "My passion has always been 
trying new and exciting restaurants. That's how I spent my free time and money overseas." Later, he moved to Washington 
D.C., then finally to Los Angeles for six years of service. Elmer enjoyed L.A. so much that, when it came time to be 
transferred out, he decided to take an early retirement instead.<P>

<P>With  his international dining experience, Elmer was hired to write a Sunday restaurant review column that lasted four 
years with the former Los Angeles Herald Examiner. In 1970, the column provided him with the opportunity  to audition for a 
radio show on KABC Talkradio. Today, his program is one of the longest running and most popular programs on the station. In 
1977, Elmer transitioned into TV where he began restaurant reviews for KHJ-TV (Channel 9). After a year, he moved to KABC-TV 
Eyewitness News, where he has been ever since.<P>

<P>Two years ago, he married Lynn,  his long-time sweetheart. The two live in Pasadena. In 
addition, Elmer's family includes four grown children from his previous marriage.<P>
<P>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><P>
<P>
<P>

<CENTER>
<map name="KMPC">
<area shape="rect" coords="1,0 45,25"    href="../home.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="46,0 90,25"   href="NF.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="91,0 135,25"  href="home.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="136,0 217,25" href="../WhatsNew/home.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="218,0 258,25" href="../Bios/home.htm">
<area shape="rect" coords="259,1 419,25" href="../SendEmail/home.htm">
<area shape="default" nohref>
</map>
<A HREF="home.map"><IMG SRC=../gifs/buttonbar.gif USEMAP="#KMPC" BORDER=0 ISMAP HSPACE=20 ALIGN=center VALIGN=BOTTOM></A>
</CENTER>


<P>
