<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Deralee Scanlon
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="AA0000" VLINK="BBBB00">
<BR><IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="white.gif"><BR>



<TABLE  BORDER=2 WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=10  CELLPADDING=8>
	<TR>
     <TD><IMG  WIDTH=167  HEIGHT=115  SRC="710talk4.gif"></TD>

     <TD  ALIGN=LEFT  WIDTH=75% >
		<H1>NORM FOX

</H1>

<FONT SIZE=5>"Traveling with Norm Fox"<BR>
Sunday 8 - 10 p.m.</FONT></TD>
	</TR>
<CENTER></TABLE>

<BR><IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=70% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=0>

<TD>Born in Denver, Fox became smitten with travel at an early age when his parents took him and his 
three siblings on long auto trips throughout most of the United States and Canada.  After 
graduating from Harvard and the Columbia Graduate School of Business, Fox attended the London 
School of Economics and Political Science.  He believes that it was during his term breaks in 
London that he truly developed his passion for traveling with extended trips throughout Europe, 
the Middle East and North Africa.<P>

        Returning to New York City, Fox entered the advertising agency business working on 
Proctor and Gamble, Gillette, Miles Laboratories and ARCO products for several large agencies.  
During this time he traveled extensively throughout the United States to test market new 
products, and because of his fluency in French, he also produced commercials for the French 
Canadian market in Montreal.<P>

When the ARCO account was transferred to the corporation's new Los Angeles headquarters, Fox 
moved to Southern California.  The following year, he was hired to write advertising copy for 
Universal Television, and he soon became an associate producer and writer for episodic 
television.  Among his television credits, Fox was head writer for the "Quiz Kids Challenge," 
won a best writer award for "Cagney & Lacey," a Humanities Award writing nomination for "Fame," 
and helped produce the NBC television movies, "Brave New World" and "Tailgunner Joe."<P>

While writing and producing television, Fox began writing travel columns for LOS ANGELES MAGAZINE
 where he eventually became a Contributing Editor.  He subsequently wrote free-lance articles on 
travel, food and wine for TRAVEL & LEISURE, FOOD & WINE, BON APPETIT, and PLEASURES OF JAPAN.  
Two years later, Fox became a syndicated travel columnist with the Copley News Service with two 
weekly columns in four hundred newspapers nationwide with six million readers.  In addition, he 
also writes food and travel columns for THE HOLLYWOOD REPORTER and is the Travel and Restaurant 
Editor for PERFORMING ARTS MAGAZINE.<P>

In 1984, Fox wrote "THE TRIVIA CHALLENGE," published by Simon & Schuster, which was cited as a 
top  performing title of that year.  He also co-authored with Bobby Chandler, "VIOLENT SUNDAYS," 
an expose of professional football published by Simon & Schuster.  In 1991, Fox co-authored with 
Steve and Pat Zifferblatt, "THE BETTER LIFE INSTITUTE FAMILY HEALTH PLAN," published by Thomas 
Nelson and translated for distribution throughout the world.<P>

Seeking a radio outlet for his accumulated travel expertise, Fox spent a year and a half hosting 
a call-in show, "Travel Talk" on KTMS-AM in Santa Barbara.   Concurrently, he also had a weekly 
feature,  "Traveling," on KCRW-TV in Los Angeles, one of the country's largest Public 
Broadcasting affiliates.  This led to his being hired in 1994 to host a two-hour weekly travel 
talk show on KMPC-AM in Los Angeles.<P>


</TD>
</TABLE></CENTER><P>
<P>

<BR><IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="white.gif"><BR>


