<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ROD LURIE
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="AA0000" VLINK="BBBB00">
<BR><IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="white.gif"><BR>



<TABLE  BORDER=2 WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=10  CELLPADDING=8>
	<TR>
     <TD><IMG  WIDTH=167  HEIGHT=115  SRC="710talk4.gif"></TD>

     <TD  ALIGN=LEFT  WIDTH=75% >
		<H1>ROD LURIE
</H1>

		<FONT SIZE=5>Saturday 8 a.m. - 10 a.m.<BR></FONT></TD>
	</TR>
<CENTER></TABLE>

<BR><IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=70% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=0>

<TD>


	<P>Rod Lurie is the popular film critic for 710 TALK / KMPC. Lurie was also the film 
critic, investigative reporter, and contributing editor to Los Angeles Magazine. He is the 
nation's only film critic to be (1) "Banned for Life" from a major studio; (2) almost divorced 
for trying to name his newborn son Ben-Hur; and (3) quoted in an advertisement for a Chuck 
Norris film.<P>

	<P>In his capacity as an investigative reporter on the entertainment industry, Lurie has 
been the subject of feature stories and segments on 60 Minutes, Entertainment Tonight, The Larry 
King Show, Nightline, Geraldo, the Jane Whitney Show, to name a few. Lurie was also "The Guy" on 
an episode of To Tell The Truth. For the record, Lurie was picked out by all the panelists, 
including Kitty Carlisle, who slept through the entire question and answer segment. Lurie also 
won prizes totaling $17,000 on Classic Concentration. But, that was when he was an unknown 
writer.<P>

	<P>Lurie, like most film critics, was educated at the United States Military Academy at 
West Point. He graduated in 1984. He served four years in the United States Army as a Combat 
Arms officer and is currently (God help us all) a Captain in the reserves. <P>

	<P>He worked as an entertainment reporter for the New York Daily News and was the film 
critic and celebrity interviewer for Channel 12 in Connecticut. He was also a frequent 
contributor to Premiere, Movieline, and Entertainment Weekly Magazines.<P>

	<P>Rod began writing film criticism for Los Angeles Magazine in 1991. However, Lurie's 
primary acclaim has come for his investigative pieces. His look into the unethical and illegal 
practices of the tabloid newspapers, gained national attention, including a piece by the 
top-rated 60 Minutes.<P>

	<P>Lurie's investigative book Once Upon a Time in Hollywood was published in May, 1995 by 
Random House and is currently available in bookstores across the country. The book has been 
optioned to be made into a major motion picture.<P>

	<P>Currently, Lurie is directing his first feature length film titled "Porkchop," which is 
based on a screenplay he wrote. Lurie lives in Pasadena, California with his wife Gretchen, and 
their children Hunter and Paige.<P>

</TD>
</TABLE></CENTER><P>
<P>
<P>


