<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>PAXTON QUIGLEY
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="AA0000" VLINK="BBBB00">
<BR><IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="white.gif"><BR>



<TABLE  BORDER=2 WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=10  CELLPADDING=8>
	<TR>
     <TD><IMG  WIDTH=167  HEIGHT=115  SRC="710talk4.gif"></TD>

     <TD  ALIGN=LEFT  WIDTH=75% >
		<H1>PAXTON QUIGLEY
</H1>

		<FONT SIZE=5>Sundays<BR> 7 to 8 p.m.</FONT></TD>
	</TR>
<CENTER></TABLE>

<BR><IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=70% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=0>

<TD>
<P>          Ten years ago, when a friend was accosted and viciously raped,
Paxton Quigley, a divorced mother of two with a Masters in Anthropology
from the University of Chicago, decided not to let it happen to her.<P>  

<P>          Her quest for personal security has transformed her into a national
authority on personal protection strategies including the use of a handgun.
Tom Browkaw on NBC Nightly News, called her "guru" to eleven million women.
Morely Safer on 60 Minutes saw her as "the great persuader."<P>  

<P>          Espousing the essence of the popular Des'ree song: You got to be
bold. You got to be stronger and wiser, the pert Chicago-born Quigley has
taught thousands of women in her "Women's Empowerment in the 90's"
seminars, how not to become victims, through training, awareness and
preparation.<P>  

<P>          A spirited fusion of mid-western conservatism and enlightened
feminism, empowermentor Quigley enthusiastically advocates that women step
out of character, abandon age-old bonds of male-dependence and free
themselves from the cycle of fear and despair that has plagued them from
time immemorial.<P>  

<P>          Author of the best selling ARMED AND FEMALE (E.P. Dutton and St.
Martins Press) and NOT AN EASY TARGET (Simon & Schuster), Quigley has
appeared on more than 300 TV and radio shows including "The Today Show,"
"Good Morning America," "Larry King," "Montel Williams," "Regis and Kathy
Lee," "Hard Copy," "The NBC Nightly News with Tom Brokaw" and "60 
Minutes."<P>  

<P>          Her recent week-long hosting of the top-rated, nationally
syndicated Ken Hamblin radio show extended her message of personal reliance
and responsibility in an increasingly violent society to millions of
concerned women, as well as the men who love and care about them. As of
March 1996, she's doing the same weekly via L.A.'s 710 TALK / KMPC on the
Paxton Quigley Empowerment Hour.<P>  

<P>          The subject of front page profiles in both the Wall Street Journal
and Investors Business Daily, Quigley has also been featured in Elle,
Glamour, Cosmopolitan, People, Harpers Bazaar, Entrepreneur, Ladies Home
Journal and MS, and widely quoted in America's leading newspapers. Her
"poster girl" ad for Working Woman Magazine including the quote: "I didn't
get where I am today reading Good Housekeeping," received the Ad Week award
as one of the ten best advertisement campaigns of 1994.<P>  

<P>          Quigley was also the featured guest speaker at the 1991 U.S.
Congressional Sportsmen Caucus in Washington D.C., won the Outstanding
Public Service Award of the California Rifle and Pistol Association, and
was recently voted "Most Popular Speaker" by L.A.'s Women in Management.<P>  

<P>          Organizations that have relied on Quigley's expertise include: The
National Congress of the National Safety Council, the Los Angeles Dept. of
Water and Power, the Young President's Organization, Sarah Lawrence
College, Westec Security, the Beverly Hills Real Estate Board, the
Hillcrest Country Club, Los Angeles Women in Business, Prudential Reality,
Cedars Sinai Hospital and the City of Hope.<P>  

<P>          Prior to her work in personal security and empowerment, Quigley was
an executive with Playboy Enterprises, reporting directly to Christie
Hefner, President and CEO. She also served as Director of Promotions for
the Jimmy Stewart National Relay Marathon, and edited the Valley Magazine,
in San Fernando Valley, California.<P>  

<P>        Paxton Quigley enjoys going at it with gusto at the broad range of
daily issues that challenge women as they prepare for the onrushing 21st
Century. Who better to spread the message of empowerment than someone who
has done it for herself.<P>  

<P>

</TD>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<BR><IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="white.gif"><BR>


