<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ROD'S BEST MOVIE-RELATED HOLIDAY GIFT BUYS</TITLE>
</HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="AA0000" VLINK="BBBB00">
<BR>
<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=90% CELLSPACING=10  CELLPADDING=8>
<TR>
<TD>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="ff0000">ROD'S BEST MOVIE-RELATED <FONT COLOR="00ff00">HOLIDAY</FONT> GIFT BUYS</FONT></CENTER>


<P>Okay, gang- Christmas- Hanukkah - time to reach in your pockets and buy gifts for those that you love and those that you 
need to suck up to.  There is only one kind of gift-getter on my list: The movie lover.  If they are not one now, they will 
be when I get through with them.   The following are gift ideas for the movie aficionado. These are unsolicited by the 
merchants mentioned and  are not, in any way, a form of paid advertisement. As a result, you may see a valley influence to 
my list because I reside in Pasadena. If you have any ideas of your own, e-mail me from the menu-bar below or call into my 
show (remember. Saturdays from 8-10AM).<P><P>

<OL>
<LI> Scripts. C'mon. Think of a cooler idea than this.  Let's say that you have a friend who is a freak about, oh, say, "All 
The President's Men." You can get him the movie, but he or she probably already has it. Why not go and purchase the original 
script? At Book City in Burbank, they have a quizillion scripts. What makes them fun is that they are rarely the exact 
shooting script. This means that they often include scenes that were omitted from the film. Check out, for example, the 
170+ page script of "Rain Man" or Stallone's original "Rocky."  Great stuff and not too expensive. You can reach the folks 
at Book City at 818-577-7035<P><P>


<LI> Laser Discs. I have said it before and I will say it again.  Video is a tool of the devil. The sound sucks. The films are 
rarely in wide-screen (and thus the dreaded pan and scan). There is a general lack of crispness to the images. Laser disc 
solves all these problems in one final swoop.  Discs are more expensive to buy than videos (although they can often be 
rented for less), but the good news is that a used laser is often as good as a brand new one.  For the best prices on used 
DISCS I would go down to the Laser Library in Pasadena. Their number is  818-577-7035<P><P>

For the record, here are the twenty-five discs I would most recommend you purchase. They are in no particular order.<P>
<OL>
<LI> ET- Special edition
<LI> Terminator 2- Special edition
<LI> Ben-Hur- Special edition
<LI> Top Gun
<LI> Lawrence of Arabia - Criterion version
<LI> Star Wars threesome- Image's latest version
<LI> Toy Story
<LI> Lion King- Special edition
<LI> Amadeus- Special edition
<LI> Taxi Driver- Criterion
<LI> Last Tango in Paris- Criterion
<LI> Last Picture Show- Criterion
<LI> 2001: A Space Odyssey- 25th anniversary edition
<LI> Braveheart
<LI> Pulp Fiction- Criterion
<LI> Beatles Anthology
<LI> Young Frankenstein- new Special edition
<LI> Scarface- Special edition
<LI> Natural Born Killers- special edition
<LI> Platoon- special edition (box set)
<LI> Schindler's List- box set
<LI> Murder in the First
<LI> All the President's Men
<LI> The Day the Earth Stood Still- autographed box set
<LI>  They Shoot Horses Don't They- autographed box set
</OL>

<BR><BR>

<LI> Laser disc players. If you can afford a VCR you can afford one of these. There are great prices at Dave's in North 
Hollywood.  They can be reached at  818-760-3472<P><P>


<LI> There are a number of new film books I would recommend strongly:  First, there is "Toxic Fame," maybe the best film 
interview compilation book I have ever come across. It certainly has the widest variety of celebrities ever to make it 
between any two covers. Dynamite stuff and fab bedside reading.  Next,  Roger Ebert's Book of Film is a collection of 
film-related essays. At times cute and fun and at other times serious and esoteric. Never boring. The Rolling Stone Film 
Reader has tons of great interviews and set pieces from the renegade magazine. The Bill Zehme interview with Warren Beatty 
is a classic.  I also recommend: "The Making of Blade Runner," "The Kennedys in Hollywood" (for good Camelot gossip), 
"Stone," and "David  Lean."<P><P>
</OL>

</TD>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>

</CENTER>
</FONT>



