<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>QUESTIONS FOR THE MOVIE GEEK-GOD
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="AA0000" VLINK="BBBB00">
<BR>
<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=10  CELLPADDING=8>
<TR>
<TD><IMG  WIDTH=167  HEIGHT=115  SRC="../Bios/710talk4.gif"></TD>
<TD><H3>QUESTIONS FOR THE MOVIE GEEK-GOD</H3></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif">

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=80% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>

<TR><TD>



<P><B>"I have often heard the notion that a picture cannot win the best picture award without it's director winning. But what 
about the screenplay? Isn't that just as important?"</B>  <I>CJ- Hermosa Beach</I>
<P>
<P>That's a great question. I also believe that the writer is too often ignored in ever element of the Hollywood press 
game. However, the simple fact is that some very well written films simply do not translate to visually exciting 
entertainment. This is often true of stage plays that transfer to screen. "Marvin's Room," while a competent film, simply 
does not have the emotional fireworks it had on screen (while Arthur Miller sufficiently opened up 'The Crucible" to make 
it an exhilarating thunderclap of a film). Another example? "Platoon" was a gorgeous bit of emotional film making. It 
certainly deserved it's Oscar for best picture. But it did not win the screenplay award- that went to the much sharper 
dialogue of "Hannah and her Sisters'  Then there is politics. In 1959 "Ben -Hur" won eleven of twelve Oscars. It's only loss 
was for it's screenplay, which was mired in a union arbitration.
<P>
<P><B>You talk a great deal about laser discs and the laser disc player, but won't DVD make it obsolete?</B>  <I>TR- Glendale</I>
<P>
<P>I don't think so.  First of all, it will take years and years for the studios to  be able to match lasers in terms of titles. Right now, there are 10,000 films on laser, many of them in special edition. Pioneer, Voyager, and Image all have contracts to create lasers well into the next century. There is also some concern about the quality of DVD which explains why it has been so often delayed. 


<P>
<CENTER>E-mail me your questions via the menu bar below</CENTER>
<P>

</TD>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<P>
<map name="KMPC">
<area shape="rect" coords="1,0 45,25"    href="../home.htm">
