<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The BEST FILM OF 1996
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="AA0000" VLINK="BBBB00">
<BR>
<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=10  CELLPADDING=8>
<TR>
<TD><IMG  WIDTH=167  HEIGHT=115  SRC="../Bios/710talk4.gif"></TD>
<TD><H3>THE BEST FILM OF 1996</H3></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif">

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=80% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>

<TR><TD>


<P>It is simplest to put it this way. "Sling Blade" is a masterpiece.  Billy Bob Thornton, it's star, writer, and director, is not only a major find, he may be, if this film is the barometer,  the most compelling all consuming creative force in  American  movies since Orson Welles. I know that this seems like hyperbole. I know. I know.  But I challenge you to see the film and come back to me with any other example wherein one man  has achieved so much, with such a sure hand, across the board.
<P>
<P>"Sling Blade" deals with a mentally ill man who is released from a state institution where he had been held for almost thirty years for having killed his mother and her boyfriend with a sling blade. The doctors say he's fine and that he must be released. Big new world out there. Go get it. Only thing is, he's not fine. We know it and Carl knows it and very probably the doctors know it. And so a sense of doom creeps like a virus throughout the film.  But, oddly, the tension in the film is created through a sense of relaxation. Not much happens through most of "Sling Blade." There are no plot twists, no car chases, no sex.  But we know it  is coming. We're not sure what that it is, but it is there, and so we wait for it, our psyche starts to play games with us.
<P>
<P>There are many surprising performances in "Sling Blade". There is the country music star Dwight Yoakim as the abusive boyfriend of the mother of Carl's twelve year old best friend. John Ritter as the mother's gay best friend. Startling cameos by Robert DuVall and John Heard and Molly Ringwald. But at the top is the extraordinary work of  Thornton himself as Carl. 
<P>
<P>When you watch the film you might be reminded of Tom Hanks as Gump or Dustin Hoffman in "Rain Man" or one of the many actors who played Lenny in "Of Mice and Men."  But  as Karl, Thornton has created a viciously original character,  a  talk-only-when-talked-to simpleton who is driven by a peculiar decency. 
<P>
<P>In retrospect it seems to me that this is an amazing feat of directing. Thornton's Karl is one of the most inwardly drawn characters ever captured on screen, yet, somehow, as a director, Thornton was  able to keep a precise eye on his supporting cast.  This might have been especially difficult with a non actor like Yoakim, who's swing between abusiveness and cowardice (often the two are mingled together) is nothing short of masterful.
<P>
<P>Unlike "Fargo" the film is not visually dazzling or even  visually interesting. The lighting is mediocre. There is not much editing to speak of given the multitude of one shots in the film.  What holds it together are these fully realize characters who make us, God help us, care what happens to them.  I cannot recommend this film more. It is the best film of the year and the most perfectly acted project since "All the President's Men."
<P>
</TD>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<P>
