<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>RODS TEN BEST ENGLISH LANGUAGE FILMS OF ALL TIME
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="AA0000" VLINK="BBBB00">
<BR>
<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=10  CELLPADDING=8>
<TR>
<TD><IMG  WIDTH=167  HEIGHT=115  SRC="../Bios/710talk4.gif"></TD>
<TD><H4>ROD'S TEN BEST ENGLISH LANGUAGE FILMS OF ALL TIME</H4></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif">


<CENTER>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=80% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>
<TR><TD>
<P>Okay, I am asked this time and time again. So, finally, I'll put my opinions on paper, or the 
airwaves, or cyberspace - my list of the ten best English language films. I have revealed your
favorite movies on <A HREF="list.htm">this page</A>.

<P>E-mail me through this web site with YOUR ten best films of all time. Rank them in order. We 
will tabulate and give the results to you on an on-going basis. In the meantime, here's my picks, in 
rank order:
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>
1. <STRONG>"All the President's Men"</STRONG> - We all know the story, but what a thriller it was nonetheless. 
Redford, Hoffman, and Robards were the quintessence of acting, solid and understated performances 
that did not lapse into one iota of hysteria or broadness. William Goldman's screenplay is a 
textbook of adapting a complicated book.
</TR></TD>

<TR><TD>
2. <STRONG>"Paths of Glory"</STRONG> - There has never been as serene or horrifying a testament against war and 
the expectations of man's limits at Kubrick's elegant masterpiece. Kirk Douglas at his very, very 
best.<BR>
2a. <STRONG>"The Killing,"</STRONG> also by Kubrick.
</TR></TD>

<TR><TD>
3. <STRONG>"Raging Bull"</STRONG> - De Niro in maybe the greatest performance of all time. Never has cruelty been 
packaged in so magnificent a package as it was by Martin Scorcese. The finest editing (Thelma 
Schoonmaker) in the history of film.<BR>
3a. <STRONG>"Taxi Driver"</STRONG> - Scorcese's bold and frightening elegy.<BR>
3b. <STRONG>"Rocky"</STRONG> - Boxing becomes sweet and tender.
</TR></TD>

<TR><TD>
4. <STRONG>"Midnight Cowboy"</STRONG> - The only X-rated film to win the Oscar. Jon Voight's performance as a 
street hustler and Dustin Hoffman as his crippled, pathetic pimp was a tragedy of almost a 
Shakesperean order.
</TR></TD>

<TR><TD>
5. <STRONG>"Platoon"</STRONG> and <STRONG>"Born on the Fourth of July"</STRONG> - Oliver Stone's films have to be seen one after 
another to get the full impact. The latter features a performance by Tom Cruise that seems almost 
divine. Never has an adult played a teen so well. Brilliant and moving. The only film that ever 
provoked full out tears from me.<BR>
5a. <STRONG>"JFK"</STRONG>  - As politically astute as it was or wasn't, was a magnificent advance in cinema style.
</TR></TD>

<TR><TD>
6. <STRONG>"The Godfather"</STRONG> - A film that violates all the rules of modern film making, yet still slick 
and fast  - one of the most violent yet poetic films of our time.<BR> 
6a. Okay, <STRONG>"The Godfather II."</STRONG><BR>
6b. While we are on the subject of Coppola - <STRONG>"Apocalypse Now."</STRONG>
</TR></TD>

<TR><TD>
7. <STRONG>"Pulp Fiction"</STRONG> - The most important American film since "Nashville" - in terms of it's 
inventive narrative structure. Travolta made his come back. That makes it good enough for me.<BR>
7a. <STRONG>"The Taking of Pelham One, Two, Three"</STRONG> - a film that Tarantino acknowledges ripping off.<BR>
7b. Since we brought it up - <STRONG>"Nashville."</STRONG>
</TR></TD>

<TR><TD>
8. <STRONG>"Lawrence of Arabia"</STRONG> - Peter O'Toole yelling "Aquaba! Aquaba!" Enough said.<BR>
8a. <STRONG>"The Bridge on the River Kwai."</STRONG>
</TR></TD>

<TR><TD>
9. <STRONG>"Braveheart"</STRONG> - For the finest and most heart-stopping battle scenes ever filmed.<BR>
9a. For the thrill of it - <STRONG>"The Road Warrior."</STRONG>
</TR></TD>

<TR><TD>
10. <STRONG>"E.T."</STRONG>  - This is the "Wizard of Oz" of my generation, with the best little boy performance ever.<BR>
10a. <STRONG>"Schindler's List"</STRONG> - For the other side of the Spielberg coin<BR>
10b. That also applies to <STRONG>"Jaws."</STRONG>
</TR></TD>

<TR><TD>
Okay, e-mail with your picks and thoughts! <A HREF="../SendEmail/home.cgi?Rod_Lurie">Click here to be linked to the KMPC e-mail section.</A>
</TR></TD>

</TD>
</TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
