<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ROD'S TEN BEST FILMS OF 1996
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="AA0000" VLINK="BBBB00">


<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=10  CELLPADDING=8>
<TR>
<TD><IMG  WIDTH=167  HEIGHT=115  SRC="../Bios/710talk4.gif"></TD>
<TD><CENTER><FONT SIZE=4>ROD'S TEN BEST FILMS OF 1996</FONT></CENTER></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>


<BR><BR>

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=80% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>
<TR><TD>
<OL>
<LI> <STRONG>SLING BLADE</STRONG> -  This voracious  directorial debut, made on a budget of less
than one million dollars,  marks the greatest confluence of talent since
Orson Welles' "Citizen Kane." Billy Bob Thornton, as an actor, writer, and
director, has created a shattering and tragic film character in the retarded
Karl.
<BR><BR>
<LI> <STRONG>THE CRUCIBLE/THE ENGLISH PATIENT</STRONG> - A tie. It took Arthur Miller himself to
"open" up his classic play.  What was once an allegory to the McCarthy
 hearings is now a cautionary tale against any kind of social or political
judgementality.  With gorgeous performances by Daniel Day-Lewis, Paul
Scofield, Winona Ryder, Joan Allen, and Bruce Davison.  The flip side of "The
Crucible" deals with forbidden love, which is the hallmark of Anthony
Minghella's "The English Patient." Some may be disturbed by romantacizing
infidelity, but Ralph Fiennes and Kristin Scott-Thomas are so searing that we
give a damn about them anyway.  At $20 million, there has never been a
greater visual  bang for the buck.
<BR><BR>
<LI> <STRONG>FARGO </STRONG> - The Coen Brothers at their most macabre and, since "Blood Simple"
anyway, their most fun. Never has so much art been made out of blankets of
snow.
<BR><BR>
<LI> <STRONG>LA HAINE </STRONG>- The shocking and tragic black and white French tale of disturbed
youth. At least the French are as messed up as we are.
<BR><BR>
<LI> <STRONG>THE PEOPLE VERSUS LARRY FLYNT </STRONG>- Milos Forman, who lived under iron curtain
oppression,  has made one of the classic filmic essays on the wisdom of the
Constitution. Woody Harrelson and Courtney Love are in brilliant form and
newcomer Edward Norton is Dustin Hoffman waiting to happen.
<BR><BR>
<LI> <STRONG>WHEN WE WERE KINGS </STRONG>- A documentary about the Ali-Foreman fight in Zaire.
Taylor Hackford's non-narrated film is really an examination about the power
of charisma.
<BR><BR>
<LI>  <STRONG>HAMLET </STRONG>- Kenneth Branagh continues to seek higher office. In this grand
70mm adaptation of le bard, we are sucked into the anguished world of the
great Dane prince with more sheer visionary power than ever before.
<BR><BR>
<LI>  <STRONG>SOME MOTHER'S SON </STRONG>- This year's great political thriller and, to boot, a
true story. On it's face, the epic  and tragic battle waged by Bobby Sands
seems to be a great natural for film. But to tell it from his mother's point
of view and bestow that role on the great Helen Mirren is  nothing short of
brilliant.
<BR><BR>
<LI>  <STRONG>BOUND </STRONG> - It's enough that two beautiful are going at it and ..... oops,
let's put the testosterone on hold there. This is a film of, all puns aside,
boundless good fun and energy, with more twists than chubby Checker on
amphetamines.
<BR><BR>
<LI> THE SUBSTANCE OF FIRE </STRONG> -  "Shine" has won all the domineering Jewish father
accolades this year, but shocking overlooked is this remarkable tale of a
publishing house about to go under because of one man's unhealthy obsession
with his tragic past. Ron Rifkin in a performance of grace and elegance and
sheer horror.
</OL>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<STRONG>BEST ACTORS-</STRONG>
<UL>
<LI>BILLY BOB THORNTON IN "SLING BLADE"
<LI>Denzel Washington in "Courage Under Fire"
<LI>Daniel Day Lewis in "The Crucible"
<LI>James Woods in "The Ghosts of Mississippi"
<LI>Paul Scofield in "The Crucible"
<LI>Kenneth Branagh in "Hamlet"
<LI>Woody Harrelson in "The People Versus Larry Flynt"
<LI>Ed Norton in  "Primal Fear"
<LI>Ed Norton in "The People Versus Larry Flynt"
<LI>Dwight Yoakim in "Sling Blade"
<LI>Martin Sheen- "The War at Home"
<LI>Ron Rifkin in "The Substance of Fire"
</UL>
</TD>

<TD>
<STRONG>BEST ACTRESSES-</STRONG>
<UL>
<LI>Kathy Bates- "The War at Home"
<LI>Diane Keaton- "Marvin's Room"
<LI>Meryl Streep- "Marvin's Room"
<LI>Julliette Lewis- "The Evening Star"
<LI>Natalie Portman- "Beautiful Girls'
<LI>Uma Thurman- "Beautiful Girls"
<LI>Joan Allen- "The Crucible"
<LI>Winona Ryder- "The Crucible"
<LI>Frances McDormand- "Fargo"
<LI>Courtney Love- "The People Versus Larry Flynt"
</UL>
</TD>
</TABLE>


</OL>
</TD>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>

