<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ROD LURIE'S LASER DISC PICK OF THE WEEK
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=ffffff LINK="#0c8c8c" VLINK="#718e8a">

<BR>
<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=5  CELLPADDING=5>
<TR>
<TD><IMG  WIDTH=167  HEIGHT=115  SRC="../Bios/710talk4.gif"></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE=4><STRONG>ROD LURIE'S LASER DISC PICK OF THE WEEK</STRONG></FONT><BR>
<IMG  WIDTH=380  HEIGHT=2  Align=Left  SRC="../gifs/redBar.1.gif">
<BR>

<TABLE ALIGN=center BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=5>
<TR>




<TD>
<A HREF="#sept14">September 14, 1996</A><BR>
<A HREF="#august17">August 17, 1996</A><BR>
<A HREF="#august3">August 3, 1996</A><BR>
<A HREF="#july20">July 20, 1996</A><BR>
</TD>

<TD>

<A HREF="#july6"> July 6, 1996</A><BR>
<A HREF="#june29">June 29, 1996</A><BR>
<A HREF="#june22">June 22, 1996</A><BR>
<BR>
</TD>

<TD VALIGN=TOP>

<A HREF="#june15">June 15, 1996</A><BR>
<A HREF="#june8"> June 8, 1996</A><BR>
<A HREF="#june1"> June 1, 1996</A><BR>
<BR>
</TD>

</TD></TR></TABLE>


</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
<TD  WIDTH=1% ALIGN=LEFT><IMG SRC="../gifs/redStripe.1.gif" WIDTH="2" HEIGHT="320"></TD>
<TD>
<A NAME="sept14">September 14, 1996</A>
<P>SCARFACE-  Yup, we're talking about the Brian De Palma remake of the 
classic gangster film starring Paul Muni.  The 1983 film was reviled 
when it came out, with critics attacking it's flamboyance and 
exorbitant violence. One scene in particular, in which Colombian drug 
dealers start to cut up a rival with a chainsaw, almost gave the film 
an X-rating.  It may be fair to say that there  is no film in the 
eighties that has undergone so much critical revisionism than 
"Scarface," which is now being hailed by critics as an almost 
"Godfather"-like study of the modern drug world. Me? I've always been 
a fan of the film, especially Michelle Pfeiffer's great and sexy 
entrance.  Universal's new "signature" edition of the film is aces, 
with a near perfect transfer and some wonderfully entertaining 
outtakes (although you can understand - from a story structure point 
of view- why De Palma removed them).  Most enjoyable, however, are the 
interviews at the end of the film - with De Palma and a wonderfully 
galvanized Pacino.<P>
</TR></TD>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG  WIDTH=450  HEIGHT=2  Align=center  SRC="../gifs/redBar.1.gif"></CENTER>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>


<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
<TD  WIDTH=1% ALIGN=LEFT><IMG SRC="../gifs/redStripe.1.gif" WIDTH="2" HEIGHT="320"></TD>
<TD>
<A NAME="august17">August 17, 1996</A>
<P>Early in his Presidency, John Kennedy declared his love for the James Bond novels, setting off  
a frenzy sales for the already popular books written bu Ian Fleming.  This mania clearly 
translated itself to the screen, first with "Dr. No' then "From Russia with Love," and, perhaps 
at it's zenith with "Goldfinger."<P>

<P>There have been about six different pressings of the film, regarded by many as the 
quintessential Bond film,  but none more impressive than Image's box set.  For one thing, the 
film is in CAV, a crisper format that I personally love. I'm a nut about freeze-framing and took 
delight in stopping the film cold when we see the "gold lady" or the great laser beam sequence 
("No, Mr Bond, I expect you to die").  Then there are the Behind-the scenes footage, a 
documentary about "Goldfingermania," and interview with Sean Connery, and even an hysterical 
screen test that the Israeli singer Theodore Bikel gave as Goldfinger himself.  For more info, 
go to <A HREF="http://www.image-entertainment.com">www.image-entertainment.com </A>   <P>
</TR></TD>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>



<P>
<CENTER><IMG  WIDTH=450  HEIGHT=2  Align=center  SRC="../gifs/redBar.1.gif"></CENTER>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
<TD  WIDTH=1% ALIGN=LEFT><IMG SRC="../gifs/redStripe.1.gif" WIDTH="2" HEIGHT="320"></TD>
<TD>
<A NAME="august3">August 3, 1996</A>

<P>When "Natural Born Killers" opened two summers ago I was in the front
line of critics who despised the film, dismissed it as the ultimate
act of cinema overindulgence.  It wasn't that I "didn't get" what
Stone was trying to say about the carniverous strength of the media,
but that I got it all to clearly. After two plus hours, my head was a
bashed in mush.  After seeing the film on CAV Laser disc my opinion
hasn't changed. What warrants this film to be a  Pick of the Week  is
Stone's cerebral analog track.  After all, this is a man who has
created some of the greatest cinema of the modern era and he deserves
his say.  It's fascinating to see some of the footage that the MPAA
banned from the "R" rated footage, including a graphic rape scene and
an extended prison riot sequence. With this disc, Stone has his clear
day in court.  There is also a wonderful series of interviews with
Stone and his stars Woody Harrelson, Juliette Lewis, Tommy Lee Jones,
Tom Sizemore, and Robert Downey Jr..  Love it or, as I did, hate it,
"NBK" is nonetheless a MUST for Stone fans.
<P>
</TR></TD>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG  WIDTH=450  HEIGHT=2  Align=center  SRC="../gifs/redBar.1.gif"></CENTER>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
<TD  WIDTH=1% ALIGN=LEFT><IMG SRC="../gifs/redStripe.1.gif" WIDTH="2" HEIGHT="300"></TD>
<TD>
<A NAME="july20">July 20, 1996</A>

<P>Any real fan of "Pulp Fiction," and there are a ton of us out there, has to - has to, has to, 
has to - own the Criterion laser disc special edition. Even if you don't own a laser disc 
player, you should get it just for show. Going over the film's essential plot elements seems 
superfluous here and so I'll divigate away from that. What's important to know about the special 
collection is that it has four deleted scenes - one of which should have stayed in the film. 
(You watch them and guess which one I am talking about). You have much of the standard laser 
special stuff - the posters from around the world, the various trailers and commercial spots - 
but the most fun exists in the hour long interview between Tarantino and the interviewer Charlie 
Rose. I'm not sure (e-mail if I am wrong on this) that any other disc has this level of film 
maker interview. For more info go to www.voyagerco.com
<P>
</TR></TD>
</TABLE></CENTER>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG  WIDTH=450  HEIGHT=2  Align=center  SRC="../gifs/redBar.1.gif"></CENTER>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
<TD  WIDTH=1% ALIGN=LEFT><IMG SRC="../gifs/redStripe.1.gif" WIDTH="2" HEIGHT="250"></TD>
<TD>
<A NAME="july6">July 6, 1996</A>

<P>Oliver Stone's  "Platoon" is an outright  masterpiece, one of the great
studies of war and the submergence of the human soul ever recorded. It's on
my ten best of all time list. Pioneer's special edition of the film is one of
the great laser discs available. There is, above  anything else, save for the
movie itself, the analog track, in which Stone takes us  through the film
step by step, image by image. metaphor by metaphor. Captain Dale Dye, the
projects military adviser, does the same.  The package also comes with not
only Stone's script (he unfail lost the Oscar that year - in this category
only - to Woody Allen for "Hannah and her sisters." ) but a documentary about
the casting, making, and aftermath of this most magnificent effort.  For
extra info go to <A HREF="http://www.pioneer-ent.com">www.pioneer-ent.com</A></P>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>


<P>
<CENTER><IMG  WIDTH=450  HEIGHT=2  Align=center  SRC="../gifs/redBar.1.gif"></CENTER>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>


<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
<TD  WIDTH=1% ALIGN=LEFT><IMG SRC="../gifs/redStripe.1.gif" WIDTH="2" HEIGHT="250"></TD>
<TD>
<A NAME="june29">June 29, 1996</A>

<P>Marty Scorcese, who began his career as a screen minimalist, has certainly
become filmdom's most dynamic dazzlist. His films have a rip-roaring style
that go to a level which would be, with any OTHER director, wildly
over-the-top. "Casino" may be his most technically accomplished work. He's
working with most of the same team that turned "Raging Bull" into such a
phenomenal piece of work. With this amazing transfer, you can hear every
clink of the dice, every rattling of a chip. It's also fun to move frame by
frame and analyze some of Marty's brilliant transitions from shot to shot.
In any case, bravo to any man who directs Sharon Stone to an Oscar
nomination. For more go to <A HREF="http://www.mcauniversalhomevideo.com">www.mcauniversalhomevideo.com</A>
<P>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>


<P>
<CENTER><IMG  WIDTH=450  HEIGHT=2  Align=center  SRC="../gifs/redBar.1.gif"></CENTER>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>

<TR>
<TD  WIDTH=1% ALIGN=LEFT><IMG SRC="../gifs/redStripe.1.gif" WIDTH="2" HEIGHT="300"></TD>
<TD>
<A NAME="june22">June 22, 1996</A>

	<P>The beauty of "<A HREF="http://www.mgmua.com/getshorty">Get Shorty</A>" was in the performance of John Travolta as Chili Palmer, 
the hitman/collector for the mob who becomes enamored (aren't we all) with Hollywood. Has there 
ever been an actor who has had a better time on screen than Travolta? I think not. He was denied 
an Oscar nomination for the film, probably because he insisted on being paid $20 million and one 
dollar for his latest film -  which many people considered an act of outright arrogance. 
Nevertheless, it's a performance worthy of that honor.
<P>
	<P>The beauty of this pristine laserdisc comes in both the analog track (featuring director Barry Sonenfeld) 
and the inclusion of a deleted scene from the film. It shows us Gene Hackman at work on a movie 
set, working with director Ben Stiller. It's fun and witty and puts the entire film in a better 
perspective.

</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG  WIDTH=450  HEIGHT=2  Align=center  SRC="../gifs/redBar.1.gif"></CENTER>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
<TD  WIDTH=1% ALIGN=LEFT><IMG SRC="../gifs/redStripe.1.gif" WIDTH="2" HEIGHT="350"></TD>
<TD>
<A NAME="june15">June 15, 1996</A>

	<P>For years, audiences had been waiting for a handsome Brit to utter the words 
"Bond.... James Bond." They had waited even longer for it to be done with competence. "Lisence 
to Kill" and "The Living Daylights," those Bond films starring Timothy Dalton had been abysma 
failures. Now, however, all is well worth the world again. As Agent 007, Pierce Brosnan found 
himself somewhere inbetween the fierce masculine nobility of Sean Connery and the tongue in 
cheek style of Roger Moore. "Goldeneye" for the sheer thrill of it, is a must-see, with the best 
opening stunt since the sky-dive in "Moonraker."<P>

	<P>This laser disc is especilly fun. You not only get a gorgeous THX-master transfer of the 
film (movies like this, with explosions and noisy gadgets, are just made for laser), but 
wonderful extras: Every trailer put out by MGM, an hour long television special in honor of 
Bond, a dubbing of one scene in German, Italian, and French, and, for me this is the most fun, 
the video of the Tina Turner title song -  the best in the history of the Bond series.<P>
<P>

	You can get more info on the film by going to <A HREF="http://www.image-entertainment.com">www.image-entertainment.com</A>
<P>
	Have fun.
</TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG  WIDTH=450  HEIGHT=2  Align=center  SRC="../gifs/redBar.1.gif"></CENTER>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>

<TR>
<TD  WIDTH=1% ALIGN=LEFT><IMG SRC="../gifs/redStripe.1.gif" WIDTH="2" HEIGHT="350"></TD>
<TD>
<A NAME="june8">June 8, 1996</A>


<P>Steven Spielberg's "1941" was an immensely anticipated film. It was the brash young director's 
first project since "Close Encounters of the Third Kind" and, as importantly, John Belushi's 
first film since his triumphant debut in "Animal House."  Perhaps because the hype surrounding 
the film was overwhelming, "1941" was a critical and financial disaster.<P>

<P>Now, we have a chance to re-evaluate the film. MCA has re-mastered the comedy film (in the THX 
format) and included footage that never existed in the theatrical version of the film. Included 
in the box se are interviews, conducted only recently with the writers John Milius, Bob Gale, 
and Robert Zemeckis (yes, him) and Spielberg himself, who seems to have warmed to the project he 
has previously shown disdain for.<P>

<P>As is typical of the MCA Signature Collection, there are wonderful extras: The original trailers 
for the film, outtakes (which are genuinely hysterical), and the storyboards for the project. 
"1941" is a must for Spielberg aficionados.<P>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG  WIDTH=450  HEIGHT=2  Align=center  SRC="../gifs/redBar.1.gif"></CENTER>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
<TD  WIDTH=1% ALIGN=LEFT><IMG SRC="../gifs/redStripe.1.gif" WIDTH="2" HEIGHT="350"></TD>
<TD>
<A NAME="june1">June 1, 1996</A>

<P>David Fincher's "Seven" was nothing short of a phenom when it came out. If nothing else, it 
demonstrated what the essence of star power is all about - in particular, the apparently magnetic 
lure of Brad Pitt. I say this because the film itself was as dark as the backside of Pluto, with 
images and emotional violence as powerful as anything ever put on screen. The film was a visual 
tour de farce, with one of the most exciting land chases ever filmed.
<P>
<P>Criterion has just come out with a wonderful four box set which should satisfy even the most 
depraved among us. In addition to the brilliant transfer of the film, we also get analog 
commentary from Fincher. Included is the original first scene of the film. Though very well done, 
I can understand exactly why it was dropped: It does not suck you as quickly into the film as 
the actual start does. There is also an "alternate" credit sequence that was junked for the 
creepier version that was used in the film.
<P>
<P>I believe my favorite part of this disc set is the story board (you have to 'step' your way 
through) of the film's original ending... which I will not spoil for you here. If you have 
trouble finding the film, you can go to the Criterion Web Site at 
<A HREF="http://www.voyagerco.com/criterion.cgi">http://www.voyagerco.com/criterion.cgi</A>

</TR></TD>
</TABLE></CENTER>

