<HEAD>
<TITLE>ROD'S WEEKLY REVIEW
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="AA0000" VLINK="BBBB00">
<BR>
<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=10  CELLPADDING=8>
<TR>
<TD><IMG  WIDTH=167  HEIGHT=115  SRC="../Bios/710talk4.gif"></TD>
<TD><H3>ROD'S WEEKLY REVIEW</H3></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif">

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=80% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>

<TR><TD>

<B>ROD'S WEEKLY REVIEW: EVITA</B><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+3>B+  </FONT><BR>
<BR>
Starring: MADONNA, JONATHAN PRYCE, ANTONIO BANDERAS. <BR>
Directed by ALAN PARKER<BR>

<P>Would it  be fair  to describe "Evita" as the most anticipated film of the year?  probably.  Not because the film is abuzz with hyperbolic talk of it's quality or poetic resonance 	or because it is swallowing up the critics awards (it is not) , but because  it's arduous history has become the stuff of mini-Hollywood legend.  Audiences are either  expecting and wanting  a n "Annie-style disaster (inspired by a [popular anti-Madonna sweep in Hollywood) or a brazen new form of American musical cinema.  At the end, booth sides will be disappointed..
<P>
<P>Ever since the Andrew Lloyd Weber stage play won eight Tony awards, there have been attempts to make it into a major motion picture (it can only be a MAJOR motion picture, right?). Oliver Stone was one of the many directors attached to it as was Francis Ford Coppola.  As for the various Evita Perons? There was  Meryl Streep, Ann-Margret, Michelle Pfeiffer, and so on. Even when the current production, this one directed by Alan Parker and starring a pregnant Madonna,  went before the cameras in Argentina, all  social hell seemed to disrupt in that country.
<P>
<P>But, now here it is. Finally.  And you can practically see the sweat dripping from it with exhaustion. The film is big and bold and beautiful, huge and triumphant, and also a little bit out of control- like an elephant on fire.  With it's huge set and crowd pieces and with it's historical perspective, it is easy to see why so many directors were drawn to it.  I am not sure that there has ever been quite such an epic  musical ever created. What baffled me is why anybody was drawn to Alan Parker.  Sure, he has made a couple of successful semi-musicals ("Fame," Bugsy Malone," "The Commitments"). But for the most part his dramas have been crammed with wretched, almost obscene excess. Films like "Angel Heart" and "The Wall" are almost unwatchable.  But here, to his credit,  Parker seeks to entertain and not overwhelm.
<P>
<P>It is the entertainment factor that, in retrospect, makes  it seem that Madonna may well have been the best choice for the film.  If anything, the chick has  presence, which was the essence of Evita Peron.  As a critic I was yearning to laugh at her, standing on that balcony in the palace square, arms raised up in dictatorial triumph like  a Rose queen. But she embodies Peron so well, that we accept her  seriously and without a hint of pretension. Conversely, She is also a remarkable vocalist and it is impossible to concentrate on anything other than the instrument of her vocal chords when her mouth opens.
<P>
<P>But therein also lies the films problem. "Evita" is an opera, which basically means that we never hear a spoken word. The presents us with two problems. First, it is difficult to follow a definitive and, at times, politically complicated storyline. Two, the film has the look of a two hour and fifteen minute MTV video - though a robust one at that.  As such, the film, at that long length, will eventually lose your interest. You will gain almost as much simply listening to the CD as watching the film.

</TD>
</TABLE>




</CENTER>
