<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ROD'S BEST ENGLISH LANGUAGE FEMALE PERFORMANCES EVER
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="AA0000" VLINK="BBBB00">
<BR>
<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=10  CELLPADDING=8>
<TR>
<TD><IMG  WIDTH=167  HEIGHT=115  SRC="../Bios/710talk4.gif"></TD>
<TD><H4>ROD'S BEST ENGLISH LANGUAGE FEMALE PERFORMANCES EVER</H4></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif">

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=80% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>
<TR><TD>
<P>
     

<OL>

<LI>     <STRONG>Jodie Foster in "Taxi Driver" </STRONG> -  Okay, a shocker for my number one choice. It was, of course, a supporting role. But has ever such a small amount of screen time so haunted an audience. As the twelve year old hooker Iris, Foster was concurrently downtrodden  and a free-spirit. In this magical performance (some magic- Scorsese was guiding her), Foster displayed the talent for cracking the little ticks of human nature that has made her the pre-eminent realist actor of her generation and, maybe, ever.    -Oscar nomination
<P>
<P>1 (A) <STRONG> Foster in "The Accused" </STRONG> - Oscar winner<P>


<LI> 	<STRONG>Mimi Rogers in "The Rapture" </STRONG> -  The most sexually  daring performance since Marlon Brando's far more pretentious take in "Last Tango in Paris."  The role of the swinger turned religious zealot was passed on by actress after actress, until it finally landed square in Rogers' hands.  You'll have to wait until the end of the film to see why the role was so unpopular and, perhaps, why it failed at the box office.

<P>2(A) <STRONG> Rogers in "Bulletproof Heart" </STRONG><P>

<LI> 	<STRONG>Anne Bancroft in "The Graduate" </STRONG> - Mrs. Robinson has created what I am sure is a great ambivalence with Bancroft. On the one hand, it was a performance of historic importance,  certainly the one piece of work that propelled her into the highest echelon of actresses. On the other, she played the cold ice bitch with such pure calculation, that I am sure she finds herself in the odd position of being an intimidating and unapproachable presence in real life.

<P>3(A) <STRONG> Bancroft in "The Miracle Worker" </STRONG> - Oscar winner<P>



<LI> 	<STRONG>Diane Keaton in "Reds" </STRONG> -  If nothing else, Warren  Beatty knows how to direct other actors into sweeping, moving performances. As Louise Bryant, Keaton offered the odd duality of social rebel and devoted lover and wife.  Keaton was unfairly locked out of the Oscar because of the Academy's relentless umbilical cord relationship with Kate Hepburn who won for playing a geriatric in "On Golden Pond."

<P>4(A) <STRONG>Keaton in "Looking For Mr. Goodbar," "Annie Hall," and  "Marvin's Room" </STRONG><P>

<LI> 	<STRONG>Geena Davis in "Thelma and Louise" </STRONG> -  For her ferocious performance as a housewife turned into a gun-totting fugitive from the law, Geena Davis soared into the rarefied aeries of classic screendom. Why not Sarandon here? Simple. She was the chick with the "arc." It was her character that changed the more dramatically and, I might add, convincingly. - Oscar nomination

<P>5(A) <STRONG>Davis in "The Accidental Tourist" </STRONG> - Oscar winner<P>

<LI> 	<STRONG>Faye Dunaway in "Bonnie and Clyde" </STRONG> - Not since Vivien Leigh landed that part in GWTW has there been a more obvious, or more successful, star-creating vehicle. As Bonnie Parker, the sexually frustrated depression-era bank robber, Dunaway was sexy and brazenly dangerous at the same time

<P>6(A)- <STRONG>Dunaway in "Network" </STRONG><P>


</OL>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<br><br>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>Okay, E-mail me with your picks  FROM THE MENU BAR BELOW.
