<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ROD'S LISTENER ALL-TIME BEST MALE PERFORMANCES
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="AA0000" VLINK="BBBB00">
<BR>
<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=10  CELLPADDING=8>
<TR>
<TD><IMG  WIDTH=167  HEIGHT=115  SRC="../Bios/710talk4.gif"></TD>
<TD><H4>THE KMPC LISTENER ALL-TIME BEST MALE PERFORMANCES</H4></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif">

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=80% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>
<TR><TD>
<P>
     
Looking forward to your comments and disagreements. Send me Your ten best performances list at..........   And we'll compile a listener chart!
<p>

<OL>
<LI> <B><font size=+1> Morgan Freeman- Street Smart</font> </B>
<p>
Probably the least seen performance on the list, and maybe the most unexpected.  It is one of those rare beings, a perfect pearl in a banged-up, crusty clam.  In the lead role of an unethical reporter, Christopher Reeve gave an almost laughable performance.  But as the pimp Fast Black, Reeve's antagonist, Freeman soared.  Never has uneducated cool menace been so forcefully played on screen.   It is a difficult piece: How does one create a character that is supposed to scare an audience senseless yet come across as sufficiently seductive and charming that he might control women to the degree Fast Black does. It's a mystery to me. I guess that's why Freeman is the actor and I'm the writer.<p>

<b>Best scene</b>:  Fast Black threatening to blind the prostitute played by Kathy Baker.
<p>
<u>And  for that Matter:</u>
<p>
Morgan Freeman in "Glory," "The Shawshank Redemption" Eric Roberts in  "Star 80,"   James Woods in "Casino,"  Harvey Keitel in "Taxi Driver," Ben Gazzarra in "St. Jack"<p>

<br><br>

<LI> <b><font size=+1>Robert  DeNiro- Raging Bull</font></b>
<p>
Textbook great acting. Every portrayal of a boxer will be judged against this one. Every performance of a lost soul - of  a wife abuser - of a man losing control of his life- as well. De Niro's prep for his portrayal of Jake La Motta is now the meat of legends (his weight gain, his training), and it shows.  You can judge a great performance by monitoring if you can clearly imagine a character continuing on even after a scene has ended.  It's a rare feat, but De  Niro achieves it.<p>
<p>
<b>Best  Scene</b> -  Jake slowly going nuts when he begins to think that his brother Joey (Joe Pesci) might be keeping his wife's infidelities from him.
<p>
<u>And for that matter:</u>
<p>
De Niro in "The Godfather II,"  "The Deer Hunter,"  "Taxi Driver," "The King of Comedy"
Sylvester Stallone in "Rocky,"  Kirk Douglas in "Champion," Marlon Brando in "On the Waterfront."
<p>

<br><br>

<LI>  <b><font size=+1>Gregory Peck- To Kill a Mockingbird</font></b>
<p>
There has never been as essentially a dignified performance as this. As Atticus Finch,  Peck was the embodiment of dignity and respect without once teetering into self righteousness.  There is a sense of good in the world after watching "mockingbird" and it all stems from this Oscar-winning performance.<p>
<p>
Best Scene : The courtroom
<p>
<u>And for that matter:</u>
<p>
Gregory peck in "Gentleman's Agreement"
Paul Newman in "The Verdict,"  James Stewart in "Anatomy of a Murder"
<p>
<br><br>

<LI> <b><font size=+1>Steve Martin- All of Me</font></b>
<p>
Think about  it. Martin has to play a man half possesed by a woman. But not any woman.  Lily Tomlin.  It  may be the greatest and most intelligent slapstick of the sound era, a film and performance that could have teetered over-the-top into Monty Python-ville, but which Martin kept on the ground with his remarkable restraint.  The performance becomes so effective that you really do believe that is Lily up there on the screen.
<p>
<b>Best Scene</b> -  The courtroom.
<p>
<u>And for that matter:</u>
<p>
Steve Martin in  "Parenthood"
<p>
Jack Lemmon in "Some Like it Hot,"  Dustin Hoffman in "Tootsie"
<p>
<br><br>

<LI>  <font size=+1><b>Martin Landau- Crimes and Misdemeanors</b></font>
<p>
The greatest  Doestevskian performance in the history of movies. As an optamologist who plots to have his mistress killed, Landau gives a performance of such tragic resonance that   you  worry for the physical health of the actor himself.<p>
<p>
<b>Best Scene</b>  -   When Landau learns about the death of Anjelica Huston
<p>
<u>And for that matter:</u>
<p>
Martin Landau in "Ed Wood" and  "Tucker: A Man and his Dream"
<p>
<br><br>

<LI>  <b><font size=+1>Robert Shaw- The Taking of Pelham One-Two-Three</font></b>
<p>
Robert Shaw, Okay. But in "the Taking of..." C'mon, ya gotta be kidding me. Nope. Not at all. I don't believe any  heist cum hostage film has ever provided this much tension. Most of that is a direct result of Shaw's assured and controlled performance.  He brings an elegance and tick-tick excitement that would have been overblown and hyper with, say, Pacino in the role of  the leader of a group of criminals who take over a subway car in Manhattan
<p>
<b>BEST SCENE</b> - Shaw's confrontation with Walter Matthau
<p>
<u>And for that matter:</u>
<p>
Robert Shaw in. "Jaws" and "A Man for All Seasons."
Al Pacino in "Dog Day Afternoon,"  Dustin Hoffman in "Straw Dogs,"  Michael Madsen in "Reservoir Dogs" 
<p>
<br><br>

<LI>  <b><font size=+1>Elliott Gould- The Long Goodbye</font></b>
<p>
Many people, critics in particular, regard this as Robert Altman's actual bona-fide masterpiece. If that's the case ( I happen to think that it is), than  Altman should erect a statue of reverence to Gould, who largely improvised his performance as the great detective Marlowe.  His casual, shuffling style,   slowly sucking us into his character's brain, was like great Brando without the pretension. 
<p>
BEST SCENE- Getting cat food
<p>
<br><br>
</OL>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<br><br>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>Okay, E-mail me with your picks  FROM THE MENU BAR BELOW.
</CENTER></FONT>



