<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>BOB HECKLER
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="AA0000" VLINK="BBBB00">
<BR><IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="white.gif"><BR>



<TABLE  BORDER=2 WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=10  CELLPADDING=8>
	<TR>
     <TD><IMG  WIDTH=167  HEIGHT=115  SRC="710talk4.gif"></TD>

     <TD  ALIGN=LEFT  WIDTH=75% >
		<H1>BOB HECKLER

</H1>

		<FONT SIZE=5>Monday - Friday<BR> 9 a.m. - Noon</H3></FONT></TD>
	</TR>
<CENTER></TABLE>

<BR><IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=70% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=0>

<TD>

Call him whatever you wish, but KMPC's Bob Heckler believes everyone is
entitled to his or her opinion. His aptly-suited last name could be
described as the theme of his conservative talk show on weekdays from
9 a.m. to Noon.  His intensity on the radio seems to bring out the
most in his listeners and callers, and serves to fire himself up.

<P>
 Bob spent a short time in the Navy before getting into the business world.
 Heckler's Loew Chemical Company was his first successful venture. That, in
 turn, allowed him to finance various other businesses, such as founding <I>Lighting Dimensions magazine</I> a
 trade magazine for TV, motion picture and theatrical lighting designers, a chemical manufacturing
  business, and a flight school where he piloted planes
 and helicopters. Bob also was President and CEO of the National Ticket
 Network/The Ticket Channel, a cable television network that was later
 sold to the Home Shopping Network.

<P>
 Bob began his radio career in Denver, where his passionate style of talk
 made him a fixture in the city's radio market. He had been conducting
 business seminars on how to comply with the Americans with Disabilities Act,
 when he was asked to appear on a financial radio program on KNUS-AM in
 Denver. His self-professed "mike fright" on the initial broadcast 
turned out
 to be not as bad as he believed. Afterwards, he was asked to do fill in on
 various shifts, and eventually was given a permanent evening time slot.

<P>
 His radio life began at KNUS-AM 710, airing the evening shift for Mile
 High Broadcasting in Denver. He later worked at Salem broadcasting at KRKS
 94.7 FM in Denver, as the host of the only secular talk show on Christian
 radio.  In August of 1995, he moved to
 KABC Talkradio in Los Angeles and, on January 22, 1996, he moved to 
 its sister station, KMPC.
 Bob has one saying to callers who are unable
 to accept his views and opinions: "Deal with it!"

<P>
 Bob has one son and a Welsh Corgi dog, and looks forward to  
 flying helicopters and airplanes in the skies above Southern California.


</TD>
</TABLE></CENTER><P>
<P>
