<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ART BELL
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="AA0000" VLINK="BBBB00">
<BR>
<IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif"><BR>

<TABLE  BORDER=0 WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=10  CELLPADDING=8>
<TR>
<TD><IMG  WIDTH=167  HEIGHT=115  SRC="../Bios/710talk4.gif"></TD>
<TD><H3>ROD'S TOP TEN SMASHES OF THE SUMMER</H3></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<BR><IMG  WIDTH=0  HEIGHT=10  Align=CENTER SRC="../Bios/white.gif"><BR>


<CENTER>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=80% CELLSPACING=0  CELLPADDING=10>

<TR><TD>
<B>Here are my predictions of the order in which the summer films will play 
themselves out:</B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>
1.  <B>INDEPENDENCE DAY:</B>  Roland Emmerich is about a month away from becoming the biggest foreign 
director in the world.   "ID4" will not only be the biggest hit of the summer, but it has a shot 
at being the most successful film in history.  It combines the key elements of three 
supersmashes:  "Jurassic Park," "Star Wars," and "The Towering Inferno/Earthquake."
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>
2.  <B>MISSION IMPOSSIBLE:</B>  The star power (read: Tom Cruise) and sheer number of screens (almost 
4000) will assure this rather mediocre film's rise to the (near) top.  However, look for bad 
word of mouth on the meandering and incomprehensible plot to devastate the film's second week 
box office take.
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>
3.  <B>THE ROCK:</B>  An Oscar Winner in an action film.  Has it ever been done?  Not since Gene 
Hackman in "The Poseidon Adventure" filmgoers can attend this one guilt-free due to the presence 
of Nick Cage.  Killer trailer.
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>
4.  <B>TWISTER:</B>  The huge opening weekend number was due more to the fact that the only competition 
was a Janeane Garafalo film than anything else.  It will end up with "Speed"-like numbers.
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>
5.  <B>ESCAPE FROM L.A.:</B>  What one must factor in the millions and millions who became HUGE fans 
of "Escape from New York" via the video.  Kurt Russell's stock as an  action star has risen 
considerably after "Stargate" and "Executive Decision."
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>
6.  <B>THE HUNCHBACK OF NOTRE DAME:</B>  Why is a Disney animated feature NOT number one?  The subject 
matter for one.  What's next, Mickey Mouse as Oskar Schindler?  Care to guess which film wins 
the best song Oscar this year?
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>
7.  <B>THE NUTTY PROFESSOR:</B>  Eddie Murphy had to look back to an old master to return to his glory 
days.  If this one doesn't work, well...... "I'll take Eddie in the center square to block."
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>
8.  <B>A TIME TO KILL:</B>  Okay, you combine Grisham with the hottest actress in Hollywood (Sandra 
Bullock) and is there even the slightest chance that it won't hit.  Look for "Client"-style 
numbers on this one.
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>
9.  <B>THE CABLE GUY:</B>  It's Jim Carey, so there is a certain built-in audience, like it or not.  
But will they come to see this very, very dark film more than once.
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>
10.  <B>ERASER:</B>  It will be a hit, but will not recoup it's money in the United States.  Hey, 
Arnold is the one who bombed as an "Action Hero" and as a "Junior."
</TD></TR>

</TD>
</TABLE></CENTER><P>
<P>
