<A HREF="roadtest_1.htm#chc"><B>1997 CHEVROLET CAVALIER </B></A><BR>
<A HREF="roadtest_1.htm#bba"><B>1997 BUICK PARK AVENUE ULTRA</B></A><BR>
<A HREF="roadtest_1.htm#ev1"><B>1997 GENERAL MOTORS EV1</B></A><BR>
<A HREF="roadtest_2.htm#cdc"><B>1997 CADILLAC DEVILLE CONCOURS</B></A><BR>
<A HREF="roadtest_2.htm#pgpg"><B>PONTIAC GRAND PRIX GTP</B></A><BR>
<A HREF="roadtest_2.htm#cvm"><B>1997 CHEVROLET VENTURE MINIVAN</B></A><BR>

</TR>
</TD>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>


<BR CLEAR=ALL><HR NOSHADE WIDTH=90%><BR>

<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=95% BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TR><TD>

<CENTER><A NAME="mb"><B>1997 MERCEDES-BENZ 'E' CLASS</B></A></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="me.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>
<P>The all-new Mercedes-Benz E-class cars, on the market for a bit more than a
year, have succeeded in capturing the imagination of car-lovers worldwide. With
a front-end style at once completely modern and at the same time a throwback to
the most classic-looking Mercedes models of the 1930s, the E-class, which
includes the 320 and 420 models, are being judged by experts as some of the
finest cars made...ever.<P>

<P>Especially the E420.<P>

<P>I have spent a week at a time in both cars, and there's no doubt that the E320
is a solid, taut and fully Germanic automobile. Four-wheel anti-lock disc
brakes, traction control (called Automatic Slip Reduction on M-B autos) and a
classic front-engine, rear-drive layout provide most all that a real sedan-lover
could ask for in a modern-day auto.<P>

<P>The E-class also comes with frontal driver, passenger AND side airbags (built
into the front doors). So the Mercedes tradition of providing more safety than
you'll probably ever need continues with both of the E-class cars. In fact, it
has been said through the years with more than a kernel of truth that if you get
killed in a Mercedes-Benz, it was probably your own fault.<P>

<P>The 320 car comes with an inline 6 cylinder engine that is a high-on-torque
powerhouse which gets you off the line quickly but takes bit longer than you
might like to get up and running at freeways speeds. Remember, all that tautness
in M-B vehicles is in large part due to the basic heavy weight of the
Mercedes...if there is such a thing as an "overbuilt" car, it is any Mercedes
four-door sedan.<P>

<P>But if it is power which you demand, then don't bother with the $45,000 or so
E320...add a few grand more to the price and get yourself the E420, the same
basic car (with the same beautiful lines) as the E320...but with a 4.2 liter V8
engine.<P>

<P>The engine is as smooth and quiet as absolutely any engine sold by any other car
company in the world. Mated with a five-speed (yes, FIVE-speed) automatic
transmission the driver can control via a nifty center-mounted gated lever, the
drivetrain is every bit as confidence-inspiring as that found in the
now-legendary Lexus LS400...except the Mercedes has a bigger engine, and the
Mercedes is simply a more solid-feeling car (due again, basically, to that heavy
weight).<P>

<P>The E420 also gets appropriately beefed-up in the suspension, braking and
steering department. M-B engineers were not going to let the powerful
V8-equipped out of the stable without the right "teaks" to allow the driver to
handle all that power without the proper total equipment package underneath him
or her.<P>

<P>Here's how much I think of the E420: I drive at least one brand-new car every
week for hundreds of miles, and my girlfriend Carey gets to hear (whether she
wants to or not) what I think about them. And I drive them all...from the basic
Hyundai to the $360,000 Bentley Continental T.<P>

<P>After driving the M-B E420 for two days, I drove over to Carey's and announced,
"I think I may have found the perfect car for me".<P>

<P>That says a lot.<P>

<P>I don't like a very big car...but I do like a sedan which can seat four
comfortably, five in a pinch. I like a lot of trunk room. I like all the modern
conveniences and the latest safety devices. I like to feel very connected to the
road. I like a responsive car which jumps when and where I tell it to. I like
rear drive, though with a lot of today's modern front-wheel drive cars, most
people can't really tell the difference. I like a car with a stiffer suspension
than most Americans prefer, also.<P>

<P>The Mercedes fills almost all my likes (including a front-seat cupholder which
is a prime example of what can happen when you give a German engineer too much
time and money)...this is that very rare car about which I have virtually no
complaints.<P>

<P>Sure, the "winter/summer" transmission switch which chooses whether or not the
car will start out in first or second gear (first in summer, second in winter
for added traction) is too close to the power window buttons, the gas filler
door can not be controlled independent of the car's central locking mechanism
and visibility out the windshield is obscured a bit by too-thick A-pillars...but
don't sweat the small stuff.<P>

<P>The positives of the E-class cars, especially the E420, outweigh any negatives
so strongly that complaining at all seems to be nit-picking.<P>

<P>Mercedes-Benz is now starting to "ramp up" for production of their all-new AAV
sport/utility vehicle at a brand-new plant in Vance, Alabama. Thus, Mercedes
joins BMW in building cars and trucks in the USA (BMW is located in Greer, South
Carolina...that's where they are building the little Z3 sports car).<P>

<P>What other German company once built cars in America? Volkswagen...they built
their Rabbit model at a plant in western Pennsylvania...until slow sales and
poor quality forced them to close that factory about a decade ago.<P>

<P>I mentioned all the positives of the E420...but left out one big negative:
Price. You'll have to cough up around $60,000 or so to bring one of these babies
home...but if you have the green stuff (or can swing a lease deal), you can be
confident you're driving one of the best cars built today.<P>


</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<BR><HR WIDTH=90%><BR>


<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=95% BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TR><TD>

<CENTER><A NAME="ft"><B>1997 FORD TAURUS</B></A></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="ft.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>
<P>One of the most highly-awaited cars of recent times has turned out to be, well,
something of a sales dud.<P>

<P>The all-new Taurus from Ford has not been selling anywhere near the huge
company's expectations, and you don't have to look much farther than the Taurus'
sheetmetal to see what at least one of the problems is.<P>

<P>The car is simply too highly-styled for the average man and women the car is
aimed at. It doesn't take a brain surgeon to see that Ford made at least some
use of their new partners at Mazda (Ford controls Japan's Mazda these days) in
designing this car; many critics think this tenth-anniversary Taurus looks more
like a pumped-up Mazda RX-7  than anything else.<P>

<P>Ovoid this, round that, not a square shape or hard angle in sight on this car.<P>

<P>And the American public responded to all this by staying away from the Taurus in
droves. In fact, as of this writing, Ford is offering incentives of up to $1500
on retail Taurus sales...something which would have been thought unheard of just
two years ago...and the Honda Accord has recently passed-up Taurus as the
best-selling car in America.<P>

<P>It's a shame, because Taurus is a very good car. But it has that pesky styling
problem, and it is pricey. A Chevrolet Lumina with more interior room and a more
powerful engine (and more traditional, conservative "American-type" styling) can
be had for up to...get this...$3000 less than a top-line Taurus.<P>

<P>With competitive cars like the Lumina, Camry and Accord on the market, Ford
could not afford to make any mistakes whatsoever with their Taurus. However, by
putting this "far out" sheetmetal on top of a very reliable, dependable and
proven auto...traditionally one of the nation's best-sellers...a lot of industry
analysts think they ruined the car for the average American.<P>

<P>But you have to respect them for coming out with a car which takes to the limit
the rounded "jelly bean" concept of the original Taurus, a concept developed by
Ford designer Jack Telnack, and a concept which has worked not only for the
Taurus but for the entire industry for the better part of the last decade.<P>

<P>It appears Ford had too much confidence in this style, though. That rounded look
is considered old and tired by a lot of new-car buyers, and in fact Toyota is
telling the press that they expect to take a lot of potential Taurus buyers away
from Ford with their all-new 1997 Camry...a car which purposely utilizes more
sharp-edged lines than rounded ones.<P>

<P>The same thing happened...virtually overnight...with hatchbacks in this country.
Hatchbacks were all the rage throughout the 1970s and into the mid-1980s...then
one day sales stopped as surely as someone had turned a switch "off".<P>

<P>You can't explain it....the best which the automotive product planners in the
world can do is try and predict what the public will want a few years from now.
When this all-new Taurus was designed, probably in 1992, the "jelly bean" style
was still all the rage. But those days of public acceptance and approval seem
gone, and with them Ford's very high hopes for Taurus.<P>

<P>A solid front-wheel drive powerplant and drivetrain, safe and reliable
operation, enough power to cruise (if not race) in-town and on long highway
trips in comfort and security, solid fuel mileage figures and a near
emissions-less V6, tens of millions of advertising and marketing dollars to
back-up the product in the marketplace...so what went wrong?<P>

<P>The all-new Taurus, if nothing else, is a prime example of how incorrectly
gauging the public's changing tastes can result in a corporate defeat.<P>

<P>Sales of the Taurus do not look all that bad on paper...but way too many of them
are being sold to corporate fleets and daily rental companies. And these are not
the markets which pay the high retail prices that turn a car into a true
"success".<P>

<P>Ford no doubt wanted this Taurus to wind up in college and industry textbooks
for more than a few reasons...but poor sales sure wasn't one of them!<P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>


<BR><HR WIDTH=90%><BR>


<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=95% BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TR><TD>

<CENTER><A NAME="cc"><B>1997 CADILLAC CATERA</B></A></CENTER>
<IMG SRC="cc.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>
<P>The big question about the Cadillac Catera is, simply: Why?<P>

<P>Cadillac has to lower the average age of their buyers; there's no doubt about 
that. But Cadillac has spent almost the past decade convincing us that their 
Northstar System, a sophisticated 4.6 liter dual overhead cam V8 front-wheel 
drive system, putting out as much as 300 horsepower and then some, is about 
the best powertrain on the planet. And you know what? They're right.<P>

<P>So, why, oh why, oh why, would Cadillac, in attempting to bring in new, 
younger buyers to their showrooms, come out with a V6-powered rear wheel 
drive car?<P>

<P>The answer: Costs. The Cadillac Catera is nothing more than a re-worked 
version of car which has been for sale for some time in Europe, a car called 
the Opel Omega. The Omega is a very nice car, no doubt about that. But is it 
the car which Cadillac should be trying to sell to American Yuppies?<P>

<P>By using the Omega as the basis for their new car, Cadillac has been able to 
avoid some of the huge costs involved with developing a true "all-new" 
automobile. As an example, Ford admitted publicly that their Contour, which 
is sold in Europe as the Mondeo, cost the company more than $6 Billion 
dollars to bring to the market. Yes, $6 *B*illion.<P>

<P>Catera handling is sportier and the suspension stiffer than traditional 
Cadillacs, another remnant of the car's very direct European heritage.<P>

<P>The Catera is a pretty good-looking four-door sedan which some of you might 
think looks a bit too suspiciously like a Nissan Maxima on steroids. The V6 
powerplant displaces 3 liters and produces 200 horsepower; not bad for a rear 
drive car with a stick shift, but the Catera will be available only with a 
four-speed automatic. And the car weighs in at well over 3500 pounds. So that 
is NOT a lot of power for this car.<P>

<P>The interior and exterior fit and finish on Catera appears to be world-class 
and then some, something Cadillac should be proud of and talk about...a lot.<P>

<P>Is the car worth as much as $36,000, which is what it will cost 
fully-equipped? Probably not...there are simply better cars for the money 
on-sale in America. Catera prices will start at just over $30,000.<P>

<P>One also must wonder about Cadillac bringing out an entry-level car (for 
them, at least) with the name Catera. Remember the Cimarron, the last Caddy 
entry-level attempt? <P>

<P>The car was an unmitigated disaster, and I think Cadillac marketing people 
must have been off the day the company got General Motors to approve the 
name. It's just too similar to Cimarron, and I guarantee that you'll be 
seeing the similarity talked about (and joked about) in all the enthusiast 
magazines.<P>

<P>Cadillac produces some of the best cars in the world...all of them featuring 
the front-wheel drive Northstar V8 power system. The Catera does not have 
that system, though it sports a pretty good drivetrain of its own, with 
electronic traction control and anti-lock brakes as standard equipment.<P>

<P>Whether this will be enough to allow Cadillac to capture buyers in the 
all-important "near-luxury" market remains to be seen. The Cadillac name 
itself can still bring a lot of people into their showrooms; whether or not 
this car will bring in people under 50 years of age is something other 
automakers will watching very closely.<P>

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<BR><HR WIDTH=90%><BR>


<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=95% BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TR><TD>

<CENTER><A NAME="fe"><B>1997 FORD EXPEDITION</B></A></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="fe.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>
<P>Ford has finally done it...and in a big, seemingly successful way.<P>

<P>After years of allowing General Motors truck and Chevrolet to virtually 
dominate alone the full-sized sport/utility market in this country with their 
Tahoe, Yukon and Suburban vehicles, Ford has bowed to market pressures and 
brought out their Expedition...the company's very first full-sized four-door 
sport/utility vehicle.<P>

<P>If this is all a bit confusing, look at it this weay: The incredibly popular 
Ford Explorer is built on the same platform as the small Ranger pick-up; the 
Blazer and Jimmy from GM and Chevrolet are built on the same platform as the 
S-10 and S-15 small pick-ups.<P>

<P>Now, go up a step: The Yukon and Tahoe and Suburban (which is also known as 
the National Truck Of Texas, so well does it sell there) are built on the 
full-sized pickup platforms, what is known in the business as the C and K 
platforms.<P>

<P>Got that so far?<P>

<P>Okay...now the full-sized Ford pickup is built on the F-series platform. And 
that is the same platform on which the Expedition is built.<P>

And as popular as the all-new F-series has been, so, I precict, will be the 
Expedition. In fact, Ford has already boasted, practically before the first 
retail Expedition has left the showroom floor, that the company will sell 
140,000 of these all-new trucks in the first model year alone.<P>

<P>A lot of those buyers will be folks who do not want to wait the 2-3 months 
which it now takes to get a GM or Chevy sport/utility. And many of the buyers 
will be diehard Ford fans who simply could not bear the thought of driving 
one of The General's vehicles...no matter how good it is.<P>

<P>Ford has been controlling the overall light truck market for some years in 
America. The company sells more than *1,200* Explorers every DAY...and sales 
of their full-sized pickups are currently more than *200,000* ahead of Chevy 
and GMC for the 1996 model year.<P>

<P>How did they do this? They planned ahead. Somehow, the product planners at 
Ford saw the current truck boom coming as much as 10 years ago, and they 
planned for the tooling and the factories they would need to meet the demand. 
Ford simply beat GM on this one, fair and sqaure.<P>

<P>On the other hand, GM has only one plant in America which still builds 
rear-wheel drive cars, and that is in Arlington, TX. After January, 1997, 
that plant will no longer build the Chevrolet Caprice, Buick Roadmaster or 
Cadillac Fleetwood...all those cars will be discontinued. Instead, the huge 
plant will be dedicated to building...you guessed it...trucks. It's something 
GM probably should have done 5 years ago...and they know they are sacrificing 
at last 40,000 sales of Caprices to police departments every year, but 
change-over the plant to trucks-only they are doing none the less. (And a lot 
of those lost police sales will be made up by the Ford Crown Victoria, the 
last full-sized rear-drive car made in America after the end of this year).<P>

<P>Now, the discussion about whether or not GM could build trucks AND cars at 
that plant is another story entirely...I hav been to enough plants in Japan 
where trucks, vans, cars and even station wagons are built by the same 
workers on the same line...but the United Auto Workers in this country want 
to make a LOT more money to do that kind of work. And they probably should.<P>

<P>But back to our vehicle at hand, the Ford Expedition. It comes, surprisingly 
and distressingly, with the 4.6 liter V8 overhead cam engine. I say 
distressingly, because this is the heart of the vehicle and it also may be 
its weakest point. Overhead cam engines make their torque and horsepower at 
the higher end of the rpm (engine speed) range; pushrod, or overhead valve 
engines, make more torque, or pulling power, at the lower end of the rpm 
range. <P>

<P>For instance, diesel engines make almost ALL their torque at VERY low engine 
rpm's, or engine speeds. That's why diesels are used to power over-the-road 
long-haul trucks.<P>

<P>Ford considered using the 5 liter V8 found in the older Mustang (and the 
newer Explorer), a pushrod engine, for the Expedition (and for the F-series 
pickup). But the engine could not pass fuel and emissions standards now and 
in the future as easily as the more sophisticated 4.6 liter overhead cam 
powerplant.<P>

<P>So while on paper the two versions of the 4.6 liter engine offered do have 
the necessary pulling torque, in real-world usage it does not feel as strong 
as I would like for a truck of this size and weight (almost 5000 pounds...and 
with a full load of 8 passengers (with an optional third rear seat) and 
baggage, that weight figure could easily be much higher).<P>

<P>In fact, the pushrod V6 engines found in smaller GM and Chevy trucks produce 
almost the same horsepower and torque as the larger and more expensive Ford 
V8 engines found in their new trucks.<P>

<P>Fit and finish in the Expedition is nothing short of wonderful; once the 
vehicle is up and running at freeway speeds (which can take some time) it 
feels like a luxury car. It's quiet, smooth and purposeful. Plus, it's 
good-looking, with the same really nifty front-end design found on the 
F-series full-sized pickup.<P>

<P>Expedition is available with a variety of trailering and four-wheel drive 
packages as you might image. The cost for all this luxury and power (though 
we wish there were MORE power): Prices range from about $28,000 to just over 
$38,000...equitable with similar GM truck and Chevrolet vehicles.<P>

<P>Is Expedition worth it? Probably. Finally, Ford has a vehicle which can 
match, feature for feature, the proven and excellent full-sized 
sport/utilties from Chevy and GM truck. <P>

<P>If they'd add a bit more low-end torque tot hate engine, I'd be a true 
believer. And, if Dodge would ever come out with a full-sized sport/utility 
based on their popular Ram truck, we'd have a great selection of three big 
sport/utes in this country instead of just two very good ones. But 
wait...Dodge WILL be coming out with an all-new sport/ute based on their new 
mid-sized Dakota...but more on that later!<P>

<P>The truckin' hits keep on coming!<P>

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>



<BR><BR>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=2>
Steve Parker
