<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Steve Parker
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT=000000 LINK="#aa0000" VLINK="#cc0000" >

<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=95% BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TR><TD>

<CENTER><A NAME="in"><B>1997 INFINITI Q45</B></A></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="in.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>
<P>
They've shrunk the car, lowered the horsepower, done away with a suspension 
system like no other in the world...and they still want to charge more than 
$50,000 for it. Is this any way to run an automotive luxury division?<P>

<P>Infiniti, the luxury sales arm of Nissan, has always had its work cut out for 
itself in this country. Infiniti has always been seen as nothing more than an 
"answer" to Lexus and Acura, and that is unfortunate, because Infiniti offers 
some very good cars for some reasonably good prices.<P>

<P>For 1997, Infiniti offers an all-new version of their Q45 model, the car 
which has always been the flagship luxury sedan of the Infiniti division.<P> 

<P>The Q45 has been, up until now, something of a technological tour de force 
for Infiniti, being the only production car in the world to feature a 
full-active suspension system, an innovative and modern suspension system 
which was originally developed for Formula One racing cars. Only the 
engineers at Nissan/Infiniti took the chance to translate this 
racing-oriented suspension system into one for a mass-produced luxury sedan.<P>

<P>But for the 1997 model year, Infiniti has sadly discontinued the availability 
of the full-active suspension option, and for several reasons. The main 
explanation which Infiniti would like to have us all believe is behind their 
decision to drop the full-active suspension option is simply that enough 
people did not order it on their Q45's in the past. And indeed, in past 
years, only about 15% of Q45 buyers in America have spent the almost $5000 
extra for the full-active option. However, in Japan, where the buying public 
seems as enamored as ever by hi-tech gadgets, fully 80% of Q45 model buyers 
opt for the expensive full-active option.<P>

<P>Another reason for the discontinuation of the full-active option on 
American-market Q's, and perhaps the most important element behind Nissan's 
decision, is that, in order to satisfy the advanced on-board diagnostic 
systems mandated by Federal law to be on all 1997 cars, it was simply going 
to cost Nissan/Infiniti a prohibitive amount per full-active-equipped car.<P>

<P>I've had the opportunity to drive Q45a models (the 'a' denoting a car 
equipped with the full-active system) and it is an amazing experience. The 
car's front end will not lift no matter how hard you accelerate, and will not 
dive even under the most powerful braking. Going into a corner at high 
speeds, in a situation which would have any other two-ton luxury sedan 
rolling on its axis from side to side, is an experience in rock-hard 
stability. The Q45a models were revelations of what a modern-day four-door 
high-powered sedan is capable of with the latest equipment. But Infiniti, in 
doing away with the full-active option, makes a used Q45a possibly the best 
buy in the marketplace today...and that could prove a boon to the smart, 
sophisticated and aware used car buyer.<P>

<P>The Lexus LS400 sedan, built by Toyota, was the first true V8-powered luxury 
sedan to come out of Japan for the US market, and it was an immediate hit. 
Nissan had Q45 models ready for road-testing by American car magazines at the 
same time they tested the Lexus model, but for some reason they made the 
decision to wait with the Q45, and give it to magazines several months after 
they had completed their initial, glowing tests of the LS400. What this meant 
was that from the very start, the Infiniti was always perceived as an 
upstart, Johnny-come-lately answer by Nissan to Toyota's Lexus, but nothing 
could have been further from the truth. However, Nissan's decision to wait 
branded the Infiniti line in general and the Q45 in particular as "too 
little, too late". <P> 

<P>But the "Q" was appreciated by those "in the know", the driver looking for 
more of an intimate experience with their car. If the Lexus was truly a 
Japanese version of the staid, conservative, ultra-reliable and safe 
Mercedes-Benz, then truly the Infiniti became quickly known as the "Japanese 
BMW", a sedan aimed not at the average driver, but at the sporting driver 
looking for some fun in the mix.<P>

<P>The Q's styling was innovative and unique. The first few years the car had no 
front grille, and indeed did not need one...cooling air was sucked into the 
engine bay from below the car, not in front. However, the car now sports a 
classic, traditional-looking front grille, due to customer demand more than 
anything else. Infiniti stylists went along with public focus groups which, 
evidently, wanted the car to look more like Jaguar than an Infiniti.<P>

<P>This year the Q has all-new body panels and the car is smaller and lighter 
than it has been in the past. However, Infiniti engineers have done some 
magic by creating more room than ever before for rear seat passengers, in 
spite of the car's smaller overall size (and a weight of just under 4000 
pounds).<P>

<P>The interior of the Q, the quality of fit and finish and the comfort levels, 
as well as the levels of "NVH" (noise, vibration and harshness) remain 
world-class and much what you would expect from a car with a base price of 
near $50,000.<P>

<P>A lot of the Q's original magic, apart from the somewhat daring styling and 
the availability of the full-active suspension, was in the engine.<P>

<P>A 4.5 liter 32-valve V8 which produced more than 300 horsepower (though the 
company would never publicly admit to that figure, as Japanese car-makers 
have sort of a "gentlemen's agreement" to keep horsepower below the 300 
mark), the roaring powerplant could propel the car to freeway speeds in 
surprisingly little time. Smooth and docile in town, the Q's engine could 
turn into a screaming wildcat at the touch of the right foot to the throttle 
pedal.<P>

<P>So what has Infiniti done with the 1997 model? They have lowered the engine 
displacement (size) and its horsepower rating as well. The engine is now a 
4.1 liter unit, though it is still a sophisticated 32-valve dual over head 
cam-equipped motor, and produced, according to Infiniti, about 266 horses. 
While reducing the weight and size of the car has helped the Q keep some of 
that original "off the line" feeling it was known for in certain enthusiast 
circles, the car is still almost a full second slower in 0-60 times with this 
all-new model.<P>

<P>Using the 4.1 litere V8 made things easier on the pocketbook for Nissan. The 
4.5 was used only in the Q, out of all the aNissan offered worldwide, but the 
4.1 is used in the Q and other Nissan models. That makes it less expensive 
for Nissan by allowing them share the 4.1 in several different vehicles.<P>

<P>Also, a racing version of the 4.1 liter V8 will be seen on the track during 
the Indy 500 next year.<P>

<P>So what have they done to the Q45? It appears an exorcism of sorts was 
performed...the Nissan/Infiniti engineers and stylists managed to keep the 
shell and some of the spirit of the original car, but by going to a smaller, 
less powerful engine and deleting the full-active suspension option, they 
have just about taken the devil, or almost all of the fun, out of this car.<P>

<P>Rather than stand apart from the crowd, as it has for years, the 1997 
Infiniti Q45 becomes just another ho-hum yawner of a $50,000+ sedan. Where, 
indeed, is the beef?
<P>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<BR><HR WIDTH=90%><BR>


<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=95% BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TR><TD>

<CENTER><A NAME="ja"><B>1997 JAGUAR XK8</B></A></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="ja.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>

<P>Jaguar has a challenge on their hands, no doubt about that. After decades of 
building exceptionally pretty cars with a reputation for poor reliability, 
the car company has realized that tradition and history alone are no longer 
enough to get people, Americans especially, to buy their motor cars.<P>

<P>With their all-new XK8 coupe and convertible, with a DOHC V8 engine and 
modern conveniences Jaguar could not have dreamed of even ten years ago, the 
car has the looks and pedigree to change Jaguar's image 180 degrees in the 
United States. The company has a lot riding on this car's success...but can 
they pull it off? Have the Jaguar's problems, especially the electrical ones, 
been solved?<P>

<P>Not that Jaguar has not been capable at times of building dependable cars. 
During the 1950s and '60s, the company built some of the world's greatest 
road racing cars, and many race car builders in Europe would specify that 
Jaguar engines only be used in their racing vehicles. However, their street 
cars never seemed able to reach the level of quality for which their race 
cars were known.<P>

<P>The XK road car series of the 1950s certainly captured the imagination of 
car-lovers worldwide. Elegant and classy-looking, with interiors suggesting 
the best "clubby" atmosphere of a British collegiate society, the XK cars 
looked great but were at best quirky in their performance.<P>

<P>The same was true of the beautiful XK-E series, introduced in the 1960s and 
considered today still as some of the most gorgeous cars ever designed. With 
straight-6 engines or powerful V12 powerplants, the XK-E cars looked fast 
standing still...and unfortunately too much of the time that's all they did. 
In fact, though the XK-E cars' popularity essentially saved Jaguar from going 
out of business (myth has it that Elves and Leprechauns helped design the car 
to save the company) the company continued to develop a reputation for cars 
which spent more time in the shop than on the road.
<P>

<P>Things did not get much better with the newer-generation XJ series of cars, 
including the XJ-6, XJ-12 and XJ-S and -R motor cars. Some of the 
best-looking cars on the road, they nonetheless had, compared to other cars 
of the 1980s and '90s, terrible quality.<P>

<P>This in spite of the fact that Ford Motor Company paid more than $2.5 billion 
for Jaguar and took the company over as the decade of the '90s came upon us. 
In an attempt to both get involved with Jaguar and yet, at the same time, 
keep a "hands off" distance in order to respect Jaguar's heritage, Ford was 
sort of caught in the middle.<P>

<P>Quality has improved in the past few years, but for the most part not to the 
extent that I could recommend a new Jaguar purchase to anyone I considered a 
friend. Especially with the advent of the Japanese luxury cars and the 
lowered prices of BMW and Mercedes-Benz autos, Jaguar become less and less of 
a choice for car-buyers looking for dependability.<P>

<P>The heart of the Jaguar problem always seemed to revolve around their use of 
electronic components from a British company called Lucas, a company with 
such a poor reputation that their nickname is "Prince of Darkness". Why do 
the British drink warm beer? They have Lucas refrigerators. What are the 
three settings on a Lucas headlamp switch? Dim, flicker and off.<P>

<P>You get the idea.<P>

<P>Finally, Ford has done something about it.<P>

<P>The 1997 XK8, the first all-new Jaguar the company has built since Ford took 
over, is one the streets and early reports have the car to be nothing short 
of miraculous in terms of overall quality and dependability.<P>

<P>Powered by Jaguar's first-ever V8 engine, a dual overhead cam almost-300 
horsepower unit built in Wales, the XK8 contains all the modern 
conveniences...from dual airbags to anti-lock disc brakes to specific Pirelli 
tires for each corner of the car to traction control...and it's all 
electronically controlled by components made not by Lucas, but by one of 
Japan's best-known automotive electronic firms, Nippon Denso.<P>

<P>This is a big thing. English car companies and their suppliers are considered 
some of the last vestiges of the "Empire", and no one in the U.K. likes to 
admit that maybe their industry would be better off with some other suppliers 
from some other countries. So Ford went very much against the grain in 
choosing a Japanese company to supply the XK8's electronics, but they did 
what had to be done.<P>

<P>Available as a coupe or convertible (and the convertible top is a one-button 
unit which operates as easily as the legendary power top in the Mercedes SL 
models) the XK8 has captured the imagination of Jaguar-lovers worldwide, men 
and women who had given up on the car as a form of daily transport, yet still 
appreciate them as a direct link to European automotive history and as 
hand-built works of functional art.<P>

<P>The XK8 even has a wooden-spoked steering wheel...something impossible in 
modern cars as far as safety officials are concerned, if not for the driver's 
airbag. Other classic and welcome interior touches include generous dollops 
of wool carpeting, leather, chrome and burled walnut paneling.<P>

<P>This front-engine, rear-drive car has loads of torque, giving it the 
get-up-and-go a fairly heavy car needs on Southern California freeway 
on-ramps. It is quiet (perhaps too quiet...I'd like more of an exhaust note), 
exceptionally smooth at all speeds, handles and corners like a slightly 
overweight older road racer, and stops on a dime thanks to those four wheel 
anti-lock disc brakes and corner-specific tires.<P>

<P>And...the XK8 is as beautiful a car as Jaguar, or any car company, has ever 
offered to the public. In fact, some of the very same stylists and designers 
who worked on the now-legendary and collectible XK-E had more than a bit of 
input to the XK8. The front oval air intake on the XK8, for example, is taken 
almost directly from the original XK-E.<P>

<P>It's a new kind of Jaguar, dependable and reliable. And it is exactly what 
the company needs to bring to the American automotive marketplace. With 
Ford's help and Japanese electronics, the car appears to be a winner.<P>

<P>And let's face it...in 1997, and for prices hovering around the $75,000 mark, 
anything less than a completely dependable car would make Jaguar the 
laughingstock of the auto world. They simply can not afford for this car to 
have ANY problems.<P>

<P>Should you join John Travolta and Jay Leno as some of the first XK8 owners? 
My recommendation would be to wait for one year or so...let's first see if 
the car works as well on the road as it does on paper. <P>
<P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>


<BR><HR WIDTH=90%><BR>


<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=95% BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TR><TD>

<CENTER><A NAME="ch"><B>CHEVROLET S-SERIES THREE-DOOR PICKUP</B></A></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="ch.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>

<P>
By Steve Parker &#169; 1997
<P>
<P>For 1997 Chevrolet rocks the small pickup truck market with the only 
mini-truck available with not two, but three doors. The extended cab version 
of the S-series trucks are available with a third door on the driver's side 
of the truck, a door which allows passengers easy access to the rear area 
(and a fold-down third seat) as well as an easy way to get to stowed, locked 
and secured equipment. The third door can only be opened if the driver's door 
is open, for added safety.<P>

<P>Dodge, Ford and Chevrolet offer third-door models on their larger, full-size 
models for 1997. But only Chevy has it on the small truck for 1997, and that 
will pay off for them in extra sales, and they deserve it. Why the industry 
waited this long for a third door on pickups is beyond me, anyway. It's 
simply an idea which makes great and perfect sense.<P>

<P>There was a time when a pickup truck was the dependable workhorse of the 
American highway and the back roads as well. On the farm and off, the classic 
pickup truck was built to work and work hard, day in and day out, year in and 
year out. And it did it all very well indeed. Any job you asked of it, any 
challenge you threw at it, the American pickup, whether Ford, Chevy, GMC or 
Dodge, responded each and every time.<P>

<P>"Reliable" and "consistent" were the best words to describe these trucks. 
They would start, run and haul when you asked them to; nothing fancy about 
these rigs, just the basics, ma'am.<P>

<P>"Comfort" and "luxury" were words which traditionally had absolutely nothing 
to do with pickup trucks. But sometime in the 1970s, there was a sea change 
in the pickup, and it all started with the appearance of the mini-pickup, 
developed and sold first in America by Toyota and Datsun (the company we 
today call Nissan). <P>

<P>And those small pickup trucks, cute and manageable and useful (and as stingy 
with gas) as they were, were immediately seized upon by two groups which up 
until that time would have nothing to do with the time-proven and large 
American pickups: Women and teenagers.<P>

<P>Within just a few years after the imports' appearance, Chevrolet was selling 
a small pickup built by Isuzu (the L.U.V. truck, which stood for "light 
utility vehicle"), Ford was selling a truck built by Mazda and Dodge was 
selling a mini-truck built by Mitsubishi. Everyone was getting into the small 
truck act. Remember the Subaru B.R.A.T.? (That stood for Bi-drive 
Recreational All-Terrain vehicle, believe it or not).<P>

<P>And with pickup trucks now being viewed by the entire marketplace, not just 
working men, as a possible answer to personal transportation needs, the 
truck-makers decided to "gussie up" their little workhorses and make them, 
quite literally, as comfortable inside and as good-looking outside as almost 
any family car.<P>

<P>With the advent of the current model F-series Ford, C/K series Chevy and GMC 
trucks and the Ram from Dodge, the full-size pickup is now as acceptable in 
the executive parking lot as it is in the corporate motor pool.<P>

<P>The popularity and acceptance of the modern pickup, both large and small 
models, led directly to the sales explosion of the sport/utility vehicles 
based on the pickup platforms, but that's another story.<P>

<P>And the pickup truck made available a few things which American cars once 
offered, but for the most part had gone away. For one thing, pickup trucks 
are rear-wheel drive. The majority of cars sold in this country are no longer 
RWD models, but have front-wheel drive (which makes for more interior space 
and is cheaper for manufacturers to build). Also, full-size pickups are all 
available with a variety of powerful V8 engines, and even the smaller trucks 
have spunky V6 powerplants. <P>

<P>Rear drive and a powerful engine? That's exactly why the pickup truck has 
become the hot rod of the 1990s. You literally can not find a new family car 
with these features in America for under $40,000 (apart from the Chevy 
Caprice, Buick Roadmaster and Ford Crown Victoria/Mercury Grand Marquis) and 
a full-size Chevy pickup with a V8 is base-priced at right around $15,000.<P>

<P>Add a seemingly simple thing like a third door to the mix in the small 
S-series truck from Chevrolet and you have one neat vehicle.<P>

<P>The standard 4.3 liter V6 in the S-series truck produces 180 horsepower in 
the 4x4 (175hp in the 4x2 model), and an engine option develops 190 
horsepower. In a vehicle which weighs less than 3000 pounds that's a lot of 
power. <P>

<P>My test truck came with a four-wheel drive system, a system unacceptable 
these days. That's because the transfer case controls are big, bulky and 
mechanical. In 1997, you should be able to push a button on the dash to get 
in and out of four-wheel drive and not have to stop the vehicle and throw a 
lever in the cockpit...that's simply too primitive for the late 1990s. <P>

<P>Also, fuel mileage in the test truck averaged about 16 miles per gallon, 
combined city and freeway driving. That figure is unacceptable for a V6 
engine in a fairly lightweight truck. <P>

<P>The test truck also came with four-wheel anti-lock brakes...and all for a 
price hovering right around the $20,000 mark. Find all those features in a 
new car for that price and I'll buy it for you. <P>

<P>One note: You'll generally find only a driver's side airbag on most trucks in 
1997, and not a passenger side bag, as they are not mandated by law on that 
side in trucks for another couple of years. The Chevy S-series has only a 
driver's side airbag in 1997.<P>

<P>Inside, comfort and convenience prevails. Let's just put it this way: If you 
have not sat in or driven a small pickup truck in the past ten years, do 
yourself a favor and test-drive one from Chevrolet soon, a model like I 
drove, with the third door option. A lot of you will start considering what a 
few years ago you have considered an impossibility: You might just buy a 
pickup truck. <P>

<P>And you know what? You can own a pickup and still be for gun control and vote 
Democratic...or not. That's what's really great about pickups...there's truly 
something for everyone.<P>

<P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>


<BR><BR>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=2>
Steve Parker
