<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Steve Parker
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY  BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT=000000 LINK="#aa0000" VLINK="#cc0000" >

<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=95% BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TR><TD>

<CENTER><A NAME="chc"><B>1997 CHEVROLET CAVALIER </B></A></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="chc.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>
<P>


By Steve Parker (c) 1996<P>

<P>It's a front-wheel drive four-cylinder car available as a two-door, four-door 
or a convertible. It gets great mileage, it's cute, it produces adequate 
horsepower and best of all...all the models are available for right around 
$15,000, fully-equipped. Anti-lock brakes are standard, traction control is 
an option on the convertible, a five-speed stick shift is standard and an 
automatic transmission is optional. And dual front airbags come with each and 
every car.<P>

<P>Just two or three years ago, that description probably would have fit only a 
Japanese import, and all the American car-makers realized it. That's why 
Detroit's Big Three have gone on a small-car development binge the past few 
years, desperately trying to create affordable, sporty and dependable 
transportation for the masses at a quality level approaching the best which 
Toyota, Nissan and all the others have to offer.<P>

<P>With the Chevrolet Cavalier (and its twin, the Pontiac Sunfire), General 
Motors has come as close as anyone to building a car containing that elusive 
Japanese concept of "things gone right".<P>

<P>That's how the Japanese started building their cars and trucks at the start 
of the '90s. Rather than concentrating on "things gone wrong", as did 
American and European auto-makers, the Japanese focused instead on taking 
their vehicles, which were already achieving unheard-of heights of consumer 
satisfaction, and making them even better.<P>

<P>With the Cavalier, Chevrolet finally has a home-grown small car of which they 
can be justly proud. It's got the right style, the right standard equipment 
and options and most of all...a price which makes sense. And the marketplace 
is supporting this particular small-car effort from General Motors...the 
Cavalier and Sunfire are selling very well.<P>

<P>While it may be too little too late in terms of grabbing market share back 
from the Japanese, at least consumers who want to "buy American" whenever 
possible now have an all-American choice when it comes to a small car in this 
very important class of vehicles.<P>

<P>And the reason this class of cars is oh-so-very important is quite simple. A 
car priced, styled and equipped such as the Cavalier is very likely to be the 
first car a person buys, helping to establish their buying patterns for the 
next 30 or 40 or even 50 years. <P>

<P>One reason the American manufacturers have lost so much market share in the 
past two decades is that, more and more often, young Americans are growing up 
in families where cars like Buicks, Dodges and Lincolns simply were not in 
the garage. Hondas, Toyotas and Infinitis are the cars in the family driveway 
these days, especially in Southern California.<P>

<P>I can remember a billboard on the Santa Ana Freeway in 1961 which said, 
simply, "You're probably following a Chevrolet". And they were right. Today, 
that billboard in Southern California would be very out of place. In fact, on 
a recent trip to England to visit the British Motor Show and do some TV work 
there, I saw the back page of the Motor Show's program. Emblazoned there was 
an advertisement which read "The car in front is a Toyota". How things change!<P>

<P>Most everything about the Cavalier is so right that it's hard to find more 
than minor things about which to complain. And for a car in this range, that 
is the price of admission into the segment, and Chevrolet has done well in 
that respect. They are to be seriously commended.<P>

<P>But one area of Cavalier (and Sunfire) falls woefully short of success. And 
it is a very important aspect of the car, some would say the most important.<P>

<P>When the GM engineers designed this platform, they decided to make the engine 
bay large enough only for a GM four cylinder engine. The previous generation 
Cavalier and Sunfire were available with V6 powerplants, but only a 120 
horsepower 2.2 liter four can be had with this Cavalier. And there is no 
step-up engine, no power option to add a little pizzazz to the unit.<P>

<P>And that's a shame, because this little car, especially with the optional RS 
package, which adds a bit beefier and capable tire, wheel and suspension 
package, could benefit heartily from even the somewhat-anemic 3.1 liter V6 
which GM has "on the shelf". <P>

<P>But weight and size and price and fuel economy restrictions being what they 
are for this category of car (not to mention insurance costs, which rise with 
a V6 as opposed to the four), meant that GM wanted a small engine for the car 
and that is what they got. While the 2.2 two-valve engine is just okay and 
perhaps enough power for the average buyer of this car (young, working-class 
or student and probably female), putting a V6 in this car would make it a 
little pocket rocket, putting it much closer to a true sports car rather than 
a mere "sporty" car.<P>

<P>Even the original version of the 2.2 would make a better fit in this car. 
Initially conceived and built as a 16-valve engine (four valves per cylinder, 
making it quite a bit more powerful) and called the Quad Four, the GM 2.2 was 
their corporate answer to the dual overhead cam engines in small cars which 
were coming into this country in droves from Japan in the late 1980s. But GM 
had a lot of problems with that engine (notably in the vibration and 
dependability areas), so the 16-valves were reduced to the more conventional 
8 there now (one intake and one exhaust valve per cylinder), so the trade-off 
for smoothness and reliability was made, and successfully so.<P>

<P>In all, a fine small car effort from The General, with the Chevrolet version 
of the car generally being priced a bit lower than the Pontiac. Everything 
works the way it should, and even the convertible top on that priciest 
version of the car is easy to put up and down, fits well and does not leak at 
all, which is saying a lot for a car in this price and size class.<P>

<P>You really can't ask for anything more for the price...and it's all made in 
America...but if only it came with a V6!<P>

<P>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<BR><HR WIDTH=90%><BR>


<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=95% BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TR><TD>

<CENTER><A NAME="bpa"><B>1997 BUICK PARK AVENUE ULTRA</B></A></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="bpa.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>

<P>
By Steve Parker (c) 1996<P>


<P>This is the top-of-the-line for Buick these days. No more rear-drive 
Roadmaster, no more V8 power, no more interiors which seem like they were 
ripped right out of a New Orleans bordello.<P>

<P>Nope, today's proper top-line American car calls for a supercharged V6 
engine, a front-drive platform and a sensible, comfortable and not 
over-wrought interior.<P>

<P>Buick's Park Avenue Ultra is the biggest and best four-door Buick you can 
buy. Production of the Roadmaster is over with for the 1997 model year; the 
factory in Arlington, TX which made all the big rear-wheel drive GM cars has 
been converted to truck production. That same factory also produced the 
Chevrolet Caprice, Impala SS and Cadillac Fleetwood. The only rear-drive 
passenger cars available from General Motors these days are the Firebird, 
Camaro and Corvette.<P>

<P>And at almost 3800 pounds, the question inevitably arises: Is the Park Avenue 
from Buick simply too big for a front-drive platform?<P>

<P>The answer: Yes and no. <P>

<P>No, if you are the "average" or "typical" Buick driver: A little older, 
fairly conservative, more likely to be in the far right lane of the freeway. 
Not, by any means, Mario Andretti looking for a car which can handle the 
curves of the Long Beach Grand Prix.<P>

<P>However, the answer is "yes" if you are an aggressive driver attempting to 
make use of the 240 horsepower available in the supercharger-equipped Park 
Avenue Ultra model. The car goes and stops great...as long as you are going 
or stopping in a fairly straight line. But stand on the power in a cornering 
situation, and even with the optional traction control system activated and 
working in your favor, the dreaded tendency of an overpowered front-drive car 
to "push" (or "understeer") is clearly evident.<P>

<P>That inclination of front-wheel drive cars was once best explained by 
champion NASCAR driver Ernie Irvan. "Push", said Irvan, "is when you see the 
crash you're about to be involved in".<P>

<P>What he meant is that when a vehicle understeers, it continues to go straight 
when you try to turn it. In the case of an oval track race car, that means 
the car goes straight (into the wall) even when you turn the wheel.<P>

<P>Rear-wheel drive cars, on the other hand, tend to "oversteer". This means 
that when you turn the steering wheel, the rear end of the car tries to come 
around to the front...and you spin. Anyone who has ever driven a rear-drive, 
rear-engine Porsche knows all too well what "oversteer" can do in a dicey 
driving situation.<P>

<P>On the Park Avenue, as it is a front-wheel drive car, the engine weight is on 
the drive wheels, and this makes it harder for the wheels to maneuver into a 
corner when you turn the steering wheel.<P>

<P>It's not an inherently dangerous condition; it's something most people who 
have driven a front-drive car have experienced at one time or another.<P>

<P>However, for someone coming out of a traditional American rear-wheel drive 
car and getting into a Park Avenue with it's front-drive platform, it 
definitely is something which can take some getting used to.<P>

<P>Apart from that major complaint (and keep in mind it will only be a major 
complaint for someone looking for a car with excellent cornering 
capabilities), the Park Avenue Ultra is a nice gem of a car.<P>

<P>The 3.8 liter V6 engine in the car produces 205 horsepower in its base 
version, but in the Ultra model, a supercharger is added to the mix and 240 
horses are trotted out for your driving pleasure. The Ultra supercharger 
"blower" also makes available a full 280 pounds feet of torque...that 
down-low power which gives Ultra a very satisfying "launch" from stop lights. 
This also makes for fine freeway on-ramp acceleration, and the standard four 
wheel anti-lock brake system makes stopping this almost two-ton missile an 
unexpected pleasure.<P>

<P>The best thing about that V6 engine is that there is nothing fancy about it. 
No multi-valve overhead cam set-up; you car nuts out there will recognize the 
arrangement in this engine as a traditional American pushrod assembly. And it 
works very well, delivering all that horsepower and the added bonus of more 
than 18 miles per gallon combined in city and highway driving...and that's 
with the driver pushing the engine pretty hard.<P>

<P>A supercharger pumps air into the top of engine's combustion chambers, adding 
extra levels of "atmospheres" and, simply put, making the fuel/air mixture 
"explosion" which drives the pistons all that more efficient. It does, 
essentially, the same thing a turbocharger does, but a turbocharger is 
powered by the pressure of the engine's exhaust gasses, so you have to wait a 
few seconds for a turbocharger to "spool up" and produce that extra power.<P> 

<P>A supercharger, on the other hand, runs directly off the engine and comes on 
as soon as you step on the gas pedal. Thus, there's no "turbo lag". And even 
though the engine is robbed of a tiny bit of power to operate the 
supercharger (a phenomenon called "parasitic drag"), the benefits far 
outweigh the drawbacks.<P>

<P>So, why isn't every car equipped with either a supercharger or turbocharger? 
The answer is easy: Cost and complexity. It costs more to make an engine with 
one of these units, and the car-makers are in the business of making the 
least-expensive vehicles they can and selling them for as much as they can. <P>

<P>In fact, turbochargers and superchargers provide so much extra bonus power 
and better fuel mileage and lower emissions that many large, expensive 
over-the-road diesel trucks are actually equipped with BOTH a supercharger 
and a turbocharger to get the most out of the engine.<P>

<P>Outside, the Park Avenue is elegant and understated. You would not be 
surprised to see a dignitary of some sort in the large, comfortable rear 
seat. With the optional heated front seats, the driver and passenger frontal 
area is a pleasure, especially with separate temperature controls for the air 
conditioning for the driver and passenger (a set-up which no doubt has saved 
many marriages!).<P>

<P>Park Avenue Ultra has every feature you can pack into a luxury car, save for 
a sunroof. There's a huge trunk, and a nifty computer monitoring system which 
tracks everything from tire pressure to the oil level. Dual front airbags are 
standard, of course, as is the very smooth shifting four-speed automatic 
transmission. <P>

<P>I have complaints about the placement of some controls and gauges, but I also 
have to keep in mind that this is NOT a "driver's car", no matter how 
powerful the engine may be. This is an "older" person's car, and not for an 
older "aggressive" driver, either.<P>

<P>This Park Avenue Ultra is a great car for the audience at which it is aimed. 
I'll always miss the full-size V8 rear-wheel drive Roadmaster, but times 
change and our vehicles must change with them. Priced in the mid-$30's, the 
Ultra is right on target. For traditional rear-drive V8 power and similar 
luxury appointments, as you'd find in a Lexus, BMW or Mercedes-Benz, you'd 
have to spend at least $10,000 more.<P>

<P>And you know what? At right around $30K, the Park Avenue without a 
supercharger is a darn nice car as well, at a very attractive price.<P>

<P>Buick was always known as "the doctor's car". This tag goes back to the days 
when doctors actually made house calls, and it was felt that to pull up to a 
patient's home in a Cadillac was too ostentatious...but the Buick allowed the 
family doc to ride in dependable luxury and comfort without being overly 
showy.<P>

<P>The Buick line still fills that bill. It's the next best thing to a Cadillac 
in the GM line-up and with Ultra, they have a four-door luxury car which is 
certainly not the best in the world, but surely can be considered one of the 
best in its class.<P>

<P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<BR><HR WIDTH=90%><BR>


<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=95% BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TR><TD>

<CENTER><A NAME="ev1"><B>1997 GENERAL MOTORS EV1</B></A></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="ev1.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>

<P>
By Steve Parker (c) 1996<P>



<P>You've seen the cute TV and print ads, you've heard all the hype. And now, you
can lease the car. But you can't buy one. Yet.<P>

<P>In other words, they're ba-a-ack!<P>

<P>Electric cars and trucks, which, believe it or not, once outsold
gasoline-powered vehicles in the USA (in some years before the 1920's), are
rearing their heads and being welcomed by a segment of the public eager for the
dual promises of cheap fuel and clean air.<P>

<P>The reason gasoline-powered cars replaced EVs early in this century was because
internal combustion engines were (and still are) much more efficient in turning
fuel into motivating power. And there was a hell of a lot more gasoline and oil
available than electricity in those days.<P>

<P>But the heavy batteries in these modern vehicles last only a few thousand miles
before they need to be replaced. The best of the EVs can go little more than 100
miles before needing a complete recharging, which can take up to 12 hours. EVs
have not been crash-tested by the government, and no one really knows for sure
what 1100 pounds or so of poisonous batteries will do in a high-speed crash.
There are real questions about the national infrastructure's ability to produce
the electricity needed to power EVs, not to mention the problem of disposing of
used, toxic batteries. And as far as the true expense of EVs...well, today it's
a given that we all will be paying for them in one way or another as public
utilities and municipalities, the first big users of EVs, will simply pass along
their costs to customers and citizens.<P>

<P>GM is building the first modern-day mass-market EV (called EV1) and is leasing
it at Saturn dealers, initially in California, Arizona and Nevada, for about
$35,000. That works out, with state and federal tax credits, to a 3-year lease
for California residents at a cost of about $450 a month.<P>

<P>Specially-trained and knowledgeable "EV specialists" at these select Saturn
dealers will treat the customer right; Saturn is already the King of customer
service and has set the customer satisfaction standard of the industry.<P>

<P>Many consumer groups are complaining that this vehicle, aimed at a very elite
audience, offers the buyers heavy tax credits which the rest of us wind up
paying for.<P>

<P>The car is being offered in the Southwest first for two reasons: 1) The smog
problem is pretty bad out here, and 2) Batteries do better in warm weather. Cold
temperatures kill their ability to hold a charge.<P>

<P>You'll also need to lease a 220-volt charger from your local utility for about
$50 a month, and pay an as-yet- undetermined amount to have the charger
installed on your property.<P>

<P>GM's Hughes Electronics subsidiary developed the nifty magnetic inductive
"paddle" you stick in the EV1 to recharge it...you can't get a shock from it,
even in a rainstorm.<P>

The EV1 is the first vehicle ever sold under the name "General Motors"; not
Buick, Cadillac, Olds, Pontiac or Chevy or GMC...just GM. You can look at this
two ways: Either no one Division in the Corporation wanted responsibility for
it, or, GM is so proud of the vehicle, they want everyone in the Corporation to
share in the honor.<P>

<P>The EV1 is hand-built at a small craft center in Lansing, Michigan. Not many
will ever be produced; perhaps a few thousand at the most. GM advertisements
will soon be shouting with glee that they are selling "all the EV1's being
built"...but keep in mind they won't be building that many to begin with. So
don't be fooled.<P>

<P>California determined some years ago that starting early in the 21st century,
major car-sellers in the state must augment their fleets with "zero-emissions"
vehicles, that is, vehicles without tailpipes. Worldwide, car-makers have
rallied against these rulings, and it appears that California has seemingly
blinked, and state agencies are backing away from these very strict rules,
having figured out their guidelinesare hindering development of other  very-low
emissions vehicles.<P>

<P>Car-makers in Europe and Japan are seriously working on hydrogen-powered
vehicles (whose emissions are pure water), and hybrid vehicles (cars and trucks
which use a combination of electric motors and batteries and small internal
combustion engines to keep the batteries charged).  But General Motors decided
they better have a showcase electric vehicle to feature in California...hence
the EV1.<P>

<P>But keep in mind...you still have to make the electricity for these cars
somewhere, and while it might give EV1 drivers a warm and fuzzy feeling to have
no emissions coming out of their short-ranged, expensive vehicles, there will be
a lot more coal being burned at power plants in the Four Corners area to keep
these cars on the road.<P>

<P>The EV1 is the most aerodynamic production car sold in the world. It even has
rear fender skirts to help the air flow smoothly over the car. The special tires
run at a very high 50 psi of air pressure, meaning the ride in the car is quite
stiff...you feel every pebble in the road.<P>

<P>It weighs about 3200 pounds, 1100 pounds of which are low-tech lead acid
batteries arranged in a 'T' shape under the car. The body panels are lightweight
and expensive plastic, just like on a Saturn.<P>

<P>EV1 comes complete with a heat pump-type air conditioner which does not work
impressively at all, but it is full of very hi-tech gimmicks like a regenerative
braking system which takes the heat generated when you hit the brakes and turns
it into electricity to help keep the batteries charged.<P>

<P>The front-wheel drive car seats only two, and has a trunk large enough to hold a
set of golf clubs.<P>

<P>The car is fun to drive, no doubt about that. It is virtually silent, and has a
lot of surprising power off the line with its 147 horsepower motor. Electric
motors have a lot of torque when they first come on, so the car's "launch" is
quite impressive.<P>

<P>GM says EV1 can cruise up to about 100 miles before needing a complete recharge,
depending on many conditions. But, if you live like most of us and never really
know when you're going to get stuck in a freeway traffic jam, you might leave
the EV1 at home unless you know the roads are going to be wide open. Running out
of power in EV1 presents an entirely different set of problems than running out
of gas in the old family four-door.<P>

<P>The true long-term, common-sense future for EVs? Probably hybrid vehicles, with
a combination of batteries and a small gas or diesel engine which serves as an
on-board recharging station. The longer-term future will see ultra capacitors in
use (like the ones used to store up energy for your camera's flash) along with
flywheels, which store energy mechanically rather than chemically (actor Kevin
Costner is a big investor in a flywheel development company).<P>

<P>We'll also see hydrogen used to power internal combustion engines and the use of
super-exotic fuel cells, like those used on spacecraft. Mercedes-Benz already
has fleets of vehicles running around Europe testing both these systems.<P>

<P>Finally, there's solar power. For the past several years, days-long solar
powered races have been run in (sunny) locations around the world testing the
mettle of teams ranging from universities to major car manufacturers.<P>

<P>The true beauty of all these technologies? They already exist and are in use in
various industries...they just need to be developed to point where millions of
them can be made and sold to the decidedly untechnical drivers of America.<P>

<P>And just like the space program, the consumer spin-offs from the development of
all sorts of EVs will benefit society.<P>

<P>GM is to be commended for being the first on the block with an EV1-type vehicle,
but I had hoped that the days of consumers doing the last 100,000 miles of
research and development for GM were over in the 1970s.<P>

<P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>



<BR><BR>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=2>
Steve Parker
