<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=95% BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TR><TD>

<CENTER><A NAME="cdc"><B>1997 CADILLAC DEVILLE CONCOURS</B></A></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="cdc.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>
<P>


<P>This is the longest, heaviest Cadillac you can buy these days. And in many ways,
for those of us who remember BIG American cars from the past few decades, this
auto is a thing of wonder.<P>

<P>Why?<P>

<P>Well, imagine if you will a 17 1/2 foot long, 4052 pound four-door car with a V8
engine producing a crisp 300 horsepower, carrying five adults in world-class
comfort...and doing all this while getting you an average of more than 17 miles
per gallon and producing emissions barely more noxious than a baby's breath.<P>

<P>They don't make the Fleetwood anymore (the plant in Arlington, TX where they
used to make it is now in the business of turning out the luxury vehicles of the
'90s...trucks), so if you're looking for sheer power and bombast, DeVille
Concours is your only choice if a Cadillac it must be. Sad, isn't it? I mean, a
world where the Cadillac Fleetwood is no longer made...barely worth living in!<P>

<P>But I digress into sentimentality...<P>

<P>The DeVille line has been completely recast for the 1997 model year, and I think
they have done just about everything as right as can be expected from
Cadillac...which is pretty damn close to perfection.<P>

<P>Behold the wonder of DeVille Concours! It has all the elegance and style and
comfort you'd expect from a (ahem) $46,000 land yacht, and it comes with an
amazing array of seamless, transparent hi-tech systems which rival the Space
Shuttle.<P>

<P>All 1997 DeVilles have restyled sheet metal outside and restyled interiors and
instrument panels inside, with dual front seat airbags and super-hip side
airbags for front seat occupants as well. The rear wheel wells were opened up
and the rear wheels pulled out to give the car just a bit of a younger, less
formal look.<P>

<P>DeVille is Cadillac's biggest seller, and has been since just about anyone can
remember. This is not a car the Division can afford to make a mistake with. Even
though the company knows they have to attract younger buyers, they can not in
any way offend their traditional, loyal (translation: old) buyers, and in the
DeVille Concours they have developed a very nice package of power and comfort
and convenience which should appeal to buyers ranging in age from 45 to 95 (and
let's face it...most folks under 45 won't be able to afford this car, anyway).<P>

<P>There are three different DeVille models for 1997, all with the highly-venerated
Northstar front-wheel drive "system", but only the Concours model allows this
wondrous engine to develop its current full potential of 300 horses (the other
models are held to only 275).<P>

<P>That engine has only gotten better since its introduction at the start of this
decade in the Seville model. (Oldsmobile likes it so much they use a smaller
version of it in their Aurora).<P>

<P>It's a 4.6 liter V8 with dual overhead cams and a total of 32 (count 'em)
valves. It is mated to what is without a doubt the smoothest-shifting four-speed
automatic in the industry.<P>

<P>The front-wheel drive system exhibits all the understeer you'd expect in a car
this heavy and powerful (that's the tendency of the car to try and go straight
even when you're turning the steering wheel). However, let's be honest about
this: Most DeVille Concours drivers are not going to be very aggressive on the
roadways, and the front-drive understeer probably will never get them into
trouble. In fact, most unsophisticated drivers wouldn't be able to tell you if
this car is driven by the front or rear wheels.<P>

<P>DeVille Concours comes with standard traction control for the front wheels and a
newly-developed and standard stability enhancement system to detect and help
correct rear-end fishtailing. Of course there are anti-lock brakes on all four
corners.<P>

<P>The car I tested for a week came equipped with GM's OnStar cellular phone
security system. It's about a $1000 option available on all Cadillacs (except
Catera) in 1997 and will eventually be available throughout the complete GM line
of pricier cars and trucks.<P>

<P>Here's what OnStar does: Pushing one button on the Hughes Electronics hands-free
cellular phone puts you instantly in touch with an operator in a central service
center (currently located in Michigan, but eventually there will be centers all
over the nation). That operator, once you give him or her your personal code
number, will know (through a satellite Global Positioning System built by
industry-leader Trimble) your exact location to within a few yards, anywhere in
the nation. The operator can give you directions to specific locations if you
are lost, or direct you to the nearest restaurant of your choice, or a hospital,
police station, etc.<P>

<P>Locked your keys in the car?<P>

<P>Get on any phone, call the service center, and the OnStar operator can (get
this) unlock the doors for you.<P>

<P>Lost your car in a big parking lot?<P>

<P>Call the OnStar center and the operator will make your Cadillac flash its
headlights and beep its horn.<P>

<P>If any of the airbags in the car is deployed for any reason, the cell phone in
the car automatically calls the OnStar center and they alert local authorities
to your exact location.<P>

<P>OnStar's secret?<P>

<P>It's wired into the car's engine and chassis computers. The possibilities are
about limitless. For instance, there's no reason why OnStar operators could not,
sometime in the near future, totally disable your car if you call and report it
stolen...and alert local cops to the car's location.<P>

<P>It's worth a trip to your local Cadillac dealer just to try-out OnStar...it's
that much fun! (Lincoln offers a similar system on some of their models called
RESCU).<P>

<P>There are some things about the car I do not like. The memory seat system is way
too complicated and has too many items tied into it...including the radio
station pre-sets. The radio itself has too many unnecessary audio
settings...Caddy is guilty here of using technology just because it's there.<P>

<P>The car does not have seat heaters, front or rear, and at these prices it should
have them all over the place.<P>

<P>But really, I don't have a lot of other objections. I'd like the CD changer to
be in the passenger compartment, as it is in the similarly-priced Lexus LS400,
and not in the trunk, as it is in this DeVille Concours.<P>

<P>Final verdict? If this is what Cadillac considers their top of the line
performance/comfort model for the late 1990s, they could have done a lot worse.
The car is classy, elegant, capable, as safe as a car can be in the late 20th
century, and does it all subtly and effortlessly.<P>

<P>Good on you, Cadillac. This car is a winner we can all aspire to.<P>


<P>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>


<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=95% BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TR><TD>

<CENTER><A NAME="pgpg"><B>PONTIAC GRAND PRIX GTP</B></A></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="pgpg.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>


<P>It isn't often that I come across a car which seems "worth the money." And 
more often than not, that statement can only said to be true of very 
expensive cars; cars with outlandish interior appointments, incredible 
drivetrains and sophisticated styling.<P>

<P>Almost never are cars in the mid-price range "worth the money". Yet I think I 
have found one for you, and one of the best things about it is that it is an 
American car with the best musclecar "pedigree" you can find anywhere in the 
worldwide automotive industry.<P>

<P>The Pontiac Grand Prix with the optional GTP supercharger package is 
available for 1997 as either a four-door or two-door, and the car is without 
a doubt "worth the money".<P>

<P>In fact, if this car were priced even a few thousand dollars MORE than its 
sticker price, it would still most surely be "worth the money". You can't say 
this about many cars and truck sold in our country in the 1997 model year, 
and to be able to say it about an all-American performance coupe and sedan is 
more than a pleasure...it's almost a thrill!<P>

<P>Coming in at under $25,000, the Grand Prix GTP offers 240 horsepower, a 
sumptuous interior and a "boy racer" exterior appearance which will turn all 
the heads in your neighborhood. Plus, it gets all that horsepower through the 
use of a supercharger...just like the Big Boys at the drag strip get THEIR 
extra motivation!<P>

<P>In fact, one of the few cars in the "worth the price" league I can think of 
to compare to GTP to in terms of performance is the mighty little four-door 
Acura Integra equipped with Honda's super high-tech four-cylinder VTEC engine 
package. But, in terms of styling and comfort, the Pontiac simply blows that 
car away.
<P>
<P>The Grand Prix will hold four fully-grown adults in comfort with no problem 
at all. And the front-driver packs the kind of whallop which can make taking 
your best friends to the movies quite a joy ride in itself...who said getting 
there was only "half" the fun?  I can remember when I got my first motorcycle 
back in 1973...I would run ANY errand for my parents, the thing was so much 
fun to ride!<P>

<P>For men and women with that kind of memory of their first car or truck or 
motorcycle, this could very well be the car for you, to help you through that 
mid-life excitement "crisis" you're going through right now.<P>

<P>Not only that, but this will definitely be one of the vehicles to help the 
Pontiac Division of General Motors through the mid-life crisis they are 
currently undergoing!<P>

<P>Not so very long ago, Pontiac was selling, regularly, more than 500,000 cars 
a year. Remember those days? Oldsmobile was selling more than 1,000,000 cars 
a year, Cadillac was the best car your money could buy, and the thought of 
driving any import other than a British sports car was simply ludicrous.<P>

<P>In 1964, Pontiac stunned the world with the introduction of the GTO, the 
world's first true factory-built musclecar, and it was marketed as such by 
the company. What Pontiac did was stuff the big 389 cubic inch V8 into the 
smallish Pontiac LeMans as an option package...and voila! The GTO, and a lot 
of automotive history, was made.<P>

<P>But even before the GTO left the Pontiac plant, the company was already 
making a wonderful "personal luxury coupe", the Grand Prix. Due to the 
determination of Pontiac's then-new General Manager, Semon E. "Bunkie" 
Kundsen, to make Pontiac a GM Division idolized by the youth of the nation, 
Pontiac created a car whose name lives on today.<P>

<P>Cadillac was supposed to get this car first; but Caddy didn't need the car 
because their sales were very good. They couldn't build enough cars to 
fulfill their dealers' orders. The last thing they needed was a new model to 
try and sell. Buick Division needed help and GM eventually gave them the 
Caddy design to make their own, and they did, as the Riviera, in 1964.<P>

<P>These were the days when each GM Division was essentially its own car 
company; the sharing of anything, from platforms to engineers to engines, was 
unheard of. Each Division had their own factories and their own complete (and 
huge) staffs of thousands of automotive specialists. So when Bunkie Knudsen 
told his Division to build a luxury sport coupe (two-door) and get it on the 
market FAST, before Buick or Caddy or anyone else, they could do it...without 
any other GM Division really knowing what they were up to. <P>

<P>Grand Prix sold great right out of the chute and sales didn't slow down for 
several years. But starting in the mid-1970s, with government mandates for 
emissions and fuel mileage targets, cars like Grand Prix began dying their 
slow death. The country, in the throes of the Vietnam war and the beginnings 
of environmental consciousness, didn't want two-door performance/luxury cars 
anymore which could barely manage more than 12 miles per gallon. Those days 
were over, and Grand Prix seemed to be over as well.<P>

<P>So starting in the '70s and throughout the '80s we saw various incarnations 
of the Grand Prix, almost all of them terrible. When a four-door model was 
introduced, it was regarded as a sacrilege by Grand Prix aficianados. There 
were some signs that Grand Prix might be ready for a revival in the very late 
'80s, and the car we have today is surely a worthy modern-day successor to 
the original Grand Prix, which was introduced more than 30 years ago.<P>

<P>This all-new car is a revelation. Dual front seat airbags, a great driver's 
cockpit where all the gauges and switchgear are right where they should be, 
four wheel anti-lock disc brakes, traction control, a four-speed automatic 
transmission (no which available) which can handle the 280 foot pounds of 
torque produced by the supercharged engine, a powerful exhaust note and 
more...Grand Prix GTP is a musclecar for the '90s and beyond.<P>

<P>Each Grand Prix model is a nice car at a nice price. Engines available 
include the 160 horsepower 3.1 liter V6 and the 195 horsepower 3.8 liter V6, 
an engine which GM is using in all sorts of cars and trucks to prove that a 
"low-tech" pushrod engine can compete favorably in today's multi-valve, dual 
overhead cam world. <P>

<P>Add a supercharger to that same 3.8 liter unit and you wind up with 240 
horsepower, instantly available at the touch of the accelerator...you don't 
have to wait for the power to "spool up" as you do with many turbochargers; 
with a supercharger, the extra power is right there, right now. Even at 
slightly over 3400 pounds, this family fun four-door simply gets up and GOES!<P>

<P>Pontiac had a great opportunity with this car which they screwed up. They 
Division got permission from NASCAR to run the 1997 Grand Prix during the 
1996 NASCAR stock car racing season, before it was available for sale to the 
public. I think NASCAR has done this only once before in the past.<P>

<P>So here is Pontiac with their all-new car with the great old name in front of 
a total of hundreds of millions of spectators and TV viewers during an entire 
NASCAR season, and the car barely makes a dent in the Ford T-Bird/Chevrolet 
Monte Carlo domination of the series racing .<P>

<P>For the 1997 NASCAR season, Pontiac promises they will be back and strongly 
so, with some of NASCAR's most famous teams running their cars. This is 
certainly something Pontiac should have had assured for the 1996 season, 
before they ever made a commitment to NASCAR to publicly introduce  the car 
through that series. <P>

<P>Pontiac's General Manager John Middlebrook has, in the past year, left the 
Division to go head up Chevrolet, the most plum job at GM, a job which is 
often the precursor to someone becoming President of the Corporation.<P>

<P>In Middlebrook's place is Roy Roberts, heading up a newly-married Pontiac and 
GMC Division (many Pontiac dealers were carrying GMC trucks anyway). Roberts 
is not a big race fan, but he comes from a manufacturing background so he 
sure knows how to BUILD cars, the kid  of cars the public likes. Roberts is 
also the first black GM Divisional chieftain and the highest-ranking black 
man anywhere in the world automotive industry. He'll want to do a good job, 
and part of that good job will be supporting his Division's racing division 
and getting them to win some NASCAR races.<P>

<P>There you have it...a great new car with a great, well-known name (hell 
they're even using the "Wide Track" line to sell this new car, a line 
originated in the early 1960s)...and yes, in its supercharged GTP version, it 
IS worth the money!<P>


<P>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=95% BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TR><TD>

<CENTER><A NAME="cvm"><B>1997 CHEVROLET VENTURE MINIVAN</B></A></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="cvm.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>
<P>

<P>Chevrolet, along with other General Motors Divisions, has had a tough time in 
a lot of markets in the past 10 years, but none tougher than in one of the 
most important segments of the marketplace...minivans.<P>

<P>Now, Chevy, Pontiac and Oldsmobile (and soon Buick) have brand-new minivans 
on the market, designed and produced in part in conjunction with GM's 
European affiliates. Now, I really liked the previous generation of GM 
minivans, derided almost universally as the "Dustbusters" because of their 
unusual front-end shape and steeply raked windshields.<P>

<P>There really wasn't much wrong with those minivans that a little creative 
marketing and advertising could not have solved for GM, but The Corporation 
has been lacking in those areas for some time until very recently. And GM has 
a bad insecurity problem concerning minivans now because of their failure in 
the market, so rather than gussie-up their existing minivans and roll them 
out as "new and improved", they have spent several billion dollars developing 
these all-new models.<P>

<P>Has their money been well spent? Probably not, is the short answer. I think 
GM should have had more confidence in their previous models, added a fourth 
door to all of them (which they did do with the Oldsmobile Silhouette) and 
re-introduced them with facelifts and some spiffy advertising and marketing 
programs.<P>

<P>Remember the great line in the movie "Get Shorty", when John Travolta finds 
out his rental car is actually an Olds minivan? "It's the Cadillac of 
minivans," says the rental shuttle driver to Travolta...and that becomes a 
running gag throughout the movie. Well, that product placement in that movie 
(a project done by Vista Group of Burbank) was the BEST thing that ever 
happened to the GM minivans...and in true GM fashion, they did NOTHING with 
it in their advertising or marketing programs. Here it was, handed to them on 
a silver platter, and they did not take advantage of the public awareness of 
their product generated by this smash-hit movie at all. I guess they figured 
it was better to spend several billion on an all-new model...oh, well...<P>

<P>And what can you say about minivans which hasn't been said already...100 
times?<P>

<P>While most industry analysts say the minivan was introduced for the first 
time in America by the Chrysler Corporation in the mid-80s, minivans had 
actually been around a lot longer than that in this marketplace. Anyone 
remember the Volkswagen Vanagon and its predecessors?<P>

<P>The Japanese have never learned how to make a good minivan on their own...it 
was a vehicle which never made sense to them in their home markets. Many 
early efforts from Mitsubishi, Toyota and Nissan were sales disasters, and 
for good reasons. Even today, Toyota and Honda (with their cute little 
Odyssey) have yet to put a V6 in their vehicles...they will come in the next 
year or so.<P>

<P>Lee Iacocca is credited with steering Chrysler into the minivan market, but 
it was really one of the product planners he took with him when he was fired 
from Ford and was hired (for $1 a year) by Chrysler who had the idea. Henry 
Ford II himself rejected the minivan concept for Ford, which opened the door 
for Chrysler to take advantage of Ford's lack of foresight.<P>

<P>The main ideas behind the minivan concept? That it would hold passengers 
comfortably and, most importantly, fit into the average American garage.<P>

<P>The Chrysler minivans were hits from the first day they went on sale and 
their domination of the market continues to this day. Of more than one 
million minivans now sold annually in America, fully half of them are 
Chryslers, Dodges or Plymouths. Every other car company is still playing 
catch-up, more than a decade after the American introduction of the minivan.<P>

<P>So, enter gigantic GM. With their first-generation of minivans unadulterated 
failures, here they are with their latest efforts. The Pontiac is still the 
Trans Sport, the Olds is still the Silhouette but the Chevy gets a new name, 
changed from Lumina to Venture. And the latest word from GM is that Buick 
will have its own minivan based on the same platform by the year 2002...so GM 
will be fighting itself once again with four of their 7 Divisions selling 
essentially the same vehicle.<P>

<P>Add to this the fact that many industry analysts believe if there is one 
segment in the business ready to cool off, it is the minivan segment, and you 
have GM jumping with both feet into a now-hot area of sales which may cool 
very rapidly.<P>

<P>Both the short and long-wheelbase versions of the Venture come with 180 
horsepower 3.4 liter V6 engines...and all the bells and whistles you'd expect 
from a late 20th century front-wheel drive minivan platform. Anti-lock 
brakes, four-speed automatic transmission (only), high-end sound and AC 
systems...it's all here.<P>

<P>I found the Venture to be quite delightful...it tracks well and powerfully 
and even on the most uneven and scored freeway lanes it went right where I 
pointed it and never drifted away from my control. <P>

<P>Gauges and switchgear are right where they should be; the optional fourth 
sliding door can be opened electronically by remote control and is a very 
nice feature, especially when you are walking up to the vehicle with a lot of 
packages and want to get them into the van quickly.<P>

<P>In other words, the Venture is a winner...in a field where there are already 
a lot of winners. Prices are comparable to the Chrysler-made vehicles, though 
the Plymouth Voyager still appears to be the best buy in the minivan 
marketplace. Ford does not yet offer a fourth-door on their Windstar (and 
will not until at least 1998...in an incredible, costly and rare Ford 
product-planning mistake this decade) so I can't count them as among the 
"best" out there from the Big Three.<P>

<P>GM is going to find the exact same problems with this generation of minivans 
as they did with their last...they have some great vehicles which will not 
move off the showroom floors if they can't give the public a compelling 
reason to come into the showrooms and test-drive them. This very serious 
problem is what plagued GM with their minivans the past five years, and 
instead of improving the marketing and advertising of the product, they 
re-did the product.<P>

<P>When you are as big as GM, you can get away with that type of thinking...but 
only for a finite period of time.<P>

<P>GM has the winning product in these all-new minivans; it's going to be up to 
the GM marketing gurus to get Americans to want to buy them.<P>


<P>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>




<BR><BR>

<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=2>
Steve Parker
<BR>
