<HEAD>
<TITLE> DocumentDescriptions</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<P>
<P>
<TABLE border>
<TR valign=top><TD>
<P><IMG src="122_0.gif"></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P><H2>World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children</H2></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><IMG src="122_1.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><H2>Family</H2><BR>

<H4>Families are the first nurturers, educators and protectors of children and their rights.  Family values are essential to the child's perception of itself and the world in which it lives.  When, for whatever reason, the family does not fulfil this obligation and trust, the child's first line of defence against an incomprehensible and unsafe world breaks down</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Worldwide, researchers have noted the strong correlation between family abuse of children, especially girls, and the drive to enter the sex trade.  The mother, in particular, plays a central role in her daughter's life decisions.  Widespread evidence of family involvement in the direct commercial sexual exploitation of children is disturbing but perhaps not surprising, given the heavy burden of severe economic inequities and hardships under which many families labour.  Carriers of poverty and despair, inherited and newly dislocating values that view children and property and hence as a source of economic support, families pass these values and their consequences on to their children.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>In fact, most often, parents who sell their children into the sex trade do so unwittingly.  They are told, and believe, that their children are going into domestic service or some other form of labour, or marriage.  Many remain ignorant of the eventual fate of their working children.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>However, some parents sell their children into the sex trade in full awareness of where they are going, although not always of the potential consequences of such activity.  It has been reported that, in some parts of Asia, families who traditionally have wished for sons to work for the family now hope to have girl children to sell, since their earning potential is greater.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Poverty is often quoted as the underlying cause of sale of children into labour, but it is important to note that not all poor families sell their children.   What pushes a poor family to make money by selling a child has been called poverty plus the closing of options.  It often involves an already poor family facing unemployment, forced migration, stigmatisation by the community, substance dependency or raised expectations from contact with consumerism.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Sometimes, however, a child is sold into commercial sex by parents who have themselves sexually or otherwise abused the child.  The child is then seen as ready for sex and able to earn money for the family.  The handing-over of a sum of money to the parents puts the child into debt bondage, a situation in which the child is forced to provide sex to earn money to repay the familys debt to the exploiter.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Another thing to note when looking at family issues involved in commercial sexual exploitation of children is how the family reacts when a child who has worked in the sex trade is able to escape and return home (sometimes alone, sometimes helped by organisations working to release children from exploitation).  Sometimes the family cannot  or will not  cope with the stigma of having a former prostitute in the family, and rejects the child.  There is then a great danger that the child might return to prostitution, or be returned to it.  The cycle begins again.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>There are also indications that older siblings or other female family members take up or contribute to prostitution to protect  younger siblings from being pulled into the trade.</H4>
<P><CENTER><hr><P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="factsheets.htm">Factsheets</A> | <A HREF="theme.htm">Theme Papers</A> | <A HREF="declaration.htm">Declaration</A> | <A HREF="links.htm">Links</A> | <A HREF="press.htm">Press materials</A>  <BR><A HREF="reports.htm">Congress reports</A> | <A HREF="intpress.htm">Interesting press</A> <BR><A HREF="default.htm">CSEC Home Page</A></P></CENTER><hr>
