<TABLE border>
<TR valign=top><TD>
<P><IMG src="122_0.gif"></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P><H2>World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children</H2></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><IMG src="122_1.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><H2>Children as commodities</H2><BR>

<H4>Commercial sexual exploitation of children has many characteristics of an organised industry sector:  from small businesses to large enterprises, with bank accounts, advertising campaigns and glossy brochures.  There are marketers who use technology to sell the product, hierarchies of profit-takers (always with the child on the bottom of the ladder) and strategic planners who work to protect and promote good business.  This industry is a flagrant abuse of children, involving deception, kidnapping, enslavement, smuggling, false passports, bribery, and corruption at many levels.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>In recent years, the demand for children for sex has increased.  The reasons for this include rising incomes and  purchasing power which have put children as goods within the reach of more people.  Misconceptions about childrens immunity to infection including HIV/AIDS, a proliferation of entertainment services which titillate and tease, and the growing consumerism of recently industrialised societies also create an environment in which children are devalued, reduced to the level of consumer disposables, available for sale and abuse.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Media interest in child pornography and prostitution can unintentionally fuel demand, and the ease of access of information both opens up supply routes and increases demand.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>The same causal factors are at play in both demand and supply.  However, what comes into particular play in the supply side of the equation is human greed.  These economic and sociological factors provide the supply of children for sale and perpetuate the opportunities for the middle man (or woman)  the pimp, brothel owner, madam or other racketeer whose sole aim is to make money from child sex  who bridges the gap between supply and demand, ensuring supply and fuelling demand.  </H4>
<P><CENTER><hr><P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="factsheets.htm">Factsheets</A> | <A HREF="theme.htm">Theme Papers</A> | <A HREF="declaration.htm">Declaration</A> | <A HREF="links.htm">Links</A> | <A HREF="press.htm">Press materials</A>  <BR><A HREF="reports.htm">Congress reports</A> | <A HREF="intpress.htm">Interesting press</A> <BR><A HREF="default.htm">CSEC Home Page</A></P></CENTER><hr>
