<P>
<TABLE border>
<TR valign=top><TD>
<P><IMG src="122_0.gif"></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P><H2>World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children</H2></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><IMG src="122_1.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><H2>Rescue and reintegration</H2><BR>

<H4>What happens to children rescued from prostitution?  Often nothing, which is part of the problem.  NGOs working in this field conduct rescue missions to deliver children from the slavery of commercial sexual exploitation, but support services are not yet developed to cope with the overwhelming needs of rescued children:  needs which embrace health services including psychological and trauma support, the difficulties -- perhaps even impossibility -- of reintegrating sexually exploited children into their communities, and the stigma and lack of understanding facing them.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>First of all, children rescued from prostitution must be returned, where possible, to good health.  They have been physically and mentally abused, and their physical and mental health must be re-established.  Sometimes the physical harm cannot be entirely undone:  children who are HIV-positive, for example, or who have become infertile through STD infection, will continue to live with the results of their exploitation.  Mental good health is supported through counselling specifically aimed at children who have been exploited.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Rehabilitation also aims to help survivors of commercial sexual exploitation to reduce their vulnerability in future.  Children receive training in skills which will allow them to earn a living and support themselves.  They may have the opportunity to live in a shelter specifically designed to put training and counselling at their disposal.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Perhaps the most difficult step on the road to rehabilitation, however, is restoration of family and friends, of home life and self-esteem within society.  In many instances, children who have been exploited in prostitution are not accepted back into the family or community because of the stigma associated with the work they have been forced to perform.  This is particularly true if they are HIV-positive and additionally in such cases, the question of confidentiality of the HIV status of a child further complicates the situation.  In such cases, a new home must be found in order to prevent the child from falling back into the grips of exploiters.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>The vulnerability of children who have been commercially sexually exploited is great, and it is vital that, once rescued, they should not be put into a position of increased or similar vulnerability, either because they have no family or community support, no means to earn a living, illegal status in a country, poor health or any form of dependency.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Many NGOs and international agencies work across this range of issues to provide support for the rescued child and to build a future for the child in which he or she will not be exploited again and will not become an exploiter in turn.</H4>
<P><CENTER><hr><P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="factsheets.htm">Factsheets</A> | <A HREF="theme.htm">Theme Papers</A> | <A HREF="declaration.htm">Declaration</A> | <A HREF="links.htm">Links</A> | <A HREF="press.htm">Press materials</A>  <BR><A HREF="reports.htm">Congress reports</A> | <A HREF="intpress.htm">Interesting press</A> <BR><A HREF="default.htm">CSEC Home Page</A></P></CENTER><hr>
