<P>
<P>
<TABLE border>
<TR valign=top><TD>
<P><IMG src="122_0.gif"></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P><H2>World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children</H2></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><IMG src="122_1.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><H2>Technology and the media</H2><BR>

<H4>The enormous advances in technology have made child pornography  a major factor in commercial sexual exploitation of children  easier, cheaper, difficult to detect and easy to distribute.  Camcorders, VCRs, home editing desks, computer-generated graphics and editing:  all these have moved the child porn industry into the home, where it is more difficult to police and has developed into a multi-million dollar industry.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>The advent of the Internet has opened up new channels of information for those seeking access to children for sex.  The inter-active nature of Internet technology means that information can be shared real-time and special requests dealt with by procurers and suppliers of children for sex.  Pornographic images and video clips can be uploaded almost anonymously and downloaded equally anonymously.  At the moment, the only intervention point for law enforcers seems to be via service providers, who can refuse to sell space to anyone they know is providing child sex materials.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Beyond technology, the press and media also play a major role in the domain of commercial sexual exploitation of children, both positive and negative.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>On the negative side, the media have undoubtedly contributed to the liberalisation of sexually explicit imagery, and to shifts in moral values.  Satellite technology, international travel and a breakdown in support infrastructures means that such images are often received in a non-supportive context, or even in a whole society for which they were not specifically intended.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Many television viewers are adolescents, and the attitude of some media to adolescence itself -- the so-called &quot;Beavis and Butthead syndrome&quot; which shows adolescents as worthless and easily exploitable -- can contribute to young people's images of themselves and their place in society.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Also on the negative side, many well-meaning reporters investigating commercial sexual exploitation of children have reported  information which has helped exploiters  street names, location of villages, readily identifiable pictures of beaches and so on.  Often, too, the temptation to broadcast or print sensational pictures has itself verged on pornography and thus on exploitation, and has given rise to criticisms of titillation television.  In a few cases, journalists have unwittingly corrupted evidence by paying for stories, enabling criminals to escape conviction on a technicality.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>But the role of the press and media can also be immensely positive.  Journalists have access to information which others ordinarily find difficult to obtain.  They have worked hand-in-hand with non-governmental organisations and police to locate exploiters and places of exploitation and uncover them, and they have then reported arrests and convictions, contributing to deterrence.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>The press and media can also contribute greatly to advocacy, underlining positive moral values and human rights.  They can support positive family values and inform parents when their children are at risk.  They help the children themselves to draw moral lines on their own behaviour and to identify risk factors or situations in which they might be endangered.  They are the most powerful educators.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Most important of all, press and media have recognised that they are important players in the whole area of commercial sexual exploitation of children, and are actively engaged in debate to examine their role and commit to the ethical underpinnings of their calling.</H4>
<P><CENTER><hr><P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="factsheets.htm">Factsheets</A> | <A HREF="theme.htm">Theme Papers</A> | <A HREF="declaration.htm">Declaration</A> | <A HREF="links.htm">Links</A> | <A HREF="press.htm">Press materials</A>  <BR><A HREF="reports.htm">Congress reports</A> | <A HREF="intpress.htm">Interesting press</A> <BR><A HREF="default.htm">CSEC Home Page</A></P></CENTER><hr>
