<P>
<P><H2>World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children</H2></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><IMG src="122_1.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><H2>Child sex tourism</H2><BR>

<H4>Sexually-oriented tourism is a developed arm of the exploitation industry, with its own paraphernalia of promotional materials ranging from glossy brochures, through organised clubs to the availability of tour information on the Internet.  This interactive technology makes information and advice available and allows clients to customize their holiday requirements in advance.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Developed sex tour industries have been documented in the Philippines, Cambodia and Thailand.  More recently, sex tours from North America to Brazil and the Dominican Republic have increased.  In Sri Lanka, several thousand boys are reported to be available for sex with male tourists in some areas.  It is likely that sex tours in the countries of Eastern Europe are increasing.   Today, also, most sex tourists travel singly or in pairs on normal air flights.  In the past, sex tours were easy to identify and to condemn, so those who organise sex tours today send their customers in a less obtrusive manner.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Since 1990 ECPAT (End Child Prostitution in Asian Tourism) has been monitoring and acting against sex tourism in Asia and, in recent times, elsewhere.   ECPAT has been successful in promoting transnational governmental cooperation, extraterritorial legislation which allows governments to bring their nationals to trial for crimes committed in other countries, and in drawing public attention to the arrest, detention and conviction of paedophiles engaged in sex tourism.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>ECPAT has also successfully engaged the interest and commitment of world tourism authorities, travel agents. holiday guide publishers and tour promoters in actively working against sex tourism.</H4>
<P><CENTER><hr><P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="factsheets.htm">Factsheets</A> | <A HREF="theme.htm">Theme Papers</A> | <A HREF="declaration.htm">Declaration</A> | <A HREF="links.htm">Links</A> | <A HREF="press.htm">Press materials</A>  <BR><A HREF="reports.htm">Congress reports</A> | <A HREF="intpress.htm">Interesting press</A> <BR><A HREF="default.htm">CSEC Home Page</A></P></CENTER><hr>
