<TITLE> DocumentDescriptions</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<P>
<P>
<TABLE border>
<TR valign=top><TD>
<P><IMG src="122_0.gif"></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P><H2>World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children</H2></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><IMG src="122_1.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><H2>Stopping it</H2><BR>

<H4>The counter-offensive against commercial sexual exploitation of children is working at many different levels.  Non-governmental organisations and UN agencies  have for some years been involved in investigation and monitoring, identifying children at risk and already involved, and identifying and bringing exploiters to justice where possible.  NGOs have also been instrumental in encouraging governments to enact extraterritoriality laws, and have worked with tourism organisations to mobilise their help in combating child sex tourism.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>The NGO coalition ECPAT has published widely, in many languages, and has mobilised the press and media to raise public awareness to unprecedented levels.  It was thanks to an initiative of ECPAT that the first World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children was proposed and that the Swedish Government offered to host it in Stockholm in August 1996.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Recovery and reintegration work is complex.  Some communities find it difficult to accept returning children, and it then falls to NGOs to help integrate these children into new communities.  NGOs also set up centres for those who can return, and offer vocational training to give the children a means to earn their livelihood, counselling and other services.  More than a thousand NGOs work with street children.  Others work specifically with HIV-positive children and in other areas of health care.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>UN agencies work alongside NGOs, for example in Cambodia, on projects to monitor and mitigate trafficking of children.  More specifically, UNICEF and NGOs work together  on long-term prevention programmes and in the area of policy formulation, advocacy and regulation.  UNICEFs focus includes girls education, education for street children, health outreach, policy development and training on child rights, communication and advocacy.  UNICEF also supports programmes and focuses on preventive measures.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>UN agencies and NGOS are also actively involved in encouraging and contributing to the training of legal professionals, police enforcement agencies and others in areas where the commercial sexual exploitation of children is involved, for example in cross-border operations.</H4>
<P>
<P><CENTER><hr><P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="factsheets.htm">Factsheets</A> | <A HREF="theme.htm">Theme Papers</A> | <A HREF="declaration.htm">Declaration</A> | <A HREF="links.htm">Links</A> | <A HREF="press.htm">Press materials</A>  <BR><A HREF="reports.htm">Congress reports</A> | <A HREF="intpress.htm">Interesting press</A> <BR><A HREF="default.htm">CSEC Home Page</A></P></CENTER><hr>
