<BODY>

<P>
<P>
<TABLE border>
<TR valign=top><TD>
<P><IMG src="122_0.gif"></TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P><H2>World Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children</H2></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><IMG src="122_1.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><H2>Care-takers</H2><BR>

<H4>Many people devote their lives to taking care of children, and it is important to recognise that such people are motivated by a deep, generous desire to make the world a better place for children to live in.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>In a way, such people are exploited too, by those who abuse the position of care-taker to gain access to children and earn their trust, setting them up for abuse and exploitation.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>At the same time,  in countries of the industrialised world in particular, there have been recent examples of men (and sometimes women) who take up employment in childrens agencies, local authority departments, organisations like scouts and guides, youth clubs and half-way houses for street kids, specifically to put them in a position where they can identify and have access to vulnerable children, gain their trust and encourage them to pose for pornographic pictures or videos, engage in sex or provide sex to others in exchange for favours.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Such people often escape detection because they are in positions of trust, and even those who may have concerns about their habits or behaviour find it difficult to believe that they might be involved in sexually exploiting children.  </H4>
<P>
<H4>Australia, even as this document is being prepared, has announced a Police Royal Commission into childrens service organisations in local government in New South Wales, following documented examples of government workers engaged in organised paedophilia, child pornography and sexual exploitation.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>In some developing countries, care-takers find their equivalents in procurers who entrap children by setting up bogus street children centres or vocational training establishments, or by organising beauty contests or charm and fashion contests.  Often children are trapped in such institutions because they are far removed from their families, in unknown areas or countries with a different language.  Even if they escape, they often face being charged with illegal immigrant status.</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H4>Ultimately all social sectors are responsible for taking care of children, and all must accept responsibility for allowing their exploitation to continue.  The vast majority of people do not exploit children, but are silently complicit.</H4>
<P>
<P>
